<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Angola ripe for an economic revolution: After the peace
deal, Julian Ozanne considers the potential of a resource-rich country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW COUNTRIES in the world have squandered their vast potential wealth as
carelessly as Angola.
Easily one of the richest five countries in sub-Saharan Africa with abundant
fertile land, huge fishing and mineral resources, extensive petroleum
deposits and tremendous energy and irrigation potential from the country's
rivers, the Angolan economy today is one of the most under-developed,
distorted and anarchic on the continent.
Sixteen years of destructive civil war and foreign invasion have left a
devastating toll. Last week's peace agreement initialled in Lisbon between
the government and Unita rebels offers hope of a substantial economic
turnaround. But even with peace and normality returning to the country the
government's economic policies will have to be substantially revised.
While many African countries woke up to the necessity of fundamental
economic adjustment by the mid-1980s, socialist Angola kept its head buried
in the sand.
Obstruction by party ideologues kept a plan for economic reform, presented
to the government in 1987, from being implemented.
Almost four years later the government announced the first minor devaluation
of the currency for 15 years from kwanza 30 to 60 to the dollar (the
parallel market rate is about kwanza 1,200 to the dollar), an insignificant
change in economic terms but an important symbol of a growing commitment to
adjustment.
'A few people in the government do now understand that there is no
alternative to sweeping economic change,' said Mr Aguinaldo Jaime, the
finance minister. 'But the fact is we have an economic system that does not
work. It is artificial and inefficient.'
The task of policy reform is formidable. Since independence in 1975 the
government has pursued a centrally-planned economy with extensive
bureaucratic controls, including administrative allocation of foreign
exchange, a fixed exchange rate, rigid price controls, rationing of consumer
goods through inadequately supplied state shops, and state control of
industry. Many prices and salaries have remained unchanged since 1975.
The results were inevitable. Industry, under poor management and critically
short of imported inputs, ground to a halt.
Angola, once a food exporter, became dependent on food imports. A huge,
bustling parallel market grew up where the dollar traded at realistic
levels, prices were set by market forces and Angolans sold off the surplus
of the few basic goods they could buy at state-run shops with a ration card.
A glimpse of how distorted the economy has become was given last October
when the government tried to mop up 95 per cent of the excessive money
supply it had printed over the years to fuel its budget deficits. Angolans
had to hand in their old kwanzas and were only given back five 'novo'
kwanzas for every hundred surrendered. The government promised the remainder
would be paid in time.
The banks took in 90bn kwanzas out of an estimated 150bn in circulation. For
a short period there was chaos and prices dropped dramatically on the
unofficial markets.
But they have increased markedly since, largely because the government was
unable to inject goods into the state-run stores to meet unfulfilled demand.
The minister of trade was sacked shortly afterwards amid allegations that
imported goods destined for state shops had been 'diverted' to the parallel
market or across the border into Zaire.
Unsustainable levels of public expenditure, with budget deficits reaching as
much as 12-15 per cent of GDP, have been possible because of Angola's
growing oil industry, which has traditionally provided about 65 per cent of
government revenues.
The oil sector, which exported 476,000 barrels a day last year, has also
kept the balance of payments afloat. With large oil earnings, Dollars 2.7bn
(Pounds 1.6bn) in 1989, Angola has generated healthy trade surpluses
throughout the 1980s.
But these have been marred by large and increasing deficits in the services
account, particularly in interest payments, transport and travel, and by a
growing debt service burden, estimated at between 45-55 per cent of exports
before debt rescheduling.
Angola's external debt is more than Dollars 7bn (about 90-95 per cent of
GDP), of which at least half is owed to the Soviet Union. In recent years
Angola has increasingly drawn on short-term commercial borrowing and has
accumulated significant payments arrears.
Resolution of the civil war will be crucial to economic revival. The war has
regularly absorbed 60 per cent of foreign exchange earnings and, according
to the United Nations, cost Angola Dollars 27-Dollars 30bn between 1980-88.
The new economic team has promised sweeping reform this year including
creeping devaluation, privatisation of many of the 400 state enterprises, an
overhaul of the banking system, and price and trade liberalisation.
However, their ability to implement the necessary measures to boost the
economy is being restricted by the reluctance of the party elite to change
during profound political change.
The few members of the ruling MPLA party who believe they have a chance of
winning the country's first free democratic elections are extremely nervous
of the impact of austerity measures and adjustment on their popularity,
especially in the urban areas.
Those in the MPLA who recognise they have no chance of electoral victory
want to keep the economic status quo because the distortions provide ample
opportunity to the party elite for substantial economic privileges.
'Economic reform is being held back by an unholy alliance of crooks and
ideologues and crooks hiding behind ideology who have vested interests in
the black market and the controlled economy,' said one western diplomat.
'Many MPLA people are grabbing as much as they can before tomorrow comes
because they know tomorrow will not belong to them.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
