<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Tudjman carries fight to UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY, East Europe Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CROATIA'S president, Mr Franjo Tudjman, last night launched a bitter attack
against the neighbouring republic of Serbia, and sections of the federal
army, accusing both of bringing Yugoslavia to the verge of disintegration
and civil war.
He also criticised western governments, in particular Britain, for
supporting what he termed, 'the Yugoslav state, which is historically
ill-conceived.'
Mr Tudjman, who made his remarks last night at the conservative Centre for
Policy Studies during a 12-hour trip to London, said Croatia would continue
to uphold its independence and would defend itself against any intervention.
'I did not call the people (of Croatia) to rise up against the army. But if
the army attacked the Croatian people, then they should defend themselves,'
Mr Tudjman explained, countering allegations that he encouraged Croats to
protect the republic against the army.
A soldier was killed in the Croatian port of Split when thousands of angry
Croat demonstrators stormed the army headquarters on Monday.
Denying that the Croats has been responsible for that incident, Mr Tudjman
said: 'They were provoked by Serbs.'
Mr Tudjman, who was sworn in as president last year following the victory of
the right-wing Croatian Democratic Union Party in free elections, singled
out Mr Blagole Adzic, the army's chief of staff, as the bete noire of
democrats.
The army, he said, was divided between those senior officers who perceived
the role of the military as the people's army of Yugoslavia, and those, like
General Adzic, who wanted to maintain 'Serbian hegemony.'
'Two-thirds of the army officers are now Serb,' said Mr Tudjman. Yet despite
his sharp criticism, he still believed 'the army will not intervene.'
However, his unremitting criticism of the Serbs - whom he described as
representing 'another world and another civilisation from the Croats' -
implied that any dialogue between Yugoslavia's two largest ethnic groups and
republics, was impossible to imagine.
Moreover, he said the division of Yugoslavia between the western, and
Catholic, republics of Slovenia and Croatia which had been ruled by the
Habsburgs, and the eastern, Orthodox and Moslem republics of Serbia,
Macedonia and Montenegro, which had been under Turkish domination,
heightened the sense of the artificiality of 'Yugoslav statehood.'
Travel advice, Page 8
Editorial comment, Page 18
</TEXT>
