<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / HDTV strategy 'still faces hurdles'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRY agreement on a European Community strategy for high-definition
television (HDTV) may be more fragile than the European Commission has
suggested, according to EC satellite operators and broadcasters.
Mr Filippo Maria Pandolfi, the technology commissioner, claimed last month
that broadcasters, satellite operators and the electronics industry had
reached 'agreement in principle' on an EC strategy.
Yesterday the five commissioners responsible for audiovisual policy debated
the framework for a consortium which would promote wide-screen HDTV services
in Europe. This consensus approach would be combined with new European
legislation which the Commission wants to put to telecommunications
ministers next month.
Although progress has been made by feuding industry factions, participants
say important hurdles remain. 'There is a reasonably high degree of optimism
that on Monday (when interest groups meet for more discussions on the issue)
we will be in a position to make some significant further progress,' said
one broadcaster yesterday. 'But it isn't correct to say that the deal is
done.'
In particular, broadcasters and satellite operators like Societe Europeenne
des Satellites, which runs the Astra satellite used by British Sky
Broadcasting, are worried that the Pal standard they use will be phased out
in favour of an intermediate HDTV standard, D2-Mac.
Satellite groups and commercial broadcasters prefer the option of
simultaneous broadcasting in Pal and D2-Mac, leading to the eventual
introduction of a full HDTV standard, known as HD-Mac.
However, electronics groups such as Thomson of France, which has invested
heavily in HDTV technology, are concerned that simultaneous broadcasting may
lead to technical problems with satellite capacity.
Last month's drafts of the framework for establishing a consortium suggested
interest groups had agreed 'the D2-Mac standard offers the best path towards
the development of HDTV with (wide-screen) D2-Mac as the main step in that
direction'.
Satellite operators fear that if they sign such an agreement, commissioners
will interpret it as a mandate to introduce compulsory D2-Mac in the draft
HDTV directive.
Attempts are being made to revive Eurosport, the satellite television sports
channel that went off the air yesterday, writes Raymond Snoddy. It collapsed
after attempts to find Pounds 60m from new investors failed before last
Friday's deadline. The Eurosport consortium brought together 17 of Europe's
public service broadcasters.
Mr Alan Hart, Eurosport chairman, said yesterday that there was still a
consortium 'and we will do all we can to keep the concept alive'.
</TEXT>
