<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Azerbaijan accuses Armenia of waging war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Soviet republic of Azerbaijan yesterday accused Armenian nationalists of
'waging an undeclared war' and said guerrillas had killed 65 Azerbaijanis
before a Soviet army clampdown last week.
In a statement carried by the official news agency Tass, the Azerbaijani
Foreign Ministry warned Armenia's leadership that it would have to carry
'full responsibility' for any further aggression.
The statement, which came a day after Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev
defended the use of troops against Armenian villages inside Azerbaijan,
continued: 'Further hostilities against Azerbaijan will produce a
catastrophe.'
It stated that between April 28 and May 3, Armenian guerrillas had shelled
or opened fire on more than 30 Azerbaijani villages and the towns of Shusha
and Kazakh.
Armenia, meanwhile, yesterday accused President Gorbachev and the Kremlin of
unleashing a campaign of state terrorism to topple the republic's elected
nationalist government.
Mr Levon Ter-Petrosyan, Armenian president, said military operations,
including attacks by helicopters and armoured vehicles, were continuing
against isolated Armenian villages. He said dozens had been killed.
Police from Azerbaijan were also taking part in the attacks, he said.
The Soviet leadership blames armed Armenian nationalist groups for the
violence and insist they be disarmed.
Mr Ter-Petrosyan quoted witness who were reported as saying that combined
Soviet and Azerbaijani forces had committed atrocities against Armenians in
the border region, including the shooting of prisoners and the scalping of
dead bodies.
The allegations were impossible to corroborate from independent sources.
'President Gorbachev says these actions are only intended to neutralise
armed (Armenian) groups. But he has another goal,' a subdued Mr
Ter-Petrosyan told a news conference.
Mr Gorbachev wanted 'to terrorise the Armenian people and overthrow the
legally-elected powers in Armenia.'
</TEXT>
