<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Gonzalez warns UK of shadow cast by Gibraltar impasse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A 'desirable easy relationship' between Britain and Spain will be difficult
to establish as long as the Gibraltar problem remains unsolved, Mr Felipe
Gonzalez, the Spanish prime minister, warned last night in London.
The premier said at a dinner in his honour at No 10 Downing Street that
'bilateral, as well as Community and multilateral relations are affected by
this problem, a hold-over from history'.
Mr Gonzalez recognised that the opinion of Gibraltarians had to be
considered in any solution but he appealed to the British government not to
take only their wishes into account.
'Perhaps it is up to the UK, in view of its special relationship with its
colony, to make an effort of imagination. We are willing, as always, to help
in this task,' he said.
Mr John Major, the British prime minister, and Mr Gonzalez, who is paying
the first official visit to Britain by a Spanish premier since General
Franco died in 1975, had earlier held talks on mainly European Community
problems.
Their talks were described by Mr Major as 'very friendly and constructive'.
They had discussed at some length the proposal for European economic and
monetary union: the British and Spanish proposals for a hard Ecu, or a
hardening of the Ecu basket, were similar, Mr Major said.
'We have neither of us given specific support to the other's proposal, but
we are very close on the principles of how we must go ahead on economic and
monetary union (Emu).'
In his speech at No 10, Mr Gonzalez underlined the need for careful planning
of Emu and warned against pushing ahead too fast, which would 'endanger the
final result'. He also stressed that economic and monetary union must be
complemented by a common foreign and security policy.
David Gardner adds from Brussels: Spain's call for an equalising budgetary
fund to redistribute wealth towards the EC's four poorest members could lead
to failure of the current negotiations on economic, monetary and political
union.
This was the clear message from five of Madrid's partners at this week's
meeting of the intergovernmental conference on political union.
Delegates from the Netherlands, the UK, France, Germany and Denmark told
their Spanish colleagues that if they made their support for EMU and
political union conditional on more cash to help the poorest nations catch
up, then the negotiations on treaty changes would founder.
Unanimous agreement is required for such changes.
</TEXT>
