<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Elf and Enterprise may bid for Occidental's UK assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELF AQUITAINE, the French oil and chemicals group, and Enterprise Oil, the
British independent exploration and production company, are expected to
announce a joint venture agreement today to buy the North Sea assets of
Occidental Petroleum, the US oil company, for some Dollars 1.4bn (Pounds
813m).
The expected deal is believed to make provision for Enterprise to acquire
the 25 per cent of its shares owned by Elf - possibly by swapping some of
its existing assets for the shares.
Elf has been widely rumoured for several weeks to be close to securing the
purchase of Occidental's assets in an auction where it has been competing
against Enterprise and Arco, the US oil operator.
The co-operation of Elf and Enterprise in a bid is likely to make the deal
more palatable to Mr Peter Lilley, the UK industry secretary, who referred
Elf's last British acquisition to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
because of the French government's 55.6 per cent stake in the company.
The commission cleared Elf's purchase of Amoco's UK petrol stations last
week.
Occidental's North Sea business includes operating the Piper field where 167
men were killed in an explosion on the Piper Alpha oil rig three years ago.
The majority ownership of this field could prove a sensitive political issue
which Enterprise's involvement could help to diffuse.
Occidental has spent some Pounds 550m re-developing the Piper Alpha
platform, but no longer regards its North Sea business as a core operation.
It has been trying to sell the UK assets in an attempt to reduce debt in the
US parent.
The Occidental assets cover a broad spread of business in the North Sea
which would fit well with both Elf and Enterprise's acquisitive strategies.
Enterprise needs experience in operating a UK field to aid its overseas
expansion and prepare it to take over the running of its Nelson field when
that comes on stream later this decade. Enterprise also needs cash flow to
develop the Nelson field, of which it owns 60 per cent and which is expected
to cost Pounds 1.25bn over the next five years.
An asset swap - could improve the independent company's cash position, but
only if it can be done in a way that will avoid a large Advanced Corporation
Tax liability.
Some analysts are speculating that Enterprise will make a rights issue to
help fund the asset purchase.
None of the companies involved would comment.
</TEXT>
