<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE futures led the share market higher as a squeeze built up in the
derivative markets. Otherwise it was a painfully slow day's trading with a
lack of institutional and retail interest.
The June FT-SE 100 index moved to a premium to the spot index of 27 points
at one stage as futures traders attempted to cover short positions built up
the previous week.
With fair value (the futures markets' theoretical premium) at just 15
points, there was a small amount of arbitraging between the futures and cash
markets. This pushed the stock market higher, although towards the close
another squeeze developed with June moving briskly ahead.
June FT-SE closed up 28 points at 2,566, while its premium stood at 29
against 15 at the previous close. The doubling in the futures' premium is a
sign of the market's belief that the immediate outlook for shares is
positive.
While the lack of institutional interest continues to cast doubt on how
soundly based another rally would be, the prospect of further cuts in
interest rates has encouraged the bulls.
Turnover in Allied-Lyons traded options was boosted by continuing bid
speculation, with call buyers in evidence. Total options turnover was
slightly higher at 18,831.
</TEXT>
