<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Setting out to build a republic
on bananas - Tim Coone describes Nicaragua's transforming interest in
plantations and investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DURING the late 1980s, when the left-wing Sandinista party's grip on power
in Nicaragua began to slip, one of the country's several conservative
parties sponsored a billboard in the capital, announcing that 'Nicaragua
will once again become a republic'. Some comic immediately painted in
'banana' before the word republic.
The anonymous graffiti writer may soon be proved correct, although the new
republic will not be one of bemedalled generals in dark glasses, being
financed by shady, foreign 'banana company men'.
The government of President Violeta Barrios de Chamorro this month passed a
new decree which will allow the return of foreign investors in the banana
business after a decade of absence from Nicaragua. New investors, as well as
the traditional banana transnationals such as Standard Fruit and United
Brands, are being invited to establish plantations.
The private Nicaraguan growers see in the decree an ideal opportunity to
transform Nicaragua's poor export performance, and in the process to make an
almost infallible investment in what has become a booming world banana
market.
Mr Ramiro Gurdian, a plantation owner and president of the farmer's
association Upanic, said that 'it is one of the agro-export sectors which
gives the quickest return on investment and shows a rapid result on the
balance of payments'. Banana plantations, once sown, produce their first
harvest within a year.
Nicaragua stopped being a major banana producer when Panama disease wiped
out the country's principal plantations on the Caribbean coast in the 1930s.
The US transnational Standard Fruit Company had purchasing contracts on the
Pacific coast with local growers such as Mr Gurdian until the 1979
revolution. From there, they supplied the US West Coast market. As Mr
Gurdian pointed out, Nicaragua is the closest point in Latin America to the
US West Coast, which has the appropriate soils and climate for banana
production.
The Sandinistas and Standard Fruit quickly fell out. Unions were legalised.
The banana export trade was nationalised and placed in the hands of the
state-run company Embanic. A decree was issued by former President Daniel
Ortega, giving Embanic a monopoly on any future banana production for
export.
A price war began in the California market to try to exclude Nicaraguan
produce. A 1985 US trade embargo then halted exports altogether.
Embanic successfully redirected fruit to the European market, although
higher transport costs cut deeply into its profits.
The growers and Embanic survived, and Nicaraguan exports are expected to
reach 6-7m boxes this year, once again returning to the levels of the
mid-70s.
Mr Gurdian is confident of further expansion as a result of the new decree.
A new foreign investment law, permitting the unrestricted repatriation of
profits generated from export earnings, has been passed. Mr Gurdian said:
'We are looking ahead to the creation of the unified market in Europe in
1993'. The market in Eastern Europe has also provided new opportunities.
Nicaraguan produce is already going to Poland, through Embanic's independent
intermediaries in Belgium.
Mr Gurdian is doubling his plantations from 120 to 240 hectares this year.
He said that he and the 15 other private growers in Nicaragua 'don't mind
the transnationals coming back. We welcome their presence'. It is unlikely
that he will be selling to them in the future.
He explained that Nicaraguan farmers, with the Colombian private growers'
association Proban, are sending a weekly shipment to Belgium through their
own outlets inedependently of the large transnationals. Five reefer vessels
are chartered.
In 1975, the price paid by Standard Fruit to local growers was only
USDollars 0.75 per 40lb box. Last year, Nicaraguan growers were selling
their produce at an average of USDollars 11 per box, cif in Belgium through
Embanic. Even accounting for insurance and freight in the latter figure,
returns to growers are some ten times higher than 15 years ago.
Mr Gurdian said that the US companies will be looking primarily to supply
the US West Coast market again. 'We don't want to enter into battle with
them' he said.
Only 2,600 hectares are presently planted to bananas in Nicaragua, an area
10-20 per cent of neighbouring Costa Rica or Honduras.
At some USDollars 15,000 per hectare to establish a plantation on the
Pacific coast, banana production is capital intensive.
Nicaragua's remote and poverty-stricken Caribbean coast, offering a shorter
route to the European market, would be even more expensive. This route would
require finance on a scale which only large foreign companies or banks could
muster.
It is thus a born-again 'banana republic' that is sprouting new roots in
Nicaragua. It is one without thumbscrews or wheezy military bands, but one
with new laws and ethics, attuned to the restructuring of the world's banana
trade and the new democratic thinking in Latin America.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32 Map (Omitted).
