<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Business and the Environment: The danger of being left out -
Judy Dempsey and Ariane Genillard continue an occasional series on cleaning
up eastern Europe by examining Bulgaria's obstacles to change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
On a cool February day in 1989 Grisha Filipov, former communist prime
minister of Bulgaria, stood on the balcony of the local communist party
headquarters in Ruse.
Once a thriving merchant centre under the Habsburgs but now a shabby and
delapidated city, Ruse is built on the river Danube and divides Bulgaria
from Romania.
Filipov, in his customary, condescending fashion, waved to the crowds. He
tried to reassure them that the chlorine fumes wafting across the Danube
from a chemical factory in the Romanian town of Giurgiu were harmless. The
crowds were too cynical to believe anything told them by this veteran party
apparatchik.
That day, mothers and their children placed scarves and handkerchiefs over
their faces, not as a sign of defiance to Filipov but to demonstrate the
need to protect themselves from the contaminated air which they breathed.*
For several years, the local population had been subjected to these fumes.
Studies show that over the past 15 years the incidence of lung disease has
increased sharply.
Ruse's inhabitants seemed powerless to do anything, until the arrival in
1989 of the national Independent Committee for the Protection of the
Environment, also known as the Ruse Committee. It joined forces with
Eco-Glasnost, Bulgaria's first national independent environmental movement,
which quickly galvanised public opinion behind it.
The Ruse Committee and Eco-Glasnost formed the beginnings of the country's
first green movement. They soon became a powerful force in Bulgarian
politics. By daring to challenge the monopoly of power held by the ruling
communists, the green movement attracted a broad range of support, and with
it experts who accumulated statistics, carried out studies and placed the
environment high on the country's political agenda.
The facts drawn together by independent experts make grim reading.
Environment minister Dimitar Vodenicharov, who assumed office in January,
says energy generation is the greatest polluter.
Bulgaria's industry is energy-intensive - it relies on brown coal;
Vodenicharov says: 'Between 800,000 and 900,000 tonnes of sulphur dioxide
are emitted each year.'
Other industrial activities produce 250,000 tonnes of nitrogen oxide a year
which seep into underground water supplies. Recent reports drawn up by
Eco-Glasnost estimates that about 70 per cent of the country's water is
contaminated.
The catalogue of woes appears unremitting. Some 4.7m hectares of arable
land, or about 44 per cent of the country's territory has been eroded,
polluted, or destroyed because 68m tonnes of dust and toxic gases are
emitted each year.
The coalition government is realising that it will take years - and
considerable sums of money - to tackle the environment, as a recent incident
at the Srednogorie copper factory confirmed. On April 19, 300 tonnes of
sulphuric acid leaked from the factory into the ground. The surrounding
agricultural regions were contaminated and use of the local water supply was
forbidden.
The point about this incident is that the government had temporarily closed
down the factory last year following local protests. But because the factory
was interconnected with so many other enterprises - it supplies 20 of them
with important industrial metals - and because it employs more than 2,000
workers, the authorities were forced to re-open it.
All the other countries of eastern Europe share a similar, if not worse,
fate than Bulgaria. But Bulgaria's large agrarian base tends to act as a
counter-weight to the large-scale programmes of industrialisation undertaken
in the other countries.
That should make the Bulgarian government's task somewhat easier but
officials in Sofia think differently. What concerns them is that this small
Balkan country of 8.9m people will not be able to compete for the interest
already being shown by western governments and investors in Poland, Hungary
and Czechoslovakia.
The response by western consultancy firms advising western governments and
industry about the costs and challenges of cleaning up the environment in
eastern Europe has justified the officials' fears.
'No, we are not yet thinking about working in Bulgaria. It's not high up on
our agenda. We have to obtain a clearer picture,' said one consultant.
The task of collating the data is now being undertaken by the European
Community's Phare programme. In December 1990 it allocated Ecu 3.5m (Pounds
2.4m) to monitor air pollution. Vodenicharov says Phare has already
earmarked Ecu 15m to be spread over two years - from 1990 until the end of
1991 - for the development of a data-gathering agency.
The World Bank, which has already granted Poland an Dollars 18m loan to
strengthen environmental management and provide technical assistance, has
not yet earmarked any finance or credits for Bulgaria's environmental
problems.
'We are sending missions to Bulgaria regularly to gather data. It is too
early to say what kind of programme will emerge from this,' commented a
World Bank official.
The World Bank's recommendations towards cleaning up the environment in
eastern Europe tend initially to focus on the need to reduce the use of
energy.
In a recent study** the World Bank suggested that 'these governments (of
eastern Europe) need to take an active role in promoting environmental
clean-up through altered economic incentives and new public investments'.
It proposed that 'on the incentive side, raising energy prices and imposing
(and rigorously enforcing) reasonable fees and fines on polluters are two
important steps that can be taken early. On the investment side, the needs
are enormous, far beyond the financial resources likely to be available.
'One obvious need is for investment to switch away from coal and towards
natural gas as a major energy source, accompanied by investments to clean up
existing coal-burning facilities and improve the safety of nuclear plans or
in some cases, decommission them . . . '
The Bulgarian government has already embarked on the first phase of economic
reforms, which include the liberalisation of prices, the reduction of the
budget deficit, higher interest rates, a squeeze on consumer spending and
higher energy prices.
Despite these efforts, Vodenicharov believes Bulgaria will remain low on the
economic agenda of western countries. And because Bulgaria is far away from
central Europe, he believes that unless his country makes the effort to lock
into Europe as quickly as possible in order to attract investments for
tackling the environment, cleaning up the country will take a long time.
'Our standards must be European,' explains Vodenicharov, who is clearly
exhausted with trying to keep the environment high on the agenda at a time
when the coffers are empty. He believes, for instance, that closer
co-operation with the Budapest-based Regional Environmental Centre, which
was set up last September, will provide some assistance. He says the centre,
financed by a US grant of Dollars 5m and matched by a Phare grant, will help
to co-ordinate environmental issues throughout the region.
But when asked what the Bulgarian government is doing to address some of the
damage, Vodenicharov shrugs his shoulders.
The bitter in-fighting among the Union of Democratic Forces (UDF), a loose
coalition of 19 political movements, to which Eco-Glasnost and the Green
Party belong, and between the UDF and the parliamentary majority held by the
Socialist (former communist) Party, means that every issue is politicised.
Vodenicharov says the government, wrestling to reduce the budget deficit
from 11 per cent of GDP in 1990 to 3.5 per cent of GDP in 1991, is in no
position to place the environment high on its economic agenda. 'Everybody is
in one way or other in favour of improving the environment, but my biggest
enemy is the empty pocket.'
* Eastern Europe: Environmental Briefing. January 1990. Issued by
Environmental Resources Limited, 106 Gloucester Place, London W1H 3DB.
** World Bank. The Transformation of Economies in central and eastern
Europe: Issues, Progress, and Prospects. Socialist Economics Unit. Country
Economics Department. April 3, 1991.
The opening article in the series appeared on February 27.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
