<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Business and the Environment: Wildlife seal of approval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ENRIQUE TESSIERI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Saimaa ringed seal is the most endangered animal in Finland. But a
campaign launched in 1979 - and relaunched last November - by the Worldwide
Fund for Nature (WWF) and the University of Joensuu in eastern Finland has
saved the Saimaa seal from extinction.
The Saimaa seal campaign generates funds in a variety of ways: through the
sale of its own products such as bird houses or clothes with the WWF panda
emblem, and by sponsoring schemes whereby companies pay for the right to use
the official WWF emblem in their advertisements.
'The campaign has been successful. In 1976 there were only 100 seals left
and we have been able to increase the number to 160,' said Mauri Rautkari,
secretary general of the Finnish branch of the WWF.
The new campaign takes the scheme further. For a sum of FM25,000 (Pounds
3,600 )a year a company can symbolically adopt a seal and for FM50,000 rent
a rock where the seal rests. A whole island where the seal breeds can also
be rented by a sponsor for FM200,000.
According to the WWF, 19 Finnish companies are taking part in the recent
campaign. Only one company - Tuko, a wholesale-retail chain - has so far
rented an island while the majority of companies prefer to adopt a seal.
As well as gaining publicity for being a sponsor, a company will receive a
serialised lithograph by a well-known Finnish painter for its contribution.
The size of the lithograph varies with respect to the size of the
contribution.
'There has not been much interest from the large forest companies which have
paper and pulp mills on the lake shores and the power companies which run
hydro-electric plants. They know that the damage they inflict on the Saimaa
seal is much greater than FM200,000,' said Rautkari.
Pollution, power companies and navigation authorities cause the water levels
of the lake to fluctuate. These variations can cause the collapse of the ice
and seal lairs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 31
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1148</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEHBSACPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Business and the Environment: Shell chairman to lead green
group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When a Shell refinery near Liverpool spilled 150 tonnes of oil into the
River Mersey two years ago, John Collins, then a director of the company,
took it personally. Shell was fined Pounds 1m - the highest pollution fine
ever levied in the UK.
Collins, now chairman of Shell UK, was chosen recently by Michael Heseltine,
secretary of state for the environment, to lead a committee of top
businessmen which will be advising the government on issues affecting
business and the environment. Heseltine said last night in a speech to the
Royal Society of Arts that he hoped the committee would be able to offer
clear advice on achieving international environmental goals.
As head of a group of business leaders who have been selected for their
interest and commitment to the environment, Collins is conscious that Shell
must improve its own record. 'Our risk as a polluter is high . . . Shell
cannot give any guarantees, but we are willing to meet certain standards. I
don't pretend that we're starting as a leader, we are all in a pioneering
role on this committee.'
When David Gee, director of Friends of the Earth, heard of Collins's
appointment, he said: 'Anyone from Shell certainly knows about pollution and
the government needs all the advice it can get.'
Collins is keen that the committee not be dismissed as yet another talking
shop. On his agenda are issues such as environmental management, recycling
and global warming. He wants to move quickly in setting goals to be achieved
in the committee's two-year life.
'There is no doubt that countries like Holland and Germany are a step ahead
of us, because of their determination to remain competitive in export
markets. But UK industry has woken up to the environment and is starting to
see it as a business opportunity.'
The learning curve is long, however. Industry typically takes an initial
look at environmental measures and is put off by the cost. Then it starts to
realise its competitors overseas are taking environmental initiatives and
begins to see that there would be a business opportunity in implementing
them. It is Collins's brief to try and turn some of this thinking into
concrete action.
Since the committee will advise and be consulted by Heseltine and Peter
Lilley, secretary of state for trade and industry, it can push for
government legislation as well as fiscal incentives. 'But I am hoping we can
get industry to deliver some of these things on its own. We will have to
move at a faster pace to be alongside the Netherlands and Germany in two
years, but if we don't do this we will be at a competitive disadvantage.'
Environmental management is one of his top priorities and he believes the
committee should draw up guidelines and help companies do an environmental
audit. In addition, he wants the body to look closely at recycling where one
company's waste product could be another firm's raw material.
The committee runs the gamut of UK industry including IBM, ICI, British Gas,
British Nuclear Fuels, Wessex Water, National Westminster Bank and
environmental consultants in a mix that is likely to provoke lively and
tough debate.
An important challenge for the group will be to restore the public's
confidence in industry's environmental record, particularly sectors that are
perceived as polluters such as the oil and nuclear industries. The US has
introduced comprehensive right-to-know laws which require companies to
publish regularly the levels of emissions they make, and environmental
groups have been pushing for the same standards in the UK.
Collins supports the public's right to this sort of information. 'The key to
succeeding in this is transparency and if we measure our emissions it can
make us more objective on what to do about them.'
He is optimistic that at the end of the committee's two-year life industry
will have met many of its environmental objectives and be clear about its
future aims. 'In the end, any body like this will be judged on what it does,
and we are looking for bold action, not rhetoric,' said Gee.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 31
</PAGE>
