FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: Aker to acquire marine
engineering company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORWAY'S Aker group yesterday announced it is to acquire Houston-based Omega
Marine engineering company in a move which forms a central plank in its
international expansion strategy.
Omega Marine had 150 employees and a revenue of Dollars 17m in 1990, while
last year Aker recorded profits of NKr632m (Dollars 93m) on turnover of
NKr13.41bn. The new company is to be called Aker Omega Marine.
Omega has been involved in several important engineering projects for the
Gulf of Mexico market and engineered the Joliett tension leg platform (tlp)
which has evolved into cost-efficient floating production technology for the
development of oil and gas fields.
Aker is best known for its giant gravity base offshore platforms, of which
it has built 13 for the North Sea and has three under construction.
Mr Gregers Kure, president of Aker Oil and Gas Technology, said the
acquisition gives his company a strong foothold in the Gulf of Mexico
market, where he estimates investment in tlps may reach Dollars 2bn annually
by 1994.
Aker and Omega have recently completed preliminary studies on tlps for
US-based Mobil Research and Development Company, Shell, Exxon and Amoco.
Omega Marine is currently owned by key employees and will continue to
operate under Mr Kenneth Caldwell, its president.
