<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: CRA hit by continued low prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK WESTFIELD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CRA, the Australian resources group, will see earnings fall by between 20
and 25 per cent this year because of continued softness in commodity prices,
Mr Don Uhrig, chairman, told the annual meeting yesterday.
Mr Uhrig said profit before extraordinary items for the first three months
of the year was about 13 per cent lower than for the corresponding period in
1990. This follows a 27 per cent fall in net profit last year, from the
Dollars A648.4m in 1989 to Dollars A472.5m (USDollars 367.4m) in 1990.
'Until the US economy rebounds, it seems probable that commodity demand will
continue to soften and prices decline,' commented Mr Uhrig. But he added
that the exception was iron ore, mainly because of continued strong demand
by the Japanese steel mills.
CRA is one of Australia's top two producers of iron ore, coal and aluminium,
owns in a joint venture with North Broken Hill the large Pasminco base
metals group, and is the controlling shareholder in Australia's largest
diamond mine at Argyle, in Western Australia.
Mr Uhrig confirmed an earlier report that CRA wanted to re-open the copper
mine on the strife-torn island of Bougainville, which is occupied by
secessionist guerrillas. He hinted, however, that CRA would consider selling
its holding if this would help bring about a return to stability on the
island.
'Expectation is that CRA will retain its (53 per cent) shareholding in
Bougainville and re-start the mine in due course,' Mr Uhrig told
shareholders.
'However, we recognise that Bougainville Copper cannot resume operations
unless there is a political settlement. It does not appear such a settlement
is imminent, although some progress appears possible.
'Should it become obvious that CRA's continued participation in Bougainville
Copper prevents the attainment of such a political accommodation, then the
company would have to consider the disposal of its investment in the mine,'
he said.
CRA had withdrawn all its staff from the island in March, 1990, and,
therefore, it was not possible to assess accurately the condition of the
mine, one of the world's largest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
