<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: Bayer pre-tax profits decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LEVERKUSEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BAYER, the least recession-prone of the three German chemical giants,
yesterday reported a 5 per cent fall in pre-tax profits to DM880m (Dollars
517.6m) for the first quarter of 1991.
Turnover fell by 2 per cent, although Polysar, the Canadian rubber company
which Bayer bought for Dollars 1bn last year, was included in the group
figures for the first time.
Bayer is partially protected from the recession by its large and highly
profitable pharmaceuticals business, which increased turnover by 8 per cent.
'Our performance was still hampered by the recession in the US and UK and by
the economic slowdown in Europe, which is gaining momentum,' said Mr Hermann
Strenger, Bayer chairman.
Apart from health care, all parts of Bayer suffered from the slow-down in
business. Industrial products were worst hit, with a 14 per cent fall in
sales (Bayer does not break down quarterly profits by sector).
Looking forward to the rest of the year, Mr Strenger said: 'There are some
positive factors that give us confidence and encouragement, even though the
economic climate has worsened.'
Bayer would benefit from the strengthening of the US dollar against the
D-Mark during April and from the low prices of petro-chemical raw materials,
he said. Profits for the whole year might be close to the 1990 level of
DM3.4bn, if the dollar did not weaken again.
Mr Strenger took the occasion of Bayer's financial press conference
yesterday to issue his strongest warning so far against 'the avalanche of
costs bearing down on us' as a result of recent and proposed environmental
legislation in Germany.
</TEXT>
