<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / International Company News: Government steps into VEV rescue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government is trying to prevent the country's biggest company
failure in a decade by stepping in to oversee rescue negotiations between
VEV, the struggling textiles group, and its bankers.
VEV, which employs some 11,000 people in its clothing and textile
businesses, has been placed under the supervision of the Interministerial
Committee for Industrial Reconstruction (CIRI), a unit of the Finance
Ministry.
Despite selling some of its most valuable assets, the group still has debts
estimated at nearly FFr2.5bn (Dollars 410m).
Credit Lyonnais and Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP), the two leading
state-owned banks, are understood to be the most heavily exposed lenders.
Credit Commercial de France (CCF) is involved mostly in VEV's capital, with
a smaller loan exposure.
VEV, whose shares were suspended on the stock exchange a week ago, said
yesterday that it was delaying publishing its 1990 results, which are
expected to show a sizeable loss, until next Monday.
In 1989, with its financial debt totalling FFr3.3bn, VEV reported net losses
of FFr188m. French press reports have suggested 1990's losses could exceed
FFr500m.
VEV's debt service is currently estimated to eat up 8 to 9 per cent of its
sales - FFr6.4bn in 1989 - and government officials believe it will need to
reduce this to 3 per cent in order to survive.
Since many of the most profitable assets have already been sold off, meeting
this target is expected to involve the write-off of a considerable portion
of VEV's outstanding bank debts.
Most French banks last year increased their provisions for bad debts
substantially to cover an increase in the number of corporate defaults, but
banking analysts believe most banks have not made provision for their VEV
debts.
</TEXT>
