</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE takeover bid by Galeries Lafayette, the French department store group,
for its competitor, Nouvelles Galeries, will receive no opposition from
Nouvelles Galeries' main shareholder.
Devanlay, the family-controlled textiles group, which holds 47.5 per cent of
Nouvelles Galeries' voting rights, announced it will not contest Galeries
Lafayette's offer, valuing the group at FFr5.4bn (Dollars 9.15m).
Ironically, Galeries Lafayette did not at first intend to make a bid for
Nouvelles Galeries. But, it was forced to do so by the French stock exchange
council after it bought a block of Nouvelles Galeries shares from another
investor.
This lifted Galeries Lafayette's stake to 39 per cent, well above the 33 per
cent threshold at which French takeover law normally obliges a buyer to make
an offer for two-thirds of the company.
