<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Accounting proposals under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW accounting proposals issued last month by the Accounting Standards Board
could discourage productivity growth in the UK company sector, according to
Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank.
The ASB's proposals envisage a radical overhaul of UK company profit and
loss accounts, including the virtual abolition of the distinction between
extraordinary and exceptional items.
Goldman argues that companies will be discouraged from undertaking necessary
restructuring of their businesses. Under the ASB's proposals, all costs will
have to be taken 'above the line' and earnings per share, and share prices,
will suffer as a result.
According to Dr Sushil Wadwhani, an analyst at Goldman, the companies most
likely to be affected are those that regularly report extraordinary charges
 -costs taken below the line.
In this category are: Lucas Industries, Trafalgar House, Simon Engineering,
Fenner, Portals Holdings, GKN, Macarthy, Molins, Grampian Holdings, Howden
Group, Bunzl, Costain, Fisons and Pilkington, all of which have reported net
extraordinary items in at least four of the last five years.
Dr Wadwhani says that the stock market is fixated on reported earnings per
share. Although the economic reality is the same however the restructuring
is accounted for, Dr Wadwhani argues that the cosmetic change will affect
investors' attitudes to companies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1176</DOCNO>
