<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / UK Company News: No change of control for Mt Charlotte
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID CHURCHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRIERLEY Investments, the New Zealand investment group, confirmed yesterday
that it had no plans to sell its majority stake in Mount Charlotte
Investments, the UK's second largest hotel group with properties ranging
from the Royal Horseguards hotel to the Selfridge hotel, writes David
Churchill.
Mr Jeremy Kemsley-Pein, a director of BIL in London, said yesterday that BIL
was 'absolutely committed' to ownership of Mount Charlotte.
He acknowledged, however, that BIL might sell further shares in the hotel
chain while retaining a 51 per cent majority stake.
'We have had a number of approaches from investors in Mount Charlotte and it
is something we are looking at,' he said.
Mr Kemsley-Pein's confirmation of BIL's continuing control of Mount
Charlotte follows Monday's sale of 30 per cent of its stake in the hotel
group to the overseas investment arm of the Singapore government for Pounds
227.5m.
The deal had been on the cards for some time, partly to reduce BIL's debt
levels, but also because BIL did not want to retain 100 per cent control of
the hotel group.
After holding a stake of just under 30 per cent in Mount Charlotte for some
years, it was forced to launch a full-scale bid last September when it
acquired a 10 per cent block of Mount Charlotte shares for 73p per share
from the Kuwaiti Investment Office.
The success of BIL's opportunistic bid surprised the City, but some
institutional investors evidently had decided that the recession and
worsening Gulf Crisis meant they should pull out of hotel stocks.
The acquisition price of 73p a share was considerably less than the 85p a
share deal struck with the Singapore government.
City analysts last night suggested that the share price premium reflected a
major coup for BIL as it came after the worst trading period for hotels.
Speculation now centred on what deal BIL might do next.
'There is nothing in the pipeline at the moment,' said Mr Kemsley-Pein. 'But
we are constantly looking for opportunities.' He confirmed that these
opportunities might come from Australia.
Mr Robert Peel, chief executive of Mount Charlotte, said yesterday that the
share sale had been anticipated and was a welcome move. 'It means that there
will be a secure base for our further development over the next few years,'
he said.
But Mr Peel acknowledged that the sale had come after 'some very tough
trading in the past few months' and a slow recovery in tourists and business
travellers.
Mount Charlotte has been particularly hit by the downturn in travel to
London, since it is the largest hotel chain in the capital.
In Singapore yesterday the deal was seen as a long-term strategic move. Mr
Ng Kok-Song, deputy managing director of the Singapore Government Investment
Corporation (GIC), described Mount Charlotte as a well-managed company with
a portfolio of well-located hotels in London. This was seen as a growth
tourist and commercial destination, he added.
</TEXT>
