FT  08 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Saatchi price steady on stake sale - Rights
issue supporter reduces holding by 75m shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAATCHI &amp; SAATCHI, the advertising group, yesterday saw its shares slip by
just  1/2 p to 19 3/4 p when St James Place Capital, one of Lord
Rothschild's funds, sold 75m shares to UBS Philips &amp; Drew, the securities
house.
P&amp;D then placed almost all the shares at 19 1/4 p. The placing is said to
have been over-subscribed.
After the disposal St James now holds 61m Saatchi shares, or 4 per cent of
the overall equity, worth Pounds 12m on Saatchi's current market
capitalisation of Pounds 304m. Other funds linked to Lord (Jacob) Rothschild
are believed to hold additional stock.
St James was involved last month in underwriting a Pounds 55m rights issue
for 10p a share as part of Saatchi's recently completed emergency
recapitalisation.
Before the recapitalisation St James Place was the largest holder of
Saatchi's Europreference shares. Under the terms of the recapitalisation
those shares were exchanged for 86m ordinary shares. It then acquired an
additional 50m shares as a result of the rights issue.
Although St James made a profit from yesterday's transaction on its rights
issue investment, it is believed to be still showing a loss on its original
investment, estimated at about Pounds 35m, in the Europreference issue.
St James said that it had sold the shares to ensure that Saatchi, which is
its biggest single investment, accounted for no more than 5 per cent of its
assets. This was the proportion of assets Saatchi represented after the
original purchase of Europreference shares.
Yesterday's placing came only two weeks after a group of its US investors
sold 53m shares. These investors, which included ESL Partners, a
Dallas-based finance house, and Mr Lawrence Tisch, the New York businessman,
were also involved in underwriting the rights issue.
St James and ESL Partners, which is also still a substantial Saatchi
shareholder with 53m shares, have both been invited to appoint non-executive
directors to the Saatchi board.
</TEXT>
