<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Auditors forced to resign over TGI row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TGI, the audio and electronic products group, has appointed KPMG Peat
Marwick McLintock as auditors following the resignation last month of
Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte.
The dispute which led to the resignation centres on profit figures reported
by Tannoy Audix, a company bought by TGI on earnout terms in February 1989.
Reported 1990 pre-tax profits for Audix were Pounds 1.1m but TGI said in a
statement yesterday said that the board was now of the opinion that Audix
did not make a profit at all in 1990, following an investigation into the
company by Peat Marwick.
TGI said it stood to suffer a potential loss because these accounts, audited
by Coopers &amp; Lybrand, formed the basis of payments due to the vendors of
Audix under the earnout agreement.
TGI issued loan notes to the vendors amounting to Pounds 1m before it
investigated the Audix accounts, but it has yet to pay any cash to vendors.
Mr Norman Crocker, TGI chairman, said yesterday that a precise
quantification of the potential loss would become clear as the 1991 audit
got under way.
In the meantime, he said the company had taken the following action:
sought, and obtained the resignation of Coopers as auditors, following legal
advice to the TGI board to the effect that Coopers are likely to have been
in breach of contract and/or to have been negligent. Coopers denied these
allegations;
dismissed Mr John Billett, one of the vendors, as executive chairman of
Audix. 'The board considers that (Mr Billett) may bear some responsibility
as to certain matters at Audix', yesterday's statement said. Mr Crocker
refused to elaborate on this;
TGI proposes to resist making any payment of the contingent consideration
under the loan notes.
Coopers has written a letter denying the allegation of negligence which is
to be circulated to TGI shareholders.
</TEXT>
