FT  08 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Bank of Ireland First Holdings shows loss
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank of Ireland First Holdings, the holding company for the Bank of
Ireland's US subsidiary First NH Banks, reported a loss before tax for the
quarter to March 31 1991 of IRPounds 12.1m (Pounds 10.93m).
This follows a loss of IRPounds 19m in the preceding quarter, and of
IRPounds 3.3m in the first quarter of 1990, a record which prompted the
resignation of Mr Mark Hely-Hutchinson, the Bank of Ireland's chief
executive, last year.
However, progress has been made in reducing operating costs, which, at
Pounds 15.9m against Pounds 16.6m, were 4 per cent down on the same period
last year.
But loan loss provisions remain 'unacceptably high', and income continues to
be adversely affected by a high level of non-performing assets. The capital
position of First NH Banks was strengthened during the quarter by an
investment of Dollars 25m (Pounds 14.57m) in equity from the group.
