<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Hong Kong group declares 43% stake in Dutch trader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL and JOHN ELLIOTT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM, HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIRST PACIFIC, the Hong Kong investment group, has built up a 43.2 per cent
stake in Internatio-Muller, the Rotterdam-based trading and technical group,
prompting the Dutch company to erect anti-takeover defences.
The Hong Kong group yesterday proposed that Internatio merge with Hagemeyer,
First Pacific's 69 per cent owned Dutch-based trading house. The deal would
create an international group with annual sales of more than Fl 5.5bn
(Pounds 2.8bn).
Trading in all three companies' shares was suspended yesterday in Amsterdam
and is due to resume today.
First Pacific said it would pursue the merger only if the proposal won the
full support of Internatio's board.
Internatio rejected a merger but agreed to investigate the proposal.
However, it also made an immediate issue of 5.59m preference shares to a
friendly company foundation, a common takeover defence in the Netherlands.
The move doubles its total share capital and halves the voting strength of
First Pacific's stake to just 21.6 per cent.
'Internatio-Muller is of the opinion that a merger with Hagemeyer would
result in no or hardly any benefits of synergy and that a merger with
Hagemeyer is in direct conflict with (our) new strategy,' the Rotterdam
company said.
Hagemeyer and First Pacific insisted their intentions were friendly,
although Internatio's response suggests that a battle may be brewing.
Mr Derek Murphy, First Pacific's corporate communications director, said
Internatio's issue of new preference shares was 'not surprising' and the
company was 'not terribly put out'. Some attempt to maintain the status quo
had been expected, he said.
Mr Manuel Pangilinan, managing director, has said he regards Hagemeyer as a
'springboard for expansion' in Europe and the US, although the group's 'main
focus' would remain in Asia, source of most of the company's capital,
management and profits.
With sales of Fl 2.5bn, Hagemeyer, has grown rapidly in recent years. Since
First Pacific acquired a stake in 1983, the company has halted its
manufacturing operations, pulled out of commodities and ended its presence
in Africa.
The company is now mainly a trader of consumer and professional brand name
products, including those of Panasonic, JVC, Moulinex and Christian Dior.
First Pacific recently reported a 28.4 per cent increase in after-tax
profits for 1990 to HKDollars 366m (Pounds 27.1m), before extraordinary
items.
</TEXT>
