<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / One-day Tube strike called off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RAIL UNIONS yesterday called off a one-day strike on the London Underground
planned for tomorrow after agreeing a compromise with management over job
losses.
The agreement lifts the threat of a series of 24-hour stoppages similar to
those which disrupted the Tube network two years ago.
However, a threat to British Rail services during the summer remains because
of a separate dispute over a 7 per cent pay offer.
RMT, the largest rail union, is seeking members' support for industrial
action, although BR said yesterday that arbitration over a similar offer to
the TSSA and Aslef unions will start on Thursday.
Settlement of the Underground dispute follows two days of talks last week at
Acas, the conciliation service.
London Underground yesterday denied RMT claims that it had agreed to save
200 of 1,005 jobs it planned to cut from its 22,500 total. There would still
be 800 job losses among members of RMT and TSSA, the other union which had
threatened a strike tomorrow. The other 200 or so jobs to go would be among
Aslef members or employees who do not belong to a union.
In the Acas talks, however, London Underground said there were no plans for
further job losses at present, thus allaying union fears of a 'hidden
agenda' on staff numbers.
</TEXT>
