<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Letter: Glimmer of hope in trade talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Prof D GREENAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Several of the features which you ran in the issues of April 26 and the
weekend of April 27/28 illustrate admirably some of the risks associated
with a failure of the Uruguay Round. In particular were the reports that
Japan faces trade sanctions by the US; the Korean declaration that it would
maintain an import ban on rice; and the continued discussions surrounding a
North American free trade area. The first of these takes forward Super 301
action to new territory; the second is no doubt action which has been
promoted by the Japanese rice ban, and the third - as some commentators have
noted - raises the prospect of the US becoming even more concerned with
regional trade liberalisation than global trade liberalisation.
These developments really do highlight the need for a resumption of serious
negotiations in Geneva. One glimmer of hope came through another of your
features on April 26, which indicated that the 15 negotiating groups are
being slimmed down to eight negotiating areas.
This actually gives some cause for optimism given the difficulties which
were associated with linkage across negotiating groups and the stimulus that
this gave to what Mr Arthur Dunkel, Gatt director-general, referred to as
'hide and seek tactics'. The fact that the new negotiating areas actually
embrace cognate issues ought to make the cutting of deals easier.
We must hope now that the major protagonists actually take advantage of the
opportunities provided by this slimmed-down framework. Strong gestures from
the US in the form of fast-track approval; from the EC on agriculture; and
from Japan on rice could clear the way for a serious resumption of
negotiations. The new framework raises a little the probability that these
negotiations could yet reach a satisfactory conclusion.
David Greenaway,
Department of Economics,
University of Nottingham
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
