<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Letter: Innovation - the government's role and industry's
challenge (1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr SIMON HASKEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, For many years those of us who manage manufacturing companies have
realised the importance of innovation to our companies' competitive
performance. Your leader, 'And Ridley Begat Lilley' (May 1), stressing the
need to improve innovation, will therefore encourage those of us trying to
gain a competitive advantage by incorporating new products and processes
into our business and financial policies. More welcome was your call for the
DTI actively to promote and encourage innovation.
You are right - government can influence a number of areas which have an
important bearing on innovation; chief among these is the skills training
needed to implement the technology. Also, government can encourage
collaborative R&amp;D with industry, even entering into partnerships. The DTI
can provide product and technical information, lay dawn compatibility and
standards policy, better protect intellectual property and encourage the
financial institutions to consider product development as an important
objective and invest in it long term. However, given the record of the DTI
over the last 10 years your call will fall on deaf ears.
How refreshing, therefore, to turn the page of the same edition and find Mr
Gordon Brown - a Labour MP - explaining that under a Labour government the
DTI would actively apply itself to these matters by which government can so
influence innovation.
The conclusion must be that Labour's industrial policies deserve more
sympathetic consideration and support.
Simon Haskel,
chairman,
The Perrotts Group,
63A Ockendon Road, N1 3NL.
</TEXT>
