<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Letter: Balance sheet strength should be priority over
short-term earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PHILIP GIBBS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The recent proposals by the Accounting Standards Board are to be
welcomed in seeking to narrow the range of profit and loss items appearing
as extraordinary. Far too many companies have been trying to uphold earnings
per share by treating abnormal losses as extraordinary.
In particular many companies have for years been taking profits above the
line on activities only then to treat costs of closure as below the line.
On the other hand, ASB proposals are going severely to limit the usefulness
of earnings per share in valuing companies. Large distortions will arise
from profits or losses on disposal of big assets or termination of
operations.
Valuations based on balance sheets and brand names will be given added
significance. In this context, I am surprised it has not been suggested that
companies should give figures for assets per share (excluding goodwill) when
revealing earnings per share.
A concentration on balance sheet strength rather than short term earnings
could, incidentally, be very beneficial to industry and might help to avoid
further collapses such as have been seen in service-based businesses in the
past few years.
Philip Gibbs,
Barclays de Zoete Wedd,
Ebbgate House,
2 Swan Lane, EC4
</TEXT>
