<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
As we move towards the millennium it looks more and more probable that the
main cause of international tension, instead of the politics of the Cold
War, could be that old Hollywood plot favourite, water rights. Israel has
given up the Sinai which has oil but no water, but the same is not true of
the West Bank and the Golan Heights: they have water which is vital for
Israel. Syria, Turkey and Iraq are locked into a major disagreement over the
uses of the Euphrates, a water course with significance dating from the
Bible and beyond. BBC2 investigates these modern feuds in Water Wars (8.10).
That is followed by the consistently outstanding MASH (9.00) and then the
first part of an Australian mini-series about a newspaper tycoon: The Paper
Man (9.25) .....Australian newspaper tycoon? There's no such thing, surely?
The story of the Soviet Union's most important Cold War turncoat, Oleg
Penkovsky, is told by ace spy-chaser Tom Bower in BBC1's Inside Story
(9.30). Channel 4 offers yet another introduction to its Satyajit Ray season
in Movie Masterclass (11.45) where Mamoun Hassan gives a shot by shot
analysis of that marvellous film 'The World Of Apu'.
</TEXT>
