<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Arts: New look for the merry month of May - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Early May is scarcely a time when you expect television to be screening lots
of new material, yet every day in the past week has brought at least one new
series (not another batch of some grizzled old sitcom, tagged 'NEW]' in the
programme magazines like an ancient detergent, but genuinely fresh series)
and some nights have provided several.
WEDNESDAY. Fans of the funniest game show on television, Whose Line Is It
Anyway, will have looked forward to Josie since we were promised Josie
Lawrence was being 'let loose on her own comedy series'. WLIIA? has
established a whole string of new(ish) comedians as very special people:
those who can think fast enough on their feet to be really funny while
improvising. Few have the gift to achieve this consistently, but Josie
Lawrence was one. Astute readers of the runes may have guessed what was in
store when La Lawrence began complaining in the hype interviews preceding
Episode 1 that people would keep asking whether her shows were to be like
Tracey Ullman's or Emma Thompson's and they jolly well weren't going to be
like either so shuttup or I'll scweam and scweam till I'm thick, I can you
know.
Unhappily the first show looked as though it had been modelled precisely
half and half on Ullman and Thompson (neither of whom managed in their shows
to approach the unvaryingly high standard of Victoria Wood or even the
occasional brilliance of French and Saunders). Lawrence's impression of
Kylie Minogue was not so good that one could forget Kylie is currently a
back number and her sister is the one in the limelight. For the rest it was
all too clear that a flair for improvisation is no guarantee of talent in
other areas.
Channel 4 is following that with a series showing excerpts from Manhattan
Cable, the New York service which combines cable technology and the freedom
of expression required under the American constitution to provide the most
astonishing public access channel on earth. Anyone who has sat in New York
and watched it for more than a couple of nights knows that the Bible
thumping grows boring only slightly sooner than the explicit sex. (Why are
they all so desperately sleazy?) Yet sliced up into miniature portions for
these British compilations it all looks fascinatingly zany rather than
tediously insane.
Easily the best of the new Wednesday series is BBC2's Water Wars which began
with a programme that proved comprehensively how important this subject is,
and how much more so it may rapidly become. The winning by American Indians
of water rights on their land, the competition between cities and farmers
for water, the broking of water rights and water itself, were all conveyed
with abnormal clarity by a combination of good pictures and a good script
(though the large proportion of the population with hearing that is
impaired, however slightly, will have hated the parts where music interfered
with speech).
THURSDAY. Birdscape on Channel 4 is described as 'a new series in which
wildlife artist and naturalist Bruce Pearson travels around Britain to paint
its birdlife'. The surprise in Episode 1 was that we saw so little of the
painting, though perhaps you could see why: the fens, with those huge pale
blue northern winter skies, the navy blue water beneath, and the vivid
yellow sedge and reed between, decorated with thousands of geese, swans and
duck, looked so magnificent that it would have been somewhat absurd to turn
away to look at paintings.
FRIDAY. Those who missed the opening episode of ITV's sitcom Second Thoughts
can decide for themselves whether to begin with Episode 2. James Bolam is a
divorce with no children but a Sloane Ranger ex wife. He is hoping to marry
Lynda Bellingham who seems to have no husband but two teenage children. The
opening exchange (in bed) was: 'I'm usually in Sainsbury's about now' -
'Well think of me as this week's special offer'. The writers were so proud
of a later line given to Bellingham, 'Could we have four sundaes with
crushed nuts' accompanied by a look clearly threatening Bolam's manhood,
that they used it twice.
SATURDAY. Tracey Ullman came to the fore 10 years ago in a BBC showcase
series called Three Of A Kind. The men in that programme were David
Copperfield and Lenny Henry. Now BBC1 has launched You Gotta Be Jokin'
(titles have deteriorated in a decade) featuring five young comedians: Maddi
Cryer, Annette Law, George Marshall, Billy Pearce and Shane Richie.
Presumably the hope is that, once again, most of them will go rocketin' to
stardom, though if it is passe to do impressions of Kylie Minogue what can
you say about an impression of Millie singing 'My Boy Lollipop'? That
reached its highest point in the British charts, number two, 27 years ago
last month. The funniest item in this opening programme was Annette Law's
impression of Penelope Keith performing a medley of rap numbers in her Margo
persona. It will be a surprise if more than one from this group makes it
into the big time.
Each of them, however, is funnier than the whole of The Wolvis Family put
together . . . at least, I think so. This BBC2 series is the sort of thing
that sounds wonderful at 'offers meetings' (where BBC department heads
consider offers for new programmes) since it is so simple: the members of a
family sit on chairs in a bare studio and undergo group therapy led by a
sickeningly trendy and somewhat dense therapist, the sort who wags his
fingers in the air like a Hampstead hostess to denote 'quotes'. There was a
small improvement towards the end of the first episode, so the series may
bear more watching.
SUNDAY. Six one-hour programmes on mankind's development and use of maps
sounds like a splendid idea: an under explored topic, yet an unusually
visual one, and lots of scope for modern technology (what fun to mix through
from, say, a mediaeval impression of Europe to the real shape of the land as
photographed from a satellite; why ever didn't they do it?) Unhappily in
ITV's The Shape Of The World the idea has been spoiled by a poor script, an
intrusive commentary, and a lack of the sort of narrative drive which is so
well exemplified by Water Wars.
The script is littered with cliche: what do you call an old map kept by an
old man who brings it out once a year? A time honoured possession. What does
the sun do in hot weather? It beats down. How does it beat down?
Remorselessly. And so on. Where commentary is concerned they have made the
oldest mistake in the documentary book and had it read by an actor with an
idiosyncratic voice. Patrick Stewart is fine in Hamlet or Star Trek but the
minute you hide his face and ask him to communicate via voice alone he does
what so many actors do and goes over the top. He is by turns arch, plummy
and portentous but always noticeable - which is the last thing you want.
MONDAY. In Watching The Detectives Channel 4 seems determined to convince us
not only that the television image of the work done by such people as
Holmes, Morse and Poirot is utterly unrealistic, but that the lives of real
detectives are narcoleptically boring. The opening episode established this
in the first 10 minutes and spent the next 50 challenging us to stay awake
as the camera watched the wet streets of Manchester from a car which was
following a stolen kitchen cabinet that we were never allowed to see. As a
dramatic climax our Manchester sleuth switched to following (still in his
car) a wife who was going to meet either her boyfriend or a business
colleague - but we were never allowed to see her either.
TUESDAY. Big Break on BBC1 is one of those game shows that you start
watching through barely parted fingers because the host, comedian Jim
Davidson, is from the 'Goodness me what a prat we have here' school, made so
familiar by Bruce Forsyth. Then, when he asks one of the contestants 'Is a
Concorde or a 737 the fastest passsenger plane?' and she replies 'Yes' you
take his point, and remove your fingers. This is the 914th variation on
'Beat The Clock' to appear since Sunday Night At The London Palladium was
axed, though this time the game is always snooker. Why don't they simply
revive 'Beat The Clock'?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17 Photograph Manhattan Cable, low down from New York in
tempting portions (Omitted).
</PAGE>
