<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Arts: Cyrano - Covent Garden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A second look at David Bintley's new Cyrano on Monday night did not bring
any greater pleasure than at the premiere. Indeed, once the element of
novelty has gone, there is even less to recommend about a piece whose
vulgarity of means and choreographic weediness are very worrying. This
Cyrano is ballet for people who can't be bothered with ballet. It is ballet
as production ideas and mime; ballet as vampire, feeding from its
interpreters; ballet as knock-about farce to a knock-about score. It is,
ultimately, ballet on the terms of indifferent musical comedy - not Cole
Porter, but Lloyd Webber.
Wilfred Joseph's score does not stand up to a second hearing, with its
fragmentary air and its blatancies - exact though it is in matching the
choreography's failings. The design by Hayden Griffin succeeds in clouding
the action in cloaks and ballooning breeches and long dresses whose tedious
verismo is in marked contrast to the balletic savoir-faire shown by Nicholas
Georgiadis in Mayerling and Manon. In a curious and disquieting way, this
Cyrano places ballet - and the Royal Ballet in particular - in an aesthetic
limbo, far removed from the obvious lineage which led from Petipa to Ashton
and thence to MacMillan. It denies ballet as an art concerned with movement
expressive or brilliant. Cyrano is production as justification for jokiness,
posturing and sentimentality.
Monday night's performance brought the debuts of Irek Mukhamedov as Cyrano,
Viviana Durante as Roxane, and Stuart Cassidy as Christian. The young lovers
were as beguiling as their roles allow, and I admire their artistry very
much. Mukhamedov cannot give an indifferent performance, and he seeks to
show Cyrano's inner life, but throughout the evening I was conscious that
this was the great artist who could storm in glory as Ivan the Terrible, and
Spartacus, and play with consummate sensitivity as des Grieux or Albrecht or
Lescaut. His Cyrano is the merest shadow of these, and the fault is not
Mukhamedov's.
This week's performances mark the 20th anniversary of the Midland Bank Proms
at the Opera House. Long may they continue, and long may the bank have our
gratitude for such enlightened sponsorship.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
