<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Management abstracts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Danger - 'entrepreneurs' at work. Business Executive (UK), Jul/Aug 90 (3
pages)
Mounts an attack on the 'immense amount of waste and petty fraud endemic
within the British economy. Ranges widely, from copier/phone abuse via
private businesses run from employed positions to those who maximise
tax-free expenses, freebies, and subsidised travel ('academics are
particular experts'). Then speculates that the condition isn't confined to
Britain - to suggest so would be racial discrimination.
*****
Fighting white-collar crime. K Ellis &amp; S Pitt in Business Executive (UK),
Jul/Aug 90 (3 pages)
Warns of the increase in white-collar crime (theft, computer fraud, bribery
and espionage) and draws attention to the services of consultants and the
availability of insurance. Suggests that consultants and insurers should get
together to convince their target market of what is needed.
*****
Champions of change. J M Howell &amp; C A Higgins in Business Quarterly
(Canada), Spring 90 (6 pages)
Outlines the significant contribution that champions make to the innovative
process by taking creative ideas, which they may or may not have generated
themselves, and bringing them to life; examines their personality
characteristics - such as self-confidence and willingness to take risks -
and leadership qualities. Discusses three processes by which champions
generally operate, defined as the renegade, the rational, and the
participative; looks at how champions may be fostered in organisations.
*****
Evaluating investments in information technology. S L Huff in Business
Quarterly (Canada), Spring 90 (4 pages)
Discusses how the assessment of pay-off from IT investments can be
considered at the macroeconomic, business unit, functional, and individual
levels; stresses that while it might not be necessary to translate
intangible benefits into quantitative terms, they cannot be omitted from the
equations if the analysis is to be meaningful.
These abstracts are condensed from the abstracting journals published by
Anbar Management Publications. Licensed copies of the original articles may
be obtained at a cost of Pounds 5.75 each (including VAT and p+p; cash with
order) from Anbar, 62 Toller Lane, Bradford, West Yorkshire BD8 9BY.
</TEXT>
