<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Syndicates expected to accept probe at Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEVERAL hundred Names in the Lloyd's of London insurance market, who were
members of the loss-making Feltrim syndicates, are today expected to reject
legal action in their attempt to recoup one of the biggest losses in Lloyd's
history.
Instead the Names are likely to agree to the establishment of an independent
Lloyd's investigation into the circumstances of the losses, making use of a
new facility announced last week by Lloyd's in response to mounting
criticism from Names.
The decision should temporarily alleviate pressure on the authorities at the
troubled insurance market, but Names are insisting that the investigation be
thorough and are refusing to rule out the possibility of legal action
eventually,
Mr Colin Hook, chairman of the Feltrim Names Association, said there were 'a
lot of questions to be answered' about the regulation and management of the
Feltrim syndicates, which specialised in catastrophe reinsurance. 'A number
of glaring inadequacies have come to light,' he said.
Two thousand Names on syndicates 540/542 and 847, formerly managed by the
Feltrim Underwriting Agency, expect to lose more than Pounds 320m on
business written in 1987, 1988 and 1989. Names with an average commitment of
between Pounds 25,000 and Pounds 30,000 are facing losses of between Pounds
150,000 and Pounds 200,000 each.
Syndicate 540's results were worst in 1989 when 547 recorded a loss
equivalent to 300 per cent of its annual stamp capacity - the maximum amount
of premium it is permitted to write.
The Council of Lloyd's agreed on Wednesday to set up a special investigation
to examine the commercial circumstances of all losses exceeding 150 per cent
of a syndicate's annual stamp capacity.
Mr Hook welcomed the move, which he said had been made 'in response to an
initiative from the Feltrim Names'. He said any investigation would have to
be 'genuinely independent'.
The Names are concerned about the way members' agents at Lloyd's continued
to channel Names into the Feltrim syndicates during 1988 and 1989, in spite
of indications that Feltrim was badly affected by catastrophes such as the
October 1987 storms and the Piper Alpha oil rig explosion.
</TEXT>
