<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Eastern Europe 'needs to adjust to trade
patterns'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DULLFORCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EAST EUROPEAN countries must speed domestic reform, if they are to draw real
benefits from adjusting trade, William Dullforce in Geneva writes.
This advice comes from a symposium of 40 eastern and western economists
organised by the UN Economic Commission for Europe (ECE) and the
Osteuropa-Institut and Sudost-Institut in Munich last year, and now in book
form*.
Trade reform in isolation is deceptively easy, the economists warn.
Enterprises can be granted rights to import and export on their own, and
foreign currency auctions can be quickly set up. But without domestic
reforms, enterprises will not respond to enhanced export opportunities and
more realistic exchange rates.
Cuts in central controls over trade seemed so far to have had only limited
effects in improving the quality of exports, the economists noted. They
favoured a shift from quotas and administrative curbs to conventional
tariffs on the import side. But they warned that partial reforms, such as
reducing limits on imports of intermediate goods while maintaining
protection for consumer goods, as in Poland, could be counter-productive, by
raising protection for domestic producers. Opinions differed on future
trading links in Comecon.
*Reforms in Foreign Economic Relations of Eastern Europe and the Soviet
Union. Pp 200. Available: Palais des Nations, CH-1211 Geneva 10. Dollars 60.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
