FT  08 MAY 91 / US to shuffle State's European specialists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US will soon reshuffle its senior State Department officials who deal
with European issues.
Mr Thomas Niles, US ambassador to the European Community, is expected to be
nominated shortly as the new Assistant Secretary for European and Canadian
affairs, in which job he would handle the review of US security relations
with Europe. He would take over from Mr Raymond Seitz, who has just become
US ambassador to Britain.
The 51-year-old Mr Niles is a highly experienced career diplomat, having
served in Belgrade, Moscow (twice), at Nato headquarters in Brussels and as
ambassador to Canada from 1985 to 1989, when he dealt with the US-Canadian
free trade agreement, as well as in various senior positions at the State
Department. He has held his present post for the past two years.
Mr Niles is to be succeeded in Brussels by Mr James Dobbins, now principal
deputy assistant secretary in the Bureau of European and Canadian Affairs,
who deals with many European issues. Aged 48, he has served in various State
Departments posts in the US, Paris, London, and Bonn, where he was deputy
chief of mission from 1985 to 1989.
