<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Indian Elections: Caste struggle strangles poor, corrupt
Bihar - State administration has broken down and violence is a threat to the
election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HOUSEGO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DRIVING through the relentless heat of Bihar, one is soon made aware how
much this part of the northern Hindi belt has been engulfed in a power
struggle between castes, one that has already led to breakdown of the state
administration and which now threatens to drown India's election in
violence.
At Masaurhi, north of the Ganges and close to Muzaffarpur, a group of
harijans (untouchables) point to their bamboo and thatched homes that were
burnt down by local landlords a few days before. The harijans say they were
seeking an increase in their wages of Rs 3-10 (9-30p) a day.
Nearby landlords of the Bhumihar caste - the dominant upper caste in the
Muzaffarpur area - unite in a conspiracy of silence and say they know
nothing of the incident.
In Muzaffarpur itself, most colleges and universities - as elsewhere in
Bihar - are closed because teachers have not been paid for three or four
months. The Bihar state government, which has the reputation of being the
most corrupt and ill-managed in the country, has run out of funds.
Returning to Patna at night, we are regularly stopped by police checking for
arms. The local papers are full of reports of booming business among village
arms makers ahead of the election. Since campaigning began there have been
at least 50 political assassinations, which has raised the question of
whether the state will be brought under direct rule from Delhi before the
elections, due to take place during the week of May 20 to May 26.
'There is no administration in Bihar, no law and order,' says Mr Raganath
Pandey, a local Brahmin and former transport contractor who is the Congress
party's candidate. 'Nobody is safe.' His opponents laugh at this profession
of righteousness from a man who in the past has faced criminal charges and
whose election strength lies largely in the support he has from the region's
underworld bosses.
The founding fathers of Indian independence had hoped that caste differences
would melt away under the impact of development and modernisation. But in
Bihar, as in much of the Hindi-speaking belt of north India, the competition
for jobs and resources has hardened caste divisions.
The big battleground is between the traditionally dominant upper castes of
Brahmins, Bhumihars and Rajputs - and the increasingly aggressive farmer
castes of Yadavs, Kurmis and Keoris who are challenging their control over
the power and patronage of government.
This power struggle was intensified last year by former Prime Minister V P
Singh's announcement that 27 per cent of central government jobs would be
reserved for these so called 'backward castes'. Job reservation for the poor
 -a term used to embrace all the lower castes, untouchables and Moslems -
has since become the central plank of his Janata Dal party's election
campaign. This has earned Mr Singh the hatred of the upper castes.
A second factor that has deepened caste conflict in Bihar is that a backward
caste leader has taken over as chief minister of the state. In the year he
has been chief minister, Mr Laloo Prasad Yadav has openly deployed the power
and patronage of the state to his community's advantage.
Dr CPN Thakur, a leader of the Bhumihar community in Muzaffarpur, sums up
upper caste fears and resentments by saying: 'Everything is at stake. Life,
prestige and property.'
Muzaffarpur is a test case of this power struggle between castes because it
is a prestige constituency. It has sent national leaders to the parliament
in the past and has been the breeding ground of several national movements.
Mr George Fernandes, the former industry and railway minister and the Janata
Dal politician who most sees himself as a revolutionary, has held the seat
in three of the last four elections. He is contesting it this time and is
thought likely to win.
Muzaffarpur - part of the fertile region between the Himalayas and the
Ganges - is also a stronghold of the Bhumihar caste, who claim to have the
same status as Brahmins. They account for 25 per cent of the population.
Yadavs, the most militant of the backward castes, are the next largest
community - thus sharpening the rivalry between the two.
For the first time since independence, however, Mr Singh's success in making
job reservation the central issue here means voting is expected to be
polarised on caste lines. Upper castes are backing the Congress and the
backward castes the Janata Dal.
Previous elections have been characterised by considerable voting across
caste lines, with many Bhumihars supporting the Janata Dal party and
lower-caste groups the Congress.
Growing caste tensions have been accompanied by rising violence. Rioting by
upper-caste youths against job reservation did more damage in Muzaffarpur
than in any other city in Bihar. Unemployment is so high in Bihar that only
20 per cent of graduates find jobs.
Backward castes also appear to have been indulging in the killing of
upper-caste boys. Dr Thakur cites seven recent cases of Bhumihars being
stopped on country roads and shot after revealing their caste.
The hope of the upper castes is that a Congress government in Delhi would
overthrow the Bihar state government and slow the pace of reservation. The
Yadavs and backward castes look to a Janata Dal victory to accelerate what
they call 'social justice'.
They do not seem to be much concerned at the damage which growing caste
conflict is inflicting on the state's economy or its education system.
'Nobody is thinking about that. Nobody bothers,' says Professor Arun Kumar
Sinha, a local Janata Dal leader. 'We are deep in a social struggle.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
