<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Fractious partners put Andreotti's political skills to test:
The Italian government's stability has been undermined barely a month after
taking office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S 50th post-war government is badly frayed at the edges just a month
after taking office.
Two key problems are undermining the government's stability: intractable
opposition to plans to cut public spending and a long-running row over
constitutional reform.
The fractious four-party coalition has opted to soldier on until the end of
the current legislature in 1992, rather than call early elections. In doing
so it has lumbered the country with a lame duck government unable to take
pressing political decisions.
The coalition has called a meeting for May 11 and it might be forced to the
polls early unless it can settle its differences.
Last Friday Mr Guido Carli, the veteran Treasury minister pledging to sort
out the country's messy finances, was said to be threatening to resign
following opposition to his proposed spending cuts.
Mr Carli wants to trim the country's huge budget deficit, targeted at
L132,000bn (Pounds 60.4bn) this year. Pension reform and a public-sector pay
curb are designed to help raise the L15,000bn-L16,000bn needed to bring this
year's government spending back into line. But the Socialists and some
Christian Democrats in the government are refusing to accept the cuts,
partly for fear of public unpopularity.
Mr Claudio Martelli, the Socialist deputy premier, said last week the
pension and public-sector pay cuts were not part of the programme agreed by
coalition parties last month. Mr Franco Marini, the former trade union
leader, who is the new Christian Democrat minister of labour, has also
voiced objections.
The dispute comes as no surprise to Mr Giorgio La Malfa, head of the small
Republican party which last month pulled out of the coalition after a clash
with Mr Giulio Andreotti, Italian premier, over ministerial posts.
'We called for early elections on an agreed basis in order to save the next
finance bill from the pressure of the elections ahead,' he explains.
'Otherwise we knew the influence of the polls would just increase the
temptation to raise spending.'
Failure to put Italy's messy finances in order would mean a larger
government deficit, possibly triggering higher interest rates and inflation,
along with the risk of an economic downturn.
With pensions and public-sector pay apparently sacrosanct, a mixed bag of
indirect tax rises and new levies is likely, with structural reform once
again being left until after the polls, if not beyond.
Last month's much-publicised decision by Moody's, the US debt rating agency,
to review Italy's top-notch triple-A borrowing status has heightened party
leaders' awareness of international attention focusing on the nation's
deteriorating finances. Criticism of domestic economic management has also
come from the International Monetary Fund and the Bundesbank.
Half-hearted measures would be unlikely to convince foreign investors, who
play an important role in financing Italy's debt, that the country's
politicians are about to get to grips with the deficit.
Mr Andreotti has remained silent about both the political storm and this
week's renewed outbursts by the president, Mr Francesco Cossiga, over
constitutional reform, the issue which was partly to blame for the collapse
of Mr Andreotti's previous government.
Mr Cossiga wants the government to push through fundamental constitutional
reform, including changes to the electoral system, the election of the
president and differentiation of the roles of the two houses of parliament.
He accepted the cabinet's decision to put off the most important proposals
until after next year's polls but, apparently unable to set the issue aside,
he has aired his views almost daily to the media.
As president, Mr Cossiga's interventions can cause no immediate political
threat to the cabinet, but his comments are embarrassing the government and
have fuelled the crisis.
He has also clashed with the Christian Democrats - his former party. Two of
his most recent targets have been berated for speaking to newspapers that
fail to meet the president's approval.
The president has singled out La Repubblica, Italy's biggest-selling
newspaper, for attack. He describes the paper, owned by Mr Carlo De
Benedetti, as being the mouthpiece for the 'politico-financial lobby' which
he claims has been waging a two-year campaign against him.
With tensions within the coalition rising, and Mr Cossiga firing off in all
directions, Mr Andreotti will need all his skills to smooth over the latest
set of upsets threatening his new government.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
