<DATE>910508
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 91 / Brussels pressure over social security: Commission seeks
acceptance of 'guidelines' intended to improve benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission yesterday put forward guidelines intended to
harmonise and improve social security benefits throughout the EC.
Brussels officials believe that endorsement of the guidelines by member
states would show stronger commitment to the Community's social aims than
the support given to the Social Charter, adopted in December 1989 with the
sole dissent of the UK.
The guidelines are a 'recommendation' which Brussels wants the Council of
Ministers to adopt. This would have no legal standing, but would, in the
Commission's view, acquire political and moral force if it gains the
required unanimous approval of member states.
Brussels wants a general right to benefits, based on need, to be recognised
all over the EC. Eight member states have some form of guaranteed minimum
income for the poor, such as 'income support' in the UK or Sozialhilfe in
Germany. Italy and Spain have similar but limited regional schemes, but
Greece and Portugal have virtually nothing.
The Commission also wants such benefits to be without a time limit, to be
extended to non-EC nationals resident in the Community, and to be
accompanied by access to health care, housing and training.
Its initiative is an attempt to generate movement in an area where it cannot
get laws through, as part of its emphasis that the 'social dimension' to the
single market programme has not been forgotten.
More practically, it wants to limit the scope for 'social dumping':
companies moving to areas of the EC where social legislation is weakest, or,
once exchange rates are locked by monetary union, countries cutting social
expenditure to boost competitiveness.
The Commission's aim is to be able to monitor the extent to which member
states' social security regimes converge. As part of this, it wants the
Twelve mutually to scrutinise each other's practice, rather as they now
examine each other's macroeconomic performance within the so-called
'multilateral surveillance' sessions of the council of finance ministers.
'The strongest we can expect . . . is to be able to embarrass laggard member
states,' a Commission official said.
Britain, which believes that EC social policy should limit itself to health
and safety regulations and the creation of jobs, 'is unlikely to have
serious difficulties with the recommendation,' British diplomats here said.
It could benefit those EC workers who now fall outside any national safety
net, they said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
