<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Bourses in decline as holidays
subdue trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST BOURSES declined yesterday, as holidays in London and Tokyo kept
trading thin, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT was marked down in thin trading in the absence of UK investors.
Domestic investors were also hesitant before Thursday's Ascension Day
holiday. The DAX index lost 7.85 to 1,623.99 while the FAZ index, calculated
at midsession, fell 2.29 to 691.29. Volume slipped to DM3.6bn from DM5.3bn.
BASF, the chemical group, fell DM4.50 to DM250.20 after reporting that its
first-quarter group pretax profit had dipped 25 per cent, slightly more than
expected.
Bucking the trend was Metallgesellschaft, which rose DM3 to DM546 following
news over the weekend that it was involved in a DM1bn project to clean up
and modernise one of the largest and most polluted areas of east Germany.
MILAN saw an early but unsustained leap in Fiat on the back of an article in
an Italian business paper, which quoted company sources as saying that the
dividend would be maintained in 1990. There have been fears that the pay-out
would be cut.
Fiat ordinary shares were officially set L195 higher at L5,446, but fell
back to L5,375 after hours, taking the market with them. The Comit index
lost 0.34 to 585.90 in thin volume estimated at L120bn after Friday's
L145bn.
Dealers said that while the market was getting some support from corporate
groups before various rights issues, nervousness over the political
situation remained. News of a net outflow of L83bn in equity funds in April
after a net inflow of L120bn in March could weigh on share values today,
they added.
Generali was weak, slipping to L36,900 after being officially set at
L37,050, down L550.
PARIS eased as hopes of a cut in interest rates were thwarted. The CAC 40
index ended 3.54 down at 1,828.77, recovering from a day's low of 1,816.58,
and turnover fell to about half Friday's FFr2.1bn.
Michelin continued to attract interest, rising FFr1.65 to FFr97.85 on volume
of 432,050 shares. The stock has gained 16.3 per cent in the six sessions
since some brokers raised their forecasts. The tyremaker told shareholders
that Mr Edouard Michelin, son of the current chairman, would be nominated
next month for the post of associate director.
One of the day's big movers was Immobiliere Phenix, the property company,
which jumped FFr8.90 or 4.7 per cent to FFr198.90.
MADRID was one the few bourses to rise. The general index edged up 0.29 to
278.68, recovering from an early fall, in turnover slightly down on Friday's
Pta12.5bn.
The banking and construction sectors produced most of the interest. Banco
Exterior rose Pta65 to Pta3,580 on the news that it is to be integrated with
other state-controlled banks in a new company, Corporacion Bancaria de
Espana.
A block of 601,200 shares or about 6 per cent of the share capital of
Petromed, a Banesto unit, was traded at Pta7,390 a share, up Pta30.
OSLO also ignored the gloom elsewhere and rose in moderate trading, as
optimism about the economy continued to improve, following cuts in interest
rates in the past couple of months. The all-share index gained 4.77 to
488.83 in turnover of NKr302m.
COPENHAGEN edged higher in quiet trading. The bourse index gained 1.28 to
349.31. Den Danske Bank rose DKr1 to DKr324 in turnover of DKr73m, on
foreign demand following its recent European roadshow.
STOCKHOLM's Affarsvarlden General index fell 7.5 to 1,042.9 in light
turnover of SKr222m. Ericsson accounted for SKr44m of that, as its free B
shares eased SKr2 to SKr191 before its first-quarter earnings report, due
today.
BRUSSELS slipped at the end of the two-week account on the forward market.
The Bel20 index lost 7.8 to 1,177.27. Petrofina, the oil group, was active;
its shares ended above a day's low of BFr11,375 at BFr11,450, down BFr50.
Yesterday was the last day to trade Petrofina's warrant which expires on May
20; the warrant fell BFr25 to BFr2,775.
AMSTERDAM fell in dull trading. The CBS tendency index ended 0.3 down at the
day's low of 95.1.
HBG and Volker Stevin, the builders, were suspended before an announcement
that HBG would purchase Volker Stevin's dredging business and shed its 60
per cent stake in the latter.
ZURICH declined, with the Credit Suisse index off 5.8 at 545.6. Unigestion
was suspended at the request of its leading shareholder, Swiss Bank, pending
news of a reorganisation.
ISTANBUL slumped 4.9 per cent on fears of further selling. The index fell
189.47 to 3,691.71, down 7.4 per cent since Thursday.
ATHENS was led lower by the banking sector. The general index dropped 49.65
or 4.4 per cent to 1,093.23.
The Eurotrack 100 index was not available owing to the closure of the London
Stock Exchange.
