<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / International Company News: Cross Border M&amp;A Deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRIAN BOLLEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Activity in the Asia-Pacific region was a feature of last week's
international mergers and acquisitions, writes Brian Bollen.
The sale of Australian merchant bank Dominguez Barry Samuel Montagu
continues Midland Bank's strategy of selling non-core assets outside Europe
and enables purchaser Swiss Bank Corp to expand its international investment
banking business.
Morgan Grenfell furthered its ambition to establish a strong independent
presence in the south east Asian securities market, taking a 30 per cent
stake in Malaysian stockbroker K&amp;N Kenanga.
Laporte of the UK is expanding its business in printed wiring board
chemicals into a fast growing market for electronics, through the
acquisition of Taipei-based Taiwan Spechem.
Elsewhere, the tender offer by South African-controlled Oceana for a stake
in UK fashion retailer Etam confirms the suspicions of some market players
that the UK retailing sector has bottomed out. While Oceana said it is
considering an offer for the whole company and is using the tender to gauge
shareholder response, Etam attacked it as an attempt to gain back door
control at an unacceptably low price.
In the ongoing restructuring of the global car industry, Japan's car
assembly presence will increase when Mitsubishi Motors completes its
purchase of one third of Volvo Cars, joining the Dutch government and Volvo
as an equal partner.
The horticultural division of UK group Fisons is making its first
significant move into continental Europe with the purchase of DSM Agro
Specialties of Holland.
