<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Struggling to hold the back door closed: The UK's attempts
to control acquisitions by foreign state-controlled companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The clearance last week of Elf Aquitaine's Pounds 300m acquisition of Amoco,
the UK petrol-station and refinery business, has thrown the whole future of
the British government's tough stance on acquisitions by foreign
state-controlled companies into doubt.
For the fourth time since Mr Peter Lilley, the Trade and Industry Secretary,
announced last July that in future he would scrutinise all acquisitions by
foreign state-controlled companies, the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
has left him powerless to act.
If the aim of the policy was to prevent 'nationalisation by the back door',
it appears to have failed. At the very least it now seems unnecessary. Can
it survive this latest blow?
At the back of Mr Lilley's policy lies the government's conviction that
private ownership leads to the more efficient allocation of resources - the
same economic policy stance which lies behind its commitment to
privatisation.
Viewed from abroad, however, it is easy to see how this new policy might
appear protectionist and contrary to the underlying principles of the single
market.
The French, in particular, appear to believe it is a protectionist policy
directed specifically at them. Four of the five references to the commission
made since the new policy was introduced have involved French
state-controlled companies.
Three of them - Woodchester/Credit Lyonnais, Sligos( owned by Credit
Lyonnais)/Signet and Elf Aquitaine/Amoco - were referred by Mr Lilley
against the advice of the Director General of Fair Trading.
In only one case, Kemira Oy/ICI, has the commission concluded that the
merger might be expected to operate against the public interest.
Credit Lyonnais, incensed by what it sees as a deliberate discriminatory
policy, has lodged a complaint with the European Commission in Brussels.
In defence of the British position it was almost inevitable that the French
would fall foul of the new policy more often than other European states.
Since early 1989 French state-controlled companies have made many more
cross-border mergers and acquisitions throughout Europe than nationalised
groups from any other European country.
They were particularly active during the first quarter of 1990 making 40
European deals with a disclosed value of Ecu 2.52bn (Pounds 1.4bn) - 58 per
cent of the value of all French deals in Europe. Britain has proved the most
popular target for French state-controlled industry.
Indeed, Mr John Redwood, Corporate Affairs Minister, first referred to the
government's intention to adopt the policy announced officially by Mr Lilley
in July after the announcement in March last year of a Pounds 301m bid by
Orkem, the French state-controlled chemicals group for Coates Brothers, the
UK inks and resins manufacturer.
The French may also have fallen foul of the Lilley policy because of their
fundamentally different attitude to public-sector enterprises. They do not
hold with the British view that private ownership necessarily leads to the
more efficient allocation of resources. It all depends on how state control
is exercised.
During the early stages of the investigation by the MMC of the Credit
Lyonnais/ Woodchester acquisition, the first of the five to be referred
following the policy statement at the end of July, the DTI took pains to
explain to the commission the reasons why Mr Lilley regards state ownership
as raising public-interest issues which may merit investigation.
A letter was sent from the DTI to the MMC outlining the reasons behind the
policy. DTI officials attended hearings at the commission and made written
submissions. The DTI letter makes it clear that the new merger reference
policy rests on the proposition that state-controlled companies are always
likely to behave in fundamentally different ways in the market place than
privately owned ones because the state as shareholder is unlike private
enterprise shareholders.
The Government believes state control represents an extreme degree of
immunity from market forces. The state may have objectives distinct from
normal commercial objectives of maximising the financial return on a
shareholder's investment. State-controlled companies do not face the threat
of financial failure.
The DTI maintains that, because their objectives may or may not be seen as
strictly commercial their behaviour is unpredictable, creating uncertainty
in the market. Competitive forces are weakened and some misallocation of
resources and overall loss of efficiency may result.
In the case of acquisitions by foreign state-controlled companies, the DTI
also fears that the state concerned might be trying to gain control of a
certain sector of the market in order to influence it in some way which
could be damaging to UK interests. Furthermore the market for corporate
control will be adversely affected because state-controlled companies
themselves are generally immune from takeover and takeover pressures.
The French approach is made clear by evidence to the MMC by its Ecomomics
and Finance Ministry. The basic thrust is that there is a broad consensus in
France on two fundamental principles which must be applied to public sector
enterprises: that they should have management autonomy and that fair and
open competition between public enterprises and between public and private
enterprises must be guaranteed in France and within the European Community.
The French government likens itself to any other majority shareholder.
French company law provides a strict framework for the government's
responsibilities. The government refrains from interfering in management
decisions although it reserves the right to pass judgment on the results of
the strategy adopted (this, it says, is no different from any majority
shareholder in a private company).
Public enterprises have no special access to special funding for
acquisitions. They decide for themselves on their commercial and financial
objectives which are approved by the government as far as they affect its
interests as shareholder. Public industrial enterprises are free to choose
their insurers and bankers. The government ensures competition law is
strictly applied.
The British response to this is that it is all fine in theory but the
reality may be different. However, on four occasions the MMC has accepted on
the evidence before it the French explanation of the role played by its
government in the management of French public enterprises.
Its conclusions on the issue of state-control in the Elf case largely echo
those in the other three French cases - the French government leaves the
running of its state enterprises to their managements.
So is Mr Lilley's policy now a dead letter? Clearly there are occasions
where state-control can be a factor which requires investigating during the
normal course of an MMC inquiry into a proposed merger which raises
competition concerns. But in the absence of sound reasons for referring a
proposed merger on competition grounds, state-control is surely no longer a
good enough reason on its own for launching a full-scale MMC inquiry.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
