<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Pretoria may return land to blacks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE South African govern-ment appears ready to restore land to some of the
3.5m blacks forcibly removed under apartheid, reversing an earlier decision
to reject all claims for restoration.
In an interview in today's Financial Times survey of South Africa, President
F. W. de Klerk makes clear that his government is willing to moderate its
tough line on the land issue, which has been criticised by anti-apartheid
groups and foreign governments. This appears to be part of the government's
attempt to create a climate conducive to constitutional negotiations at a
time of rising political tensions.
The African National Congress has said it will boycott talks unless the
government takes steps by Thursday to end violence which has left more than
150 people dead in the past week.
Relations between the ANC and Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi's Inkatha Freedom
Party further deteriorated during the weekend amid further killings - six
people died in a bus ambush in Tembisa township, north of Johannesburg
yesterday - and an Inkatha threat, later denied by Chief Buthelezi, to
deploy 250,000 armed warriors in black townships around Johannesburg.
Mr de Klerk's policy shift follows the publication in March of a white paper
which said that it 'would not be feasible' to restore land to victims of
forced removals. The victims referred to are families evicted from their
homes during the past 30 years as part of Pretoria's policy of confining all
blacks to separate homelands.
In the interview, which was conducted three weeks ago but was under embargo
until today, Mr de Klerk stresses that the government is 'not . . .
unapproachable' on the issue of restitution. 'Government's general approach
to this issue is to address the cases concerned with sympathy and
reasonableness.'
It is understood that the government has agreed to set up a land commission
to advise on claims resulting from apartheid removals. It is also understood
that some of the legislation tabled as part of a land reform package will be
withdrawn for further discussion.
The government will go ahead, however, with a bill abolishing the Group
Areas Act, which imposes residential segregation, and the 1913 and 1936 Land
Acts, which prevented blacks from owning more than 13 per cent of South
Africa.
South Africa Survey, separate section
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1250</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDAEAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / How to make a bad job worse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY HARRIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After the local elections, the government has been stuck with a Micawber
strategy; but if you are waiting for something to turn up, you should at
least ensure that nothing you do will impede it. The news on the public
spending front suggests that they have not taken this simple precaution.
The Thatcher government started its term with two economic strategies: a
medium-term financial strategy, which was meant to provide a stable policy
background, and a system of cash budgeting, which was designed to enlist the
public sector in the fight against rising costs. These rules were meant to
make government policy predictable and stabilising. In the event, they were
badly designed and had the opposite effect.
The medium-term strategy was framed in terms of the broad money supply,
which proved uncontrollable, as it was bound to do. It blew a fuse. The cash
rules were increasingly applied not to control budgeted spending, which
would have been sensible, but to borrowing. This is a destabilising rule. In
the US, it applies to most state spending, because the US has
balanced-budget laws. The result is that it is imposing an additional
squeeze of about Dollars 50bn on an already depressed economy, since it has
to cut spending as revenue falls; one reason why the promised economic
recovery keeps getting later.
Now the Treasury seems to be applying the same handbag economics to the UK
national budget; spending must be cut because revenue is weak. This is
likely to have the same result as in the US, in spite of the fact that the
chancellor explained in his Budget speech that a rise in borrowing at a time
of recession is not only to be expected but to be welcomed; it is an
automatic stabiliser. Not if you switch it off, it isn't.
There are three possible explanations for this, all of them bad. It could be
just a recurrence of bad habits; Mrs Thatcher's intense distaste for public
borrowing, even for productive investment, never did make sense. It could be
nostalgia for 1981, when tight fiscal policy at a time of recession heralded
a recovery, in defiance of 364 Keynesian economists. But the 1981 budget
worked because under the market conditions of the time, it weakened a
grossly overvalued pound. Now it is a prime objective of policy to keep the
pound too strong for comfort, to the horror of six monetarist economists; so
a tight budget cannot produce an external stimulus.
Most probably, though, ministers are scared of a bad reception in the gilts
market - a return of rule by the young men who write brokers' circulars, as
Mr Denis Healey complained. They seem to be younger than ever now; some of
the comments are evidently written by analysts who have no experience of any
government borrowing at all, so they find all large numbers frightening. In
fact, though, it is remarkably easy to borrow large sums in a recession, as
the US Treasury has found, to its surprise and delight. A world financial
market which can cheerfully accommodate some Dollars 300bn of US borrowing -
a genuinely frightening figure - is hardly likely to choke over the odd
Pounds 5bn of extra UK borrowing.
It is time to revive a medium-term strategy within the meaning of Mr
Lamont's speech - a plan for public spending designed to rise in line with
the expected trend growth of the economy (or preferably a bit slower). Once
he has such a plan, the chancellor should stick to it.
He would rightly be condemned if he embarked on a spending spree just
because the private sector was unexpectedly strong - that was how President
Reagan got the US economy into chronic debt; but he should be just as firm
in ignoring unexpected weakness and the market should understand this.
Otherwise, public policy is prey to every shifting mood in the private
sector, which is not a strategy of any kind.
Meanwhile, the Department of Trade and Industry is going in for its own kind
of destabilisation. In pursuit of market transparency, it is showing an
unhealthy interest in what goes on at brokers' corporate lunches. Again, the
reasons sound sensible: the officials are afraid that brokers may get an
inside tip about profit trends from the ho-hums and eyebrow-waggling which
take the place of any hard information at these meals (a form of
communication first perfected by the Bank of England).
The DTI therefore urges boards to make a general profits announcement before
they go out to lunch. However, companies can hardly issue revised forecasts
every day, so the actual result is likely to be the same as that of the
insider trading law it is meant to support - to keep honest men in
ignorance. The sensible answer would be to repeal the insider trading law,
since it is virtually unenforceable and gives innocent investors a false
impression. This will not happen, though; it would offend the fashionable
cult of the small investor.
The City must seek some other remedy for the real damage the law does: it
deprives the institutions, who control most of the shares, of the
information they need to act as responsible shareholders. The good news is
that some sensible ideas are beginning to emerge, though they have taken a
long time to surface.
Some insurance companies, and one or two issuing houses - notably BZW - are
trying to devise a new form of intermediary; a committee which would
represent big shareholders, but would not itself hold or trade in shares.
Such a committee could demand management information without offending the
law, and could be given the clout, by way of proxy votes, to get it.
It could then insist that problem companies call in consultants to address
particular problems; and logically, it could also demand the appointment of
new directors, as we are already seeing at Granada. This would,
incidentally, remove one main cause of the 'illogical' take-over bids on
which the Select Committee on Trade and Industry will no doubt be
pronouncing soon.
The only trouble is that the DTI may soon get suspicious about these
activities, and strangle the infant committees in red tape. One government
department throwing out the baby with the bath water is more than enough.
</TEXT>
