<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / France and Soviets in joint move on Mideast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and PETER RIDDELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH president Francois Mitterrand and Mr Mikhail Gorbachev, the Soviet
leader, yesterday threw their joint weight behind creation of a Palestinian
state and proposals for a Middle East peace conference.
After talks with Mr Mitterrand, who was in Moscow on a one-day visit,
President Gorbachev said that failure to resolve the Middle East conflict
swiftly could 'once again spill over into difficult, acute situations' such
as the Gulf war.
At the same time, the Soviet Union confirmed that foreign minister Mr
Alexander Bessmertnykh would visit Israel this week - the first head of
Soviet international diplomacy to visit the Jewish state since Moscow
severed diplomatic ties in 1967.
Mr James Baker, the US secretary of state, is also to return to the Middle
East later this week. Mr Baker said he intended to meet Mr Bessmertnykh, 'so
that we can continue to try to co-ordinate our efforts to promote a peace
conference jointly sponsored by the US and the Soviet Union'.
The US is seeking to promote both face-to-face negotiations between Israel
and each of its Arab neighbours and direct discussions between Israel and
Palestinian representatives. Mr Baker said this would be 'a very broad
conference of a nature and type that has never before taken place'.
The Soviet foreign minister, on a four-day tour starting tomorrow, will
visit Jordan, Egypt and possibly Lebanon. A foreign ministry spokesman said
Mr Bessmertnykh hoped to meet Mr Yassir Arafat, chairman of the Palestine
Liberation Organisation.
Israel, while willing to talk to Arab states directly, has opposed an
international conference or any discussions involving the PLO. Saudi Arabia
and other Gulf states are unwilling to participate in the initial stages of
any conference, while Syria has said it would only join talks sponsored by
the United Nations.
In Moscow Mr Mitterrand said he would campaign in his own country and the
international community for as much assistance as possible to 'help
President Gorbachev and perestroika'.
Shevardnadze aid call, Page 2
</TEXT>
