<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Economists foresee autumn poll: FT survey suggests declining
prospects for government next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC conditions could box the government into an October general
election, after the Tories' performance in last week's local government
elections in effect ruled out a snap June poll, economists warn today.
Next month the economy will be still stuck in recession with annual
inflation running at about 6 per cent. Although it will fall to about 4 per
cent by the end of this year, by early 1992 it will have started to climb
again, the economists predict. Interest rates will have stopped falling and
the trade gap begun to widen, they add.
With unemployment expected to average 2.6m next year and set to continue
rising well into 1993, the Tories are likely to preside over an increase in
public borrowing to at least Pounds 12.2bn next year from a forecast Pounds
8.8bn in the 1991-92 financial year.
If the government wants to avoid going to the polls against either of these
poor economic backcloths, it will have to capitalise on the low interest
rates and inflation likely in October.
These conclusions emerge from today's Financial Times spring survey of
economic forecasts from 21 leading academic economists, City institutions
and private-sector financial groups.
It discloses increasing anxiety about the strength of the recovery which Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, has said is 'round the corner'.
Over the weekend, the Institute of Directors and the 3i investment capital
group reported a significant rise in business optimism over the past two
months. The independent forecasters, however, are convinced that the
recovery will be much less rapid than the descent into recession last year,
and fragile and weak at best when it starts around the third quarter of this
year.
The consensus among the 21 forecasters suggests a turnaround in gross
domestic product from a 1.6 per cent drop this year to growth of around 2
per cent next year. But this will be insufficient to stem sharp rises in
unemployment. Manufacturing output is projected to fall by 4.6 per cent this
year and the current account deficit to grow from Pounds 6.3bn in 1991 to
Pounds 7.3bn next year.
Recent interest rate cuts will not be as effective as in previous
recessions, because companies will use cheaper borrowing to repair balance
sheets rather than invest in new plant, machinery or labour.
Economists fear that the recovery will not be sustained. Worries centre on
the government's reliance on growth in real incomes and consumer spending to
pull the economy out of recession, rather than structural improvements to
manufacturing industry.
Rising demand pressures - and technical factors associated with the
compilation of the retail prices index - are predicted to cause inflation to
rise to 4.3 per cent by the end of next year, after falling to 3.6 per cent
this autumn.
Some economists fear for sterling's stability in the wake of the local
government elections. The political uncertainty will mount, 'weakening
sterling and hence limiting the authorities' ability to cut base rates and
even, conceivably, forcing them to increase rates', warns Mr Roger Bootle,
of Greenwell Montagu.
Rapid descent into recession, Page 9
</TEXT>
