<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Ban urged on mortgage service tie-in
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LAW Society has called on the government to impose a market-wide ban on
the tying-in of financial services to residential property loans, writes
Robert Rice.
The society says a ban would promote competition between financial
institutions, which from next year will be able to provide conveyancing
services to their borrowers, and protect consumers by offering them a choice
in selecting the services needed to buy or sell a house.
The government proposes, under the Courts and Legal Services Act 1990, to
allow the tying-in of services provided consumers are given written
cautions.
The society says this 'half-hearted approach' gives consumers no clear
rights to buy mortgage, insurance, estate agency and conveyancing services
from separate providers at separately identified prices.
</TEXT>
