<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Companies shown to be ignorant of EC market rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST OF the UK's top companies have a poor knowledge of European Community
competition law, according to market research carried out for Theodore
Goddard, a leading City law firm.
Only 4 per cent of UK companies knew that the EC could impose a fine of up
to 10 per cent of a company's turnover for contravening competition laws,
compared with 28 per cent of their French counterparts, the study showed.
The survey covered 50 leading companies in the UK and France with a minimum
turnover of Pounds 70m and a similar number of advisers including lawyers,
accountants and bankers.
Yet 84 per cent of the companies had been involved in a cross-border merger,
acquisition, joint venture or trade agreement in the EC in the past three
years. Almost all expected to be involved in such activity within the next
five years. All the French companies had recent experience of cross-border
activity.
Overall, 84 per cent of the companies thought that their understanding of
national competition law was 'fairly good'.
Even so, 64 per cent of the UK companies admitted a 'fairly poor' or 'very
poor' knowledge of EC competition law. The comparable figure for French
companies was only 8 per cent.
The research concluded that 36 per cent of UK companies failed to take
account of national competition laws and 64 per cent failed to take account
of EC competition laws to achieve strategic goals.
UK companies adopt a reactive approach to competition issues, it said, only
showing an interest when problems arise.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
