<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): Teaching unions closer to merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO OF the smaller non-striking teachers' unions took a step towards merger
over the weekend. If the merger succeeds, the National Union of Teachers may
soon cease to be the largest teachers' union.
The 130,000-strong Assistant Masters and Mistresses Association and the
Professional Association of Teachers, with 39,000 members, have reached
provisional agreement on merger and final proposals are likely to be put to
members by next year.
Neither union is affiliated to the Trades Union Congress. The merged union
would be larger than the National Association of Schoolmasters/Union of
Women Teachers (Nasuwt), with 20,000 members fewer than the NUT's 190,000.
In a joint statement, the two unions emphasised the need for a new, moderate
and professional image for the teaching profession. Mr Peter Dawson, PAT
general secretary, said the union would speak for the 'moderate majority'
and mark 'a new beginning for the education service'.
The new union would 'concentrate on representing the professional and
educational interests of practising teachers and lecturers'.
The merger terms involve the PAT giving up its no-strike constitution in
return for a commitment to 'respect and safeguard' those opposed in
principle to any industrial action.
Mr Peter Smith, AMMA general secretary, said: 'We still have a lot of work
ahead, but we are seemingly on course to create a genuinely democratic union
which will represent the authentic voice of practising teachers and raise
their professional esteem.'
If established, the new union would further increase the isolation of the
NUT. The NUT is the only teachers' union opposed to the setting up of a pay
review body for teachers. Last month the NUT conference voted to boycott the
government's standard assessment tests, a move overwhelmingly rejected in a
ballot of members last week.
NUT membership has been falling steadily, from 250,000 in the mid 1980s.
Combined AMMA/PAT membership has risen from 115,000 to nearly 170,000 today.
Nasuwt membership is stable.
</TEXT>
