<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): BP Exploration staff to assess
managers' work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BP EXPLORATION, the oil and gas drilling company, has begun to assess
managers according to the views of the staff working for them. Such 'upward
appraisal' of managers will eventually become one of the factors in setting
their pay.
Staff have been asked to fill in detailed questionnaires on their managers'
performance, rating them on a scale of one to five under several headings.
The scheme is one of the first in Britain allowing staff to assess managers.
The appraisals are in their first year of operation. They are not yet linked
to the pay of BP Exploration's 2,000 managers and supervisors but the
company believes they will be.
The 'upward feedback' scheme is unusual because most appraisal systems
operate downwards. Mr Doug Webb, the company's human resources manager, said
he knew of only five or six organisations in the world operating such a
system.
In Britain, W. H. Smith Retail introduced a pilot upward assessment scheme
last year. International Business Machines also asks employees about their
managers as part of a wider staff attitudes survey, although the results do
not feed formally into the appraisal system.
Experimentation with appraisal at BP Exploration is part of sweeping changes
in performance management in the BP group. Attempts are under way to
introduce a set of 'essential behaviours' such as innovative thinking and
team building throughout the group.
The company's new scheme, to run from October each year, uses the external
London-based consultancy Forum Europe. Staff are given questionnaires
listing 23 different management 'practices' which they are asked to rank on
a scale of one to five.
Examples of practices are: 'accurately representing the views, opinions and
feelings of staff up the line'; 'willingness to share power in the interest
of common goals'; and 'maintaining high standards for the unit's work'.
Staff are then asked to rate, on the same scale, how well their managers or
supervisors have applied them. The same rating process is applied to BP's
overall list of 'essential behaviours'. Individual responses are
confidential and results are aggregated by the outside consultants, who then
go through the findings with each manager.
Meetings are set up between managers and staff to help the manager to
develop an action plan for improvement. The action plan is then discussed
with the manager's boss and can be incorporated into objectives for the
coming year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
