<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): Performance pay bonus for postal
managers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROYAL MAIL is to pay senior managers bonuses worth up to Pounds 20,000
if they meet new efficiency, profit and individual targets.
The inducements are aimed at putting the Post Office on a footing akin to
that in the private sector by introducing 'a strong business culture' into
the state-owned corporation.
Managers taking charge of the nine independent business centres, replacing
the old 64 divisional districts early next year, will be offered bonuses
worth up to a quarter of their salaries, which are expected mainly to range
from Pounds 45,000 to Pounds 60,000.
Mr Bill Cockburn, Royal Mail managing director, re-fused to say whether
there would be penalties for those who failed to meet the targets. He said:
'If they are not successful, there are a whole range of things we can employ
to make them successful.'
Managers of the new business centres, organised in geographical areas, will
be in charge of their own pay bargaining, quality of service and
profit-and-loss accounts. They will also be expected to generate initiatives
aimed at boosting profits and turnover.
Mr Cockburn said: 'They will have much more freedom to think up their own
ideas on how to generate additional profits. They will be judged on specific
individual targets related to their personal performance.'
That might lead to fierce competition between managers in different areas.
If the manager in charge of Scotland, for example, initiates a scheme that
increases productivity, other managers will be under pressure to trump it
with an idea of their own.
In a separate move, the Post Office has established a joint body with the
Mail Users' Association, a pressure group that claims to represent
businesses with postal bills totalling Pounds 40m a year.
The Postal Forum is aiming to improve postal services.
</TEXT>
