<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): AEU chief questions Labour's pay
policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTROVERSY over Labour's pay policy re-emerged yesterday when a leader of
the AEU engineering union cast doubt on whether Labour could 'square the
circle' of a national minimum wage and higher pay for skilled workers.
Mr Gavin Laird, AEU general secretary, said a Labour government might not be
able to introduce a national minimum wage unless there was sustained
economic growth because it would have to compress pay differentials to do
so.
Mr Laird's remarks came after the AEU supported a TUC policy endorsing free
collective bargaining as well as a national minimum wage. A TUC policy
document was amended after controversy over pay differentials.
The document now says: 'Any exceptional increase given solely for the
purpose of implementing the provisions of statutory minimum pay legislation
will not be regarded by trade unions as a vehicle for general increases.'
Mr Laird said there would have to be increased generation of wealth through
growth in manufacturing to make the policy work. 'If that is not done, you
can forget about the national minimum wage,' he said.
Mr Laird wrote in the AEU Journal before the TUC document was revised that
for employees in engineering and manufacturing 'pay norms and incomes
policies can be of no relevance'.
He argued that to fund a national minimum wage the government would have to
deliver a substantial improvement in the quality and quantity of training
and give manufacturing industry the same incentives to investment as in
Japan and Germany.
Although TUC leaders agreed unanimously on the revised policy which will be
debated at the Trades Union Congress in September, there has since been
continued evidence of the internal strain caused by the question.
</TEXT>
