<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Businessmen report revival of confidence in economy and
prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH businessmen are more optimistic about future economic trends,
according to two surveys.
A poll of 300 members published today by the Institute of Directors points
to a sharp rise in confidence about the economy and their own companies'
prospects over the past two months. A survey of clients by 3i, the
investment capital group, found a marked reduction in pessimism about the
general business climate since January, with 56 per cent of those polled
believing the recession will be over within six months.
Both surveys have to carry statistical 'health warnings', however.
The latest IoD survey is not strictly comparable with the previous poll of
directors in February because of changes in the size and method of sampling.
The IoD said the changes in attitude disclosed were sufficiently large to
indicate 'a substantial shift in optimism.'
The 3i survey was based on 392 replies to questionnaires sent to a random
sample of 1,000 of the company's clients last month. The group says they
tend to be more profitable, more likely to be exporters and growing faster
than the average UK company.
The IoD survey, carried out in the first two weeks of April, found that 53
per cent of the 300 directors polled were more optimistic about the UK
economy than six months ago, and only 20 per cent were less optimistic. In
February, at the time of the institute's last poll, only 8 per cent of
directors expressed more hope about the economy, while 72 per were less
optimistic than six months before.
A similar recovery in confidence was found at company level, especially in
the Midlands and the south. Last month 56 per cent of directors were more
optimistic about their company's outlook than six months before, against
only 18 per cent in February. Those saying they were less optimistic fell to
19 per cent from 54 per cent in February.
Nevertheless, those improvements in sentiment have yet to be reflected in
company performance. The IoD survey found a fairly even split between the 40
per cent of directors reporting a drop in business volume over the previous
six months and 37 per cent reporting an improvement. No less than 49 per
cent of the sample said profits were down in the six months compared with
the same period a year before.
The picture for investment and employment was also mixed. While 62 per cent
of directors expected unchanged employment levels, a strong minority of
larger companies planned job cuts.
</TEXT>
