<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Council tax bill forecasts seen as too optimistic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE first council tax bills in 1993 are likely to be up to nearly Pounds 70
higher than the government has forecast, according to a report published
today by the Local Government Information Unit.
The report by the research unit - which is backed by Labour-controlled
councils and nine public-sector trade unions - claims that the government's
council tax projections assume full collection of the poll tax in its final
year.
In reality, the report says, councils will have to set higher council taxes
to make up for the shortfall caused by the rise in non-collection of the
poll tax. The announcement of the abolition of the tax will encourage more
people not to pay it, the unit argues.
Assuming a poll tax non-collection rate of 5 per cent - 'a conservative
estimate', according to the report - the council tax on properties in the
middle tax band in Langbaurgh, Cleveland, would be Pounds 41 higher than
forecast. Those in the lowest band would pay Pounds 27 more, and those in
the highest Pounds 68.
In Solihull, West Midlands, properties in the middle band would pay Pounds
22 more than predicted, those in the lowest band Pounds 15, and in the top
band Pounds 40 more.
Even in Lewisham, south London, which shows the lowest rises of nine sample
councils examined in the report, properties in the middle band would pay
Pounds 12 more, compared with Pounds 8 in the lowest band and Pounds 20 in
the highest.
Mr Michael Carr, leader of Middlesbrough District Council and chair of the
LGIU, commented: 'As with the poll tax, the government has got in a muddle
with its sums. Its poll tax predictions were consistently wrong because it
failed to base them on realistic assumptions. The same thing is happening
with the council tax because ministers have rushed out incomplete and poorly
thought-out proposals.'
</TEXT>
