<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / The improved competitiveness of the US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS and JILL LEYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STAGNANT state of the US economy has been uppermost in the minds of US
economic policy-makers in recent months - but not all the recent economic
news has been bad. The US current account deficit has shrunk over the past
year - to 1.8 per cent of gross national product in 1990 from 3.6 per cent
in 1986 - easing fears that US companies can no longer compete effectively
on world markets.
The driving force behind the fall in the US deficit, and the contraction of
the Japanese and German current account surpluses, is illustrated in the
chart below. The international price competitiveness of US goods in world
markets, measured by the US real exchange rate, has improved markedly over
the past five years. This remains true despite the dollar's recent
appreciation.
These and other trends in inflation, earnings and competitiveness in the
world's six largest industrial countries are apparent in this week's fifth
and final table in the FT's new series of international economic indicators.
The most widely used indicator of inflation in all economies is the annual
percentage increase in an index of consumer prices. This index measures
changes in the prices of a basket of goods and services bought by an average
consumer in each country.
While inflation is on a downward path in the US and UK, the reason for the
Bank of Japan's nervousness over inflation is clear. The annual rate of
inflation in Japan has increased from 2.7 per cent in the first quarter of
1990 to 3.7 per cent in February. In west Germany, by contrast, inflation
has eased, despite the Bundesbank's fears about inflation.
The rate of producer or 'factory gate' price inflation may provide a more
reliable guide to underlying inflationary pressures. As consumer price
indices often include indirect taxes or mortgage interest costs, a tighter
fiscal or monetary policy, designed to reduce inflation, tends to increase
consumer price inflation in the short-term.
In the UK, for example, retail price inflation has fallen sharply since
November of last year, owing to falls in mortgage interest rates and petrol
prices. Yet the rate of producer price inflation has risen over the same
period.
With the growth rate of average earnings stuck around 9 per cent, UK
manufacturers appear to have been trying to pass increased wage costs on to
consumers, despite depressed consumer demand.
The fall of 0.7 percentage points in the annual increase in the earnings
index since its peak last July results largely from a reduction in overtime
working.
Movements in the real purchasing power of wages in different countries can
only be assessed by looking at the earnings and consumer price indices
together. Nominal earnings in the US rose by 14 per cent between 1985 and
1990, for example, but consumer prices rose by 21.5 per cent. As a result
average real earnings in the US fell by 6.2 per cent in real terms, but they
grew by 10.7 per cent in Japan and 14.9 per cent in west Germany over the
same period.
While both real wages and average earnings have grown faster in Japan than
in the US since 1985 the average domestic cost of labour per unit of output
has remained roughly constant in both countries. The reason for this is that
the average productivity of Japanese workers has grown faster than that of
US workers. Meanwhile, domestic unit labour costs in west Germany have risen
by 10 per cent since 1985.
Relative growth of unit labour costs between countries are an indicator of
the competitiveness of industries producing internationally traded goods. If
a country's nominal exchange rate is fixed but unit labour costs in the
production of traded goods rise faster than those abroad, its goods will
become less competitive on world markets. Equally, if the domestic unit
labour costs in the production of traded goods rise at the same rate as
those abroad, a rise in the country's nominal exchange rate will have the
same effect: the production of exports and substitutes for imports becomes
less profitable and trade performance deteriorates.
The real exchange rate series in the table combines these two determinants
of price competitiveness - changes in nominal exchange rates and in relative
unit labour costs. A rise in the real exchange rate indicates a fall in
competitiveness.
The depreciation of the US real exchange rate since 1985 is the product of
these two effects - the depreciation in the dollar exchange rate since its
1985 peak and the lower rate of inflation of US unit labour costs in dollars
than of European labour costs in European currencies. Together these explain
the encouraging performance of US export volumes in recent years and have
contributed to the contraction of the US current account deficit.
The FT has already published the following tables: National Accounts (April
8), Balance of Payments (April 15), Money and Finance (April 22) and
Production and Employment (29 April). Back issues can be obtained by writing
to the Back Issues Department at the FT or by telephoning 071-873-4683/4
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC INDICATORS: PRICES AND COMPETITIVENESS Yearly figures
are shown in index form with the common base year of 1985. The real exchange
rate is an index throughout, other quarterly and monthly figures show the
percentage change over the corresponding period in the previous year and are
positive unless otherwise stated.
