<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Legal challenge to east German newspaper sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A DM850m (Pounds 290.1m) privatisation deal ran into difficulty yesterday as
the German opposition Social Democratic party (SPD) announced a legal
challenge to last month's sale of east German newspapers to western press
groups.
Mr Hans-Ulrich Klose, SPD party treasurer, accused the Treuhand, the Bonn
government's industrial holding company, of acting illegally in deciding the
sale of 10 former Communist newspapers in the biggest east German
privatisation to date.
The SPD is pressing an ownership claim to at least seven of the newspapers,
based in regional towns around east Germany, on the grounds that they
belonged to the party before its property was confiscated by the Nazis in
1933.
Mr Klose said a Berlin administrative court might decide as early as next
week whether to grant the SPD's request for an injunction to delay the
transaction.
Purchasers of the daily newspapers include west Germany's largest press
groups, ranging from Springer, which publishes Bild and Die Welt, and
Grunerand Jahr to the Burda and Bauer companies.
Mr Klose said the SPD was not seeking to regain full ownership rights but
wanted an economic stake in the newspapers. The party would also be prepared
to negotiate compensation.
The SPD is also complaining about separate sales last year of daily
newspapers in Chemnitz and Halle to west German publishing concerns friendly
to Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Mr Hans-Dietrich Genscher, foreign minister.
The SPD charges that the two politicians used their influence to steer
through the sales rather than putting them up for general bidders in the
manner of last month's transactions.
The Bundesbank yesterday warned that Germany's inflation rate could approach
4 per cent by the end of the year, in the wake of a landmark 7 per cent pay
deal in the metal-working industry reached at the weekend.
Mr Lothar Muller, president of the Bavarian regional central bank and a
member of the Bundesbank's policy-making council, ruled out interest rate
cuts in coming months as a result of the 'stiff breeze' blowing on the
inflation front.
Mr Muller said the annual rate of price increases was likely to rise to 3.5
to 4 per cent by the end of the year, fuelled by tax increases as well as by
latest wage settlements. This compares with the present rate of 2.5 per
cent.
The weekend pay deal, coming after a week of warning strikes organised by
the IG Metall trade union, was reached for 700,000 workers in the
pace-setting North Wurttemberg-North Baden region in south-west Germany.
Made up of a 6.7 per cent rise plus other top-up payments, the accord is
likely to become the norm for nearly 4m west German metal industry workers.
The agreement is also expected to be adopted for 1m east German
metal-workers.
</TEXT>
