<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / EBRD draws up list of its priorities in east Europe: Bank to
focus on privatisation and restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE newly established European Bank for Reconstruction and Development will
play a selective role in helping the countries of eastern and central Europe
adopt market economies and will focus its efforts initially on such areas as
privatisation and economic restructuring.
In a first statement of the bank's priorities and policies, the EBRD said it
would concentrate on developing 'an entrepreneurial spirit at grass roots
level by helping the establishment of small enterprises'. It will support
their development by promoting a new financial infrastructure in the former
communist countries that could one day include a network of merchant banks
spanning the region.
The bank, which formally began operations last month, will seek a close
advisory relationship with the governments in central and eastern Europe and
will not hesitate to express its views to them on their political and
economic reforms. Senior bank officials have said that the EBRD intends that
its offices in eastern and central Europe should become the prime sources of
on-the-spot advice for governments in the region.
However, the bank admits that it will not be able to take a leading role in
all areas of activity. 'It expects to respond to country needs progressively
in a manner that is commensurate with the growth of its own experience and
expertise,' the document said. Especially in the early days, it will
co-operate and co-finance projects with other multilateral institutions such
as the World Bank and European Investment Bank.
The document goes some way to fleshing out the aims of the bank, which
remains a controversial institution under its mercurial president Mr Jacques
Attali despite declarations of support from member governments. Whereas Mr
Attali refers frequently to his 'vision' of the bank as the first
'pan-European institution' to bind together the eastern and western halves
of the European continent, the policy statement focuses on more mundane
issues.
However, the EBRD appears at one point to express reservations about the
current belief among western governments that eastern Europe must take rapid
and radical steps towards the market economy.
The statement was approved by the bank's 23 strong board of directors, who
represent the 39 countries and two European Community institutions that are
subscribing the EBRD's Ecu10bn (Pounds 6.95bn) capital. It says the bank
will place initial emphasis on programmes and activities that support:
the creation and strengthening of infrastructure, including regulatory
infrastructure and improved energy, transport, and telecommunications;
privatisation;
reform of the financial sector, including development of capital markets and
privatisation of commercial banks;
development of a productive, competitive private sector, including small and
medium-sized companies in industry, agriculture and services;
restructuring the region's industrial sectors to put them on a competitive
footing;
encouraging foreign direct investment, and
cleaning up the environment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
