<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Shevardnadze calls for western aid to avert 'catastrophe'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOVIET economic reform requires technical and financial assistance from the
west if it is to succeed, Mr Eduard Shevardnadze, the former Soviet foreign
minister, urged yesterday.
His plea was made during a speech to the Brookings Institution in Washington
before he saw President George Bush and Mr James Baker, the US secretary of
state, with whom he developed a close working relationship until his
resignation last year.
The US is opposed to direct economic assistance to the Soviet Union at
present, in view of its deteriorating economic condition and political
uncertainties. Mr Bush has not taken a decision on a Soviet request for a
further Dollars 1.5bn (Pounds 880m) in US export credit guarantees to
finance purchases of American corn, wheat and soyabeans, though many
officials doubt whether approval should be given.
Mr Shevardnadze said yesterday these credits were 'a very acute issue' for
the Soviet Union. He said the decision 'will to a large extent determine the
fate of reform and democracy in the Soviet Union. We have very little time.'
He argued that the Soviet Union could 'not avoid getting assistance from the
outside. This is not supposed to be a form of charitable assistance, but
rather technological, intellectual and financial assistance on very
favourable terms.'
He said mistakes were being corrected and it was important 'to strengthen
the new tendencies which are emerging and head for cardinal reforms, for the
implementation of the laws which have already been adopted calling for the
transition to a market economy.'
Mr Shevardnadze warned that if these reforms were stifled there was not
simply a risk of material loss but also 'a return of our country to the past
would be a catastrophe.'
He repeated earlier warnings about the threat of dictatorship which might
emerge from a situation of chaos. This danger was 'very severe' during the
autumn and winter, but every day the threat of such a development became
less.
Soviet migration law, Page 4
</TEXT>
