<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / US to reopen Gatt dispute over Airbus state subsidy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEATTLE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US plans to file a second and much broader complaint in the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) against European government support
for Airbus aircraft programmes.
Washington has already taken the European consortium before the Gatt
subsidies committee on the issue of Bonn's exchange rate support for
Daimler-Benz, the German partner in Airbus.
It plans to file a much broader complaint against direct subsidies for
development and production costs. It is also considering taking unilateral
action against Airbus, including special duties and quotas on Airbus
aircraft sales in the US market.
'Airbus still continues to distort trade although it now claims to be
operating profitably,' Mr Frank Shrontz, chairman of Boeing, Airbus's main
international competitor, said in an interview in Seattle. 'We feel
subsidies for both development and production are no longer necessary for
Airbus.'
Mr Shrontz said the US aircraft industry was especially concerned by
increasing subsidies for Airbus sales in the US. Airbus granted large loans
last year to Northwest Airlines and America West. Although Boeing also
advances finance to support purchases, it does so out of its own resources,
Mr Shrontz said.
In contrast, a substantial amount of Airbus financing in the US is done with
European government support, he alleged.
Boeing, the world's largest manufacturer of commercial jets, has become
increasingly frustrated by long and unsuccessful efforts between the US
government and the European Commission to negotiate a compromise. Mr Raymond
Waldman, Boeing's director of government affairs, said the US had made a
good offer to the EC to try to settle the dispute last December.
The US is seeking to limit government launch aid for new aircraft programmes
to 25 per cent of their overall development and production costs instead of
45 per cent as proposed by the EC.
Mr Waldman said the US had agreed on a 45 per cent ceiling for a three-year
transition period provided the Europeans accepted the 25 per cent limit
after that.
'At Boeing, we did not like the compromise because it was an open invitation
for European governments to throw money at Airbus during the transition
period,' he said. But the European Council of ministers rejected the
compromise and changed some of the working assumptions, according to Mr
Waldman.
The original plan was for launch aid restrictions to apply to all aircraft
of 100 seats or more. The EC said the new limits should cover only 140 seats
and over. The US suspected the Continued on Page 20
EC of trying to support European plans to develop new 100- to 130-seat
regional jets.
Germany, France and Italy are considering a new Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.1bn)
regional jet programme. British Aerospace and Fokker of the Netherlands also
have plans to build a larger, 130-seat version of their BAe 146 and
Fokker-100 jets respectively.
On the German government's exchange rate support scheme for Daimler-Benz, Mr
Waldman claimed it was equal to a Dollars 2.5m subsidy for each Airbus
aircraft produced last year.
Although Boeing claimed Airbus was selling aircraft below cost in the US
market, Mr Waldman said Boeing was pressing the US government to concentrate
at this stage on the general issue of direct launch aid subsidies.
Mr Jean Pierson, the Airbus managing director, warned last month that the EC
would use 'every legal weapon' to defend the interests of the consortium. He
claimed that Boeing and McDonnell Douglas had received between them over the
past decade about Dollars 23bn in indirect support from the US government.
Washington says Airbus has received direct subsidies totalling Dollars
25.9bn.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
