<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDAC1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Survey of South Africa (11): 'A hand on the tiller for a
long time' - Patti Waldmeir and Michael Holman speak to President F. W. de
Klerk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARE you encouraged by the outline of constitutional principles put forward
by the ANC? What do you have in common and where are there potential
differences?
Areas of potential difference are definitely there, but there are some
interesting facets in their proposals (and) there are many areas of
agreement on certain basic principles. Areas of difference focus on the
(ANC) philosophy of very strong central government, as opposed to the
concept of decentralisation of power, and absence of adequate provision for
checks and balances to handle the problems arising from the diversity of
South Africa's society. There is no doubt that a broad consensus now exists,
that apart from a new constitution, there must also be a bill of rights, and
that individual rights - we also put heavy emphasis, for example, on the
protection of private property ownership - to a great extent can best be
protected in a bill of rights.
Even collective rights, in the religious field, in the cultural field, can
be dealt with in a bill of rights (but) I don't think one can write policy
into a constitution. You can write fundamentals into a constitution, you can
write rules into a constitution, but you cannot write economic policy or
social policy into a constitution. And inasmuch as their programme tries to
do that, I don't think it is acceptable.
On the issue of power sharing, do you feel that the principle of
proportional representation should apply to the executive?
Yes, the National Party has publicly stated that is its view. The Swiss
model provides an interesting model, where the main role players are
represented in the executive and where the executive operates on the basis
of consensus. (Our) fundamental departure point is that a winner-takes-all
constitution is very wrong for South Africa, it cannot work. I'm also on
record as saying that there should not be a State President with so much
power as I have.
How well do you think the National Party might do in an election, and what
kind of coalition might be formed?
I think firstly that the National Party itself definitely has the potential
to attract wide support across colour lines. But I also believe we must
bring together those who share the same principles . . . but we're not
pressing now for alliances . . . any impression of ganging up at this stage
will threaten the negotiation process itself.
But I have no doubt that when the real electoral process is in the offing,
alliances will be formed, and that there will be a moderate alliance in
which the National Party will play an important part, which has more than an
even chance to win an election.
Would you consider Chief Buthelezi's Inkatha Freedom Party a natural partner
in that alliance?
It's quite possible that the Inkatha Freedom Party and the National Party
can move into an alliance, but I don't think they will be alone if the two
of them decide to do so. The only definite statement which I have made is
that I can't see us in alliance with the ANC, as long as the ANC is in
alliance with the South African Communist Party, because the National Party
is strongly opposed to communism.
Is the National Party becoming over-confident? And is it taking seriously
enough the degree to which violence is undermining Mr Mandela's authority?
We are definitely not over-confident. The leadership of the party is deeply
aware of the risks involved, of the fact that we are dealing with something
which is fragile, of the dangers of continued violence as a factor not only
undermining the ANC, but undermining stability.
We are constantly involved in further planning to prevent violence and where
it occurs, for impartial handling of violence. Individual members of police
forces across the world sometimes make bad errors of judgement. But there is
definitely no pattern . . . Police are there to safeguard the lives and
property of all South Africans. Cannot more be done?
Let's just look at it from another vantage point, Mr Mandela also says he's
against violence. Have you seen some of his supporters participating in
violence? In our case it's the exception, in his case it's the rule. The
real perpetrators of violence, in the overwhelming number of cases, are the
supporters of either the ANC or some other party. The funny thing is that
the common denominator is that on one side you will always find ANC
supporters.
The government's recent White Paper on Land Reform took a strong line on the
restitution of land to those forcibly evicted under apartheid . . .
The White Paper states that a programme for the restoration of land would
not be feasible. That does not meant government is unapproachable.
Government's general approach to this issue is to address the cases
concerned with sympathy and reason What is the next step in the negotiating
process?
We envisage a multi-party conference. Its aim is to reach consensus on
underlying principles for a new constitution, as well as on the structure
and functioning of a forum for constitutional negotiations.
If consensus was reached on the principles of a new constitution, could this
be put to a larger body, going some way towards meeting the demands of the
ANC that the constitution be drawn up by this constituent assembly?
As I say, the conference's aim is to reach consensus on underlying
principles as well as on the structure and functioning of a forum for
constitutional negotiations. Almost at the top of the agenda will be - if
and when we agree on basic principles - how do we formalise this? What is in
a name? The ANC will no doubt say, let's have a constituent assembly in
terms of their proposal. We don't agree with the concept of a constituent
assembly, but we are prepared to give structure and formality to such a
forum.
But the one principle over which we feel very strongly is that . . . we
cannot create a constitutional vacuum in the sense of abdicating power to an
interim government, or a constituent assembly, or a negotiating forum. In
the final analysis, a new constitution will have to be passed by parliament,
as an act of parliament, and by parliament as it is.
Instead of using the term interim government, is it conceivable that the
consultative process could take on a more formal structure, so that there
might be a consultative body on education, on health, and so on?
That type of thing is not out of the question and if agreement is reached on
such a general approach I have nothing in principle against it. While
rejecting an interim government, we accept that there must be certain
transition arrangements.
What are your thoughts on the concept of affirmative action?
If affirmative action is to mean retribution, restoration, taking away from
those who have, dishing it out, I'm absolutely against it. But I'm fully in
favour of specific strategies to improve the quality of life of all South
Africans, to wipe out backlogs, to improve education, to in a dramatic
manner broaden the base of private home ownership, we're already doing all
those things. Human development is the major challenge of the future, not
constitution-making . . . I don't think one should ever, however, relinquish
the principle of merit just for the sake of numbers. I'm not in favour of
racism in any form.
How concerned are you about the right wing, the Conservative Party?
You earlier referred to over-confidence. About one thing I am confident: I
will win a referendum among whites. With regard to the extra-parliamentary
threat, I am not unduly concerned, but I think that might become a very
serious threat if we were not to succeed in offering to the public of South
Africa a well-balanced constitution with proper checks and balances. In
terms of power sharing, can you foresee any time when the National Party
will not have at least one hand on the tiller?
In essence a political party exists because it believes in its policy. And
the main goal of a political party is to be a winner at the polls. I believe
the National Party, because of its very capacity to adapt to realities, is a
young and dynamic party at this moment, although it has a long history. And
that it will play a leading role - not in a dominating sense, but an
important, fundamental role in government for as long as it retains its
character of thinking along lines of principle, and of not being
opportunistic, of having an open mind, and of constantly submitting itself
to the question whether it needs to adapt and reform within the framework of
its principles. I therefore think that because of its inherent strength, it
will have one hand on the tiller for a very long time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI Photograph Mr de Klerk, Human development is the challenge,
not constitution-making (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1296</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Survey of South Africa (12): On the road to 'normalisation'
 -Michael Holman on international relations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICA'S changing status in the international arena was vividly
illustrated last month by the experiences of President F. W. de Klerk and
Nelson Mandela, the ANC deputy-president, during their briefly overlapping
visits to London.
At meetings of leading businessmen and before a packed press conference, the
South African president - en route to Denmark and Ireland - confidently
outlined his vision of a 'new South Africa', and pressed the case for a
rapid end to remaining sanctions.
By contrast, Mr Mandela, speaking to journalists in the same hall that last
year saw a triumphant appearance during his first official visit to Britain,
seemed a subdued figure.
Sanctions had to stay, he argued, adding that he was opposed to the visit to
South Africa later this year by Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign
secretary. But his case lacked conviction.
In his heart Mr Mandela must surely have conceded what many of his senior
officials now acknowledge privately: sanctions are crumbling, and the
barriers to political, cultural, academic and sporting contact with Pretoria
are falling. The combination of reform at home and revolutions abroad is
making the process irreversible.
In the eyes of most outsiders - including an increasing number of African
states - Mr de Klerk has demonstrated his reformist credentials. And the
once reliable rear-bases for the ANC - the Soviet Union and its eastern bloc
allies - have been among the first to establish links with post-apartheid
Pretoria as they undergo radical reforms of their own.
For Mr Neil van Heerden, director-general of the foreign affairs ministry,
who played a key role in Namibian independence negotiations early last year,
the developments have opened new horizons. Today's objectives were once
unattainable: consolidating existing African links and developing new ones,
notably Nigeria; exploring opportunities in Pacific Rim countries;
cautiously assessing the trading potential of eastern Europe; and preparing
for Organisation of African Unity membership.
'Our first priority is to normalise relations with the outside world,' says
Mr van Heerden. Evidence of this 'normalisation' has come thick and fast,
often catching the ANC on the hop. Over the past year Pretoria has opened
trade or 'interest' missions in more than 20 countries as diverse as
Hungary, Togo, Ivory Coast, Mauritius and - later this year - the Soviet
Union.
Mr van Heerden particularly welcomes the fact that relations with the
European Community as a whole have dramatically improved. It seems unlikely
South Africa will be as divisive an issue for the EC as it has been in the
past. Shortly before President de Klerk's arrival in London, the EC ignored
the last-minute objections of a delegation of senior ANC officials, and
lifted its 1986 ban on the import of South African iron, steel and gold
coins. This followed the repeal last year of the EC's voluntary ban on new
investment.
'The decision again shows clearly how Europe allies itself with white South
Africa,' complained Mr Mandela. 'We are the victims, yet they reward the
jailer for letting a little more light into our hell-hole.'
Mr Mandela might well direct his wrath on states much closer to home.
It has long been the case that all but a handful of African states trade
with Pretoria, overtly or covertly: this trade is now flourishing, and South
Africa's diplomats are boasting of contacts which they once made
surreptitiously.
New links are paying off handsomely. According to the South African Foreign
Trade Association (Safto), the value of exports to the rest of Africa rose
40 per cent in 1989, and a further 22 per cent last year, making the market
worth some R5.5bn.
The ANC leader can derive some comfort from the United States, however.
Washington is still applying sanctions, banning imports of agricultural
products, coal, iron, steel, uranium, sugar and gold coins and other items.
It also bans US investment in South Africa, computer exports and direct air
links between the two countries. But the wall is likely to breached later
this year.
Last week Mr Hank Cohen, the assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, told a congressional committee that Pretoria had met three of five
conditions that must be fulfilled to allow the US to lift economic
sanctions: repeal the state of emergency and release detainees held under
it; unban democratic political parties and permit participation of all races
in the political process; and agree to enter good faith negotiations with
the black majority without preconditions.
The two further demands - release of political detainees or repeal of the
racially based Group Areas Act and Population Registration Act - are being
put into practice.
The process of repeal, Mr van Heerden estimates, should 'come to fruition in
the second half of this year'.
He acknowledges that what he calls 'second tier' sanctions - measures
imposed by cities for example, which are not susceptible to executive fiat -
will continue, but expects a gradual erosion.
The platform for any recovery in the South African economy, however, is the
region as a whole, however welcome the resumption of international trading
opportunities. Mr van Heerden stresses the link between a successful outcome
to peace talks in Mozambique and Angola, now under way, and South Africa's
own transition to democracy.
'If we can stop these wars, our part of the continent can take off,' says Mr
van Heerden. 'And our neighbours tell us: 'Whatever you do, don't
self-destruct, because we're depending on you to be the source of
technology, consumer goods, and so on', except the Zimbabwean government,
where President Mugabe still sees South Africa as the enemy, even though our
trading figures are going through the roof]'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
