<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Survey of South Africa (9): A different drought threatens -
Farmers don't shout back like they used to, Philip Gawith is told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE residents of Pretoria, South Africa's capital city, woke one morning
this January to find their city paralysed. An estimated 5,000 white farmers
had brought the city to a standstill by parking an assortment of
agricultural vehicles in city centre intersections.
The farmers were protesting their financial plight and the alleged uncaring
attitude of the government. Mr Kraai van Niekerk, minister of agriculture,
says the protest illustrates the powerlessness farmers feel about their
future.
On top of the perennial climatic variable, particularly hostile in recent
years, farmers are having to deal with enormous political and economic
changes, none of which they feel they have any control over. For a
conservative community, this adds up to a most unsettling package. As Mr van
Niekerk noted: 'Farming in South Africa finds itself in the midst of a
profound crisis that has all the elements of personal tragedy, community
disruption and an uncertainty common to the state of mind which prevailed
during the Great Depression (during the Thirties).'
The chief concern of South Africa's roughly 65,000 farmers is financial.
Most of the 80s were drought years, and the past summer saw rains falling so
late in some areas that many farmers were left without crops. The farmers
have aggravated this adversity with some rank financial folly of their own.
The industry, which contributed R10.8bn (4.6 per cent) to gross domestic
product in 1990, 8 per cent down on 1989, has debts of R16bn.
The debt ratio (debt in relation to assets) deteriorated from 12.8 per cent
in 1979 to 27.9 per cent in 1985. It has since improved to 23.2 per cent in
1990 as growth in the value of farm assets has outstripped growth of the
debt burden. Nevertheless, with real interest rates of above 5 per cent for
more than two years now, anybody with large borrowings has been hurt.
Coupled with this, the farmers' terms of trade (ratio of producer prices to
farm input prices) continue to deteriorate - from 0.87 to 0.82 during 1990.
Field crops and animal husbandry went backwards, but horticultural terms of
trade improved. The price of farming requisites rose by about 12 per cent,
while producer prices of agricultural products rose by 5.4 per cent.
Consumer food prices increased by 16 per cent.
On top of economic hardship comes political insecurity. The government's
decision to abolish the Land Acts, which prevented blacks from owning land
in roughly 87 per cent of the country, has unleashed fears in the white
farming community that they face redistribution of farmland to landless
blacks. These fears have been manipulated by the Conservative Party (CP).
CP criticism of government, however, falls on fallow ground. For reasons
both political (most of the farmers now support the Conservative Party) and
economic (the state is seeking to lessen its role in the economy),
agriculture is no longer the recipient of generous state largesse. Spending
on agriculture in the current budget, R253.7m, forms only 0.3 per cent of
state spending compared to 3.7 per cent as recently as 1987/8. And whereas
R583.4m was spent on subsidies and rebates granted in 1988, this figure was
down to R198m last year.
Farmers, understandably, are unhappy. They were outraged recently when Mr
van Niekerk had the temerity to suggest that as much as R5bn of their debt
was non-agricultural - cars, holiday homes, townhouses and playing the
horses were mentioned. Part of their debt was also the product of bad
decisions - cultivating marginal land, paying too much for land, financing
long-term projects with short-term capital, and so on. Such straight talking
from an agricultural minister is unprecedented, a clear symptom of the
changing times.
Mr van Niekerk believes one way of improving the financial position of
farmers is via a more market-oriented approach to agriculture. This process
is already well under way with reductions in State aid and producer
subsidies, removal of import controls and deregulation of the excessive
state role in areas like marketing, pricing and hygiene. The days of merely
producing, without worrying about signals from the market is over.
Another big issue, which the government claims to be attending to on an
ongoing basis, is the role played by the country's 22 agricultural control
boards, which regulate the marketing of about 80 per cent of the country's
agricultural products. Although many farmers, especially weaker ones, favour
the boards, the trend is towards diluting their influence. Some query
whether they should exist at all. Mr Frans Venter, agricultural adviser to
First National Bank comments: 'Not one of the boards is really adding value
to the product.'
The other way to improve farmers' positions, says Mr van Niekerk, is by
increasing the purchasing power of the consumer. A combination of low growth
and a high population growth rate has seen per capita incomes in the country
recede. The key here lies in the extent to which the government can assist
in getting economic growth started again.
Is the government succeeding in getting the message that the short term
offers no solution, and that the farmers' salvation lies in structural
readjustment, both within agriculture and the wider economy? Mr van Niekerk
thinks so. 'They don't shout back as hard as they used to,' he says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V Chart (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1300</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDACWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Survey of South Africa (7): Testing times for optimism -
Manufacturing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DECADE of stagflation, domestic unrest and international isolation has
done remarkably little damage to the famous optimism of South Africa's
businessmen. The difficulties of transition offer little respite, but they
remain convinced that the 90s can't possibly be as bad as the 80s.
They argue that hard times have forged a lean and resilient business sector.
They also identify the considerable benefits flowing from the country's
readmission to the international arena, and the prospects of regional peace.
Their ability to deliver, however, will be tested as never before in the
years ahead. The country's real gross domestic product per capita has fallen
by an average annual rate of 1.5 per cent since 1981. Nobody doubts the
consequences of that trend persisting, and the responsibility for addressing
it falls largely to business.
The portents are sobering. The average growth rate between 1979 and 1989 was
only 2.14 per cent, compared to 3.02 per cent in the 1970-79 period. By no
means exempt from this was the manufacturing sector. Mr Ted Osborne of the
Nedbank Economic Unit calculates that gross domestic fixed investment in the
sector declined by an average 0.81 per cent per annum over the period
1979-89 - hardly the basis for sustained growth.
This should not be surprising - capital sanctions limited the country to
about 3 per cent growth per annum, otherwise balance of payments problems
ensued. This meant that the authorities had to douse any economic recovery
which threatened to gather steam, the net effect being a massive
disincentive to invest.
When the origins of future growth are discussed, three areas top the list.
First are those who will benefit from the shift in budgetary priorities
towards social spending. Infrastructural upgrading in black areas and the
increased supply of schools and houses should benefit construction and
related sectors.
Next is the 'second world' - those in transition from a Third to a First
World economy - consisting largely of black urban residents. They have
enormous unmet needs.
Finally, there are exports. It is broadly received wisdom that the country
should follow an export-led manufacturing growth path. This coincides with
the economy's shift from being import-replacement oriented to being more
outward-looking. The latest manifestation of this was the report released
last month by the Industrial Development Corporation (IDC) on the
modification of the country's tariff regime. The report notes: 'South
African industry has been stagnating for a long time. The country's future
prosperity will be determined by its ability to play a bigger role in
international trade in industrial goods.' It recommends reduced tariffs,
lower import surcharges and a realistic exchange rate policy as essential
elements in making the existing industrial structure more export
competitive.
Although the cabinet has still to consider the report, the chances of it
being accepted are good, as it is consistent with government economic
thinking. This should bring to an end a long and debilitating doctrinal
dispute about how best government should promote export-led industrial
growth: through focused 'Structural Adjustment Programmes' (SAP), in
industries with perceived comparative advantages, or through a General
Export Incentive Scheme (GEIS), such as is currently in place. The report
favours the former, government having vacillated between the two in recent
years, to the consternation of the country's exporters.
A salutary aspect of the report is the line: 'These findings are supported
by the results of a number of previous official investigations . . .'
Sceptics wonder whether the government will do any better than its
predecessors in implementing the findings. However, government's clear
desire to place the economy on a structurally sound footing before political
transition may provide the necessary impetus.
South Africa's export performance in recent years has been mixed. Commodity
prices, especially gold, but also steel, ferro-alloys and platinum, have
been weak, and this has dampened revenues. What has given cause for cheer,
however, has been the performance of merchandise exports. In the period 1984
to 1990, covering the height of the sanctions era, these rose by an average
annual rate of more than 10 per cent. These trends are reflected in
manufactured exports, increasing from 18 to 29 per cent of total exports
between 1980 and 1989.
In 1990 the country's exports were R60.6bn, 3.1 per cent up on 1989 (up 4.3
per cent in dollars, to Dollars 23.4bn). Mr Wim Holtes, chief executive of
the South African Foreign Trade Organisation, says gold's weakness means the
country will do well to achieve 2 per cent growth this year. He believes the
recovery of world economies in 1992 will see a return to a 5-7 per cent
growth rate.
Mr Holtes says the euphoria surrounding the easing of sanctions and the
opening of new markets needs to be put into context. Remembering that Europe
accounts for more than 50 per cent of South Africa's trade, he suggests the
combination of South Africa's political reforms and 1992 single market
reforms in Europe will be the dominant trade dynamics for the country in
years ahead.
Eastern Europe, where South Africa has established an extensive trade and
diplomatic presence over the past year, has been largely a political and
media event. 'Economically the opportunities have been modest,' says Mr
Holtes.
The breakthrough into Africa has been more substantial. South Africa's trade
with the rest of the continent increased by 40 per cent in 1989, 22 per cent
last year, and currently stands at the level of about R8-9bn a year. The
prospect of South Africa, Mozambique and Angola reaching political
settlements will create positive business synergies for South Africa. Local
businesses have a head-start when it comes to understanding the environment,
and are sure to be participants in the infrastructural development the area
will embark on, as well as in the satisfaction of long neglected consumer
needs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV Chart (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1301</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDACVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Survey of South Africa (6): Gold loses its glitter - Mining
is no longer the bulwark it was
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE declining fortune of the gold mining industry, suffering the worst
crisis in its history, dominates the local mining scene. The recent decision
by Gengold, the gold arm of the Gencor mining house, to close the
Stilfontein mine was both a symbol of hard times and a gloomy portent of the
considerable hardship that lies ahead.
Closing a mine is, ultimately, inevitable. But as Mr Gary Maude, Gengold's
managing director, pointed out, the difference with Stilfontein was that it
was not 'mined out' when closure was announced. It had a large, coherent
body of reef which could profitably have been mined at the real gold price
of five years ago.
Mr Maude predicts, and industry opinion agrees, that Stilfontein is only the
first of a number of such mines which will have to close. The broad figures
bear him out. At a gold price of R933 per ounce*, an estimated 40 per cent
of the country's gold is produced at a loss and 45 per cent of the
industry's labour force, or about 190,000 men, works on mines unable to make
a profit.
The industry is no longer the bulwark of the domestic economy. Tax receipts
from gold fell from 10.7 per cent of state revenue in 1981/2 to 0.9 per cent
in 1990/91 and its contribution to GDP was down to 8.8 per cent in 1990.
Where its influence remains pronounced is on the export front - last year it
accounted for 25 per cent of the country's exports.
however, the industry's troubles have wide ramifications, particularly in
the labour market. Approximately 40,000 workers lost their jobs last year
and that figure is expected to be repeated in 1991. Some see this as a
pretext for state intervention.
The root cause of the industry's difficulties is a relentless cost-price
squeeze. The last three years have seen revenues flat at about R990/oz.
Costs, however, have been rising inexorably at an inflation rate of about 14
per cent per annum. Result? A decline of at least 36 per cent in the real
rate of return over three years.
Producers' attention is obviously focused on what steps can be taken to
remain profitable. The main response has been a much greater focus on mining
where grades are higher, and returns better. Labour has been shed on a vast
scale. In truth, no strategy which might prolong the life of a marginal (low
return) mine has gone unexamined.
A worrying, if inevitable, feature of the present time is the declining
exploration effort. The industry mines about 100m tonnes a year, but new
mines are not being opened to provide the replacement tonnage. Most of South
Africa's better prospects are very deep mines which would cost about R3bn to
start. Analysts reckon the gold price will have to double before such
projects would be viable.
Gold's shrinking importance is shown by the fact that 1989 was the first
year in which profits from mining activities in South Africa, other than
gold, exceeded profits from gold. Also revealing is that in the year to
March 1990, 9.7 per cent of equity accounted earnings at Anglo American, the
country's largest mining house, came from platinum, with gold only slightly
higher at 11.9 per cent.
Although the platinum sector is having to deal with a fairly depressed
price, down from a high in February last year of Dollars 525/oz to around
Dollars 400 now, the price of rhodium - an important by-product of platinum
mining - has quadrupled in two years to current levels of about Dollars
5,300/oz. This is a function of the increasing demand for the metal in car
exhaust catalysts as emissions standards are tightened.
The buoyant price has boosted the profits of South Africa's mines, which
produce about 75 per cent of the world's platinum, although the price of
producing more rhodium is more platinum, a fact that contributes to a
perception of oversupply which puts a cap on the platinum price.
Bolstering this perception is the expansion plans South African producers
have announced which, if implemented, would add a million ounces a year to
the approximately 2.8m ounces the country produced in 1990.
The biggest talking point in the industry at the moment is the future of the
ailing Crocodile River mine, managed by Barmines, the platinum arm of the
Rand Mines group. The mine is estimated to need R350-400m to develop its
underground operations, money which could not be raised easily or cheaply
through a rights issue. Barmines recently held unsuccessful discussions on
the matter with Rustenburg Platinum, the world's largest producer, and has
now moved on to talking to Genmin, the mining arm of Gencor.
The outlook for coal, South Africa's second largest export earner after gold
with revenues of R3.52bn last year, is modest. Demand on the domestic market
is weak as a result of the recession.
The export market offers hope, at least for better prices if not volumes.
With sanctions crumbling, the Dollars 3-5/tonne political discount on South
African coal has started to erode. Contracts with European customers for
1991 included price increases, considered very satisfactory, of 3-8 per
cent. The country had lost about 25 per cent of its export markets in 1986
when major markets like the US, France and Denmark were closed to it.
South Africa will not find returning to these markets easy, as producers
like Colombia and Venezuela have become a force since it left. There are
also infrastructural constraints. More than 90 per cent of the country's
exports go through the Richard's Bay terminal on the east coast, which has a
nominal capacity of 44m tonnes, currently being extended to 53m. Even if
South Africa had more capacity, it is by no means clear world markets could
absorb this and sustain the price.
South Africa is also one of the world's big diamond producers and De Beers,
continues to dominate the world diamond market. Attributable profits dropped
16 per cent down to Dollars 911m in 1990 because of recessionary conditions.
*The real gold price is subject to exchange rate fluctuations as well as
international price swings: R933 would be Dollars 345-360.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
