FT  07 MAY 91 / International Company News: Holderbank to increase share
capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DULLFORCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOLDERBANK, the Swiss cement group, plans an increase in share capital after
posting a 27.6 per cent decline in net consolidated earnings to SFr311m
(Dollars 210m) in 1990. Group turnover rose 5.5 per cent to SFr5.25bn.
Holderbank Financiere Glaris, the parent company, reported a 5.1 per cent
advance to SFr78.9m in 1990 net profit and the board proposes to pay
unchanged dividends of SFr125 per bearer share, SFr25 per registered share
and SFr12.50 per participation certificate.
Shareholders will be offered a rights issue as part of an increase from
SFr231m to SFr280m in the nominal share capital. In a first tranche 46,200
bearer shares with a par value of SFr500 will be offered at a price of
SFr2,500, almost exactly half the price at which the bearer shares traded in
Zurich before the announcement. The allocation will be 1 for 10 for bearer
shares, 1 for 50 for registered shares and 1 for 100 for participation
certificates.
The board will also seek authority to issue at its own discretion a further
51,800 bearer shares without rights attached, of which a limited number
would be earmarked for employees.
The declines in group net profit and cash-flow, down by 8.6 per cent to
SFr869m, in 1990 are steeper than those forecast by Mr Thomas Schmidheiny,
the chairman and managing director, in November.
Negative currency movements reduced group turnover by SFr428m,
newly-acquired companies added SFr410m while internal growth contributed
SFr290m.
Weak construction markets in North America and South Africa, low profit
margins in some newly-acquired companies and unfavourable currency movements
are given as the main reasons for the setback in earnings. In addition,
Holderbank maintained a high level of capital spending.
Investments in property, plant and equipment grew by 13 per cent to SFr641m.
</TEXT>
