FT  07 MAY 91 / International Company News: Devenish makes hostile attack on
Boddington
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J A DEVENISH, the brewery and public house group, has launched a vigorous
assault on Boddington as part of its defence to the Pounds 122.3m hostile
offer from the public house, hotels and healthcare group.
The Devenish document criticises Boddington for its 'misconceived strategy
of diversification' into nursing homes, hotels and restaurants and accuses
it of being 'slow to invest in its own pub division.'
Devenish is sending a letter to Boddington shareholders suggesting seven
questions that they should ask the board at the predator's extraordinary
meeting in Manchester on Friday.
Meanwhile, the document does not include a profits forecast, but says that
between 1986 and 1990 operating profits per Devenish's managed pubs
increased by 70 per cent. It also values Devenish's fully diluted net assets
per share, as of September 30, at 272p, a premium to the Boddington offer
price.
On the subject of its brewery, Devenish says 'management has continued to be
dissatisfied with the returns generated by our brewing business. Firm action
is being taken to resolve this situation and we are actively working to
achieve a solution on a financial basis satisfactory to Devenish.'
The document shows that the directors of Devenish are employed on four year
rolling contracts.
Boddington's offer is 10 of its shares for every seven in Devenish; on the
basis of Friday night's closing Boddington price of 156p, that values each
Devenish share at 223p. There is also a cash alternative of 210p per share.
Boddington is also offering 1,096 of its shares for every 1,000 convertible
preference shares in Devenish, valuing each convertible share at 171p.
</TEXT>
