FT  07 MAY 91 / International Company News: Norton starts internal inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROFITS of a German fasteners company bought by Norton Group, better
known for its motorcycle business, have been paid into court because of an
ownership dispute.
The new management of Norton has launched an internal investigation into
both the German company and a US subsidiary called Pro-Fit, a distributor of
pipe fittings bought in 1988.
Both were acquired as profitable businesses to support the development of
the motorcycles and rotary engines.
Mr Norman Wilson, a new non-executive director of Norton, said the inquiry
was particularly concerned with the Pounds 8.2m German purchase. He
described the situation as a mess.
Earnings were being paid into court and Norton did not even know what it
owned because of the dispute, which was mentioned in the acquisition
document.
The results of the internal inquiry would be handed over to the Department
of Trade and Industry, which launched an investigation into Norton's affairs
in January.
At that time a poorly supported Pounds 6.5m rights issue, related to the FUS
Beteiligungs-und Verwaltungs acquisition, was struggling to a conclusion.
Although shareholders approved the FUS purchase in November, some dissidents
tried to block it.
Part of the controversy was that the vendor of the business was a Channel
Islands trust company set up to benefit the offspring of Mr James Tildesley,
Norton's chairman, who resigned about 10 days ago.
Norton's shares were suspended at 18p on April 1 because of a delay in
publishing its results for the six months to October 31. Mr Wilson said
Pounds 6m was owed to Midland Bank, which was being co-operative.
