<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / International Company News: Decision day for Etam
shareholders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHAREHOLDERS in Etam, the 250-store women's fashion chain, will today decide
whether to accept a tender offer for shares which could lead to a bid
valuing the group at about Pounds 120m.
The offer of up to 185p per share has been made by Oceana Investment
Corporation, a vehicle for the Lewis family which runs the 700-store
Foschini chain in South Africa. Oceana already owns a 6.6 per cent stake and
could take that to 25.1 per cent.
Mr Michael Lewis, a director of Oceana and Foschini, said his organisation
was considering making an offer for the whole group, but wanted to gauge
shareholder opinion at the maximum price of 185p.
The offer is for up to 12.1m shares, 18.5 per cent of the equity, and the
outcome depends on the number of shares tendered. At less than 3.2m, the
offer will be withdrawn; between 3.2m and 12.1m, the shares will be bought
at 185p.
Oversubscription will lead to a striking price: shares tendered below it
will be bought at that price; tenders at the striking level will be scaled
back and those above it will be rejected. Oceana would use this response to
put pressure on the Etam board to come to an agreement.
Some analysts have recommended that shareholders tender because they believe
it will take at least two years for the shares to reach 185p on
fundamentals. The offer price compares with 87p in January and 176p on
Friday, and is 25 times the earnings recently announced for 1990-91.
Gartmore Investment Management, the largest institutional holder, increased
its stake from 11.1 to 12.3 per cent on Friday and is unlikely to tender. Mr
Vivian Balzalgette, a director, said: 'Oceana has highlighted the investment
potential.'
</TEXT>
