</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FLOOD of rights issues from property companies has been blamed by
Bellway, the Tyneside-based housebuilder, for the disappointing response
from shareholders to its own cash call.
The shares were offered last month at 220p on a 5-for-11 basis. But there
was only 52.3 per cent take-up.
Charterhouse Bank placed the rest of the 11.6m shares with institutions at a
slight premium.
The company said it was disappointing that so many shareholders had decided
not to take up their rights.
Construction and property groups, including Higgs and Hill, Costain and
Berkeley, have called for more than Pounds 700m in 11 rights issues.
Mr Alan Robson, finance director, said: 'We have been tarred with the same
brush of other property companies tapping the equity market to reduce their
debt. Unlike many property companies we had no gearing and did not need to
raise the cash.'
Last month Bellway announced pre-tax profits for the six months to January
1991 of Pounds 3.36m (Pounds 6.11m). For the full year it is forecasting
Pounds 8.75m.
