<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDABWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Economics Notebook: Spain prepares for an end to innocence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN'S chronic attachment to high real interest rates is beginning to eat
away at the country's equanimity.
It is under fire from France, which wants to cut its rates but cannot
without breaking out of its European Monetary System limits against the
peseta. Meanwhile, the Spanish Treasury is trying to cut the cost of medium
and long-term debt, but cannot lower yields as much as it wants to.
Finally, in a supposed bid to inject more competition into the inefficient
Spanish banking system, the Government last week agreed to the merger of all
state-owned financial institutions. By becoming the country's biggest banker
the Government hopes to be able to jawbone domestic interest rates lower.
A few weeks ago Mr Pierre Beregovoy, the French Finance Minister, called the
strength of the Spanish currency - which has been trading at the upper limit
of its 6 per cent EMS band against the franc for more than five weeks -
'unnatural'. He said so again at the Group of Seven meeting in Washington
last month. In private the Spanish authorities, frustrated by their
inability to make the economy behave, might even agree.
Two years ago, frightened by rising inflation and apparently unquenchable
consumer demand, Madrid flung its economic levers sharply into reverse.
Import tariffs were lifted early to cheapen consumer goods. Anyone borrowing
cheaply abroad was forced to deposit up to 30 per cent of the loan, interest
free, with the Bank of Spain.
Growth in bank lending was limited, by decree, to 10 per cent after private
credit had grown almost 25 per cent the year before.
Amazingly, these ferocious measures have had little effect, although by the
beginning of 1990 industrial production was falling. The invasion of Kuwait
also helped because it panicked Spaniards into shelving investment
decisions.
But the Gulf crisis, perhaps, ended too early. The government had promised
to begin lifting its credit controls by the beginning of this year and it
has done so. As a result private credit is growing close to 20 per cent
again and the ALP, the broad money supply measure, is growing almost twice
as fast as its target.
Madrid, desperate to demonstrate its ability to control its economy, cut the
official intervention rate by one point at the Bank of Spain's regular CD
auctions in March, to 13.5 per cent.
The Central Bank governor was wheeled out to give a lame explanation. The
forecasts looked good, he said. But the Bank of Spain does not really matter
in this debate. It does what it is told by the Finance Ministry.
The Finance Minister, Mr Carlos Solchaga, has been promising more interest
rate cuts this year but it is easy to misread that message. How does he make
borrowing cheaper without cutting official rates?
One of Mr Solchaga's gripes has been that, although the intervention rate
has been cut, the commercial banks have not been passing the benefits on to
borrowers.
What the banks have been doing is cutting rates on interest-bearing current
accounts launched 18 months ago and which threaten the high retail margins
that have made them some of the most profitable banks in the world.
Hence the creation last Friday of the Corporacion Bancaria Espanola (BCE) -
the aglomeration of the State-controlled Banco Exterior, the big public
lending group, the Instituto de Credito Oficial (ICO), which includes the
biggest mortgage and agricultural lenders in the land, and the Caja Postal,
the post office savings bank.
With combined assets of about Dollars 80bn, it is not only much bigger than
the biggest private bank, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya (BBV), but its 19,000
employees and 1,200 branches are far fewer than BBV is saddled with, making
it a potentially powerful competitor.
Announcing the merger, Mr Solchaga repeated old arguments about only big
banks being able to compete in the Europe of 1993 and exhorted the remaining
private banks to think again about merging.
The point, though, was that the BCE would 'be belligerent in the financial
markets, which will oblige the other (private) banks to cheapen their loans
and give normal reward to deposits.' In other words, having failed to
convince Spaniards not to overspend, the authorities are back to attacking
the banks for lending so much so expensively.
This is an adventurous way of trying to cure inflation and cutting the cost
of borrowing.
Banco Exterior apart, the official lending bodies are famously inefficient.
In a recent interview the Prime Minister, Mr Felipe Gonzalez, warned that
'you can make a bureaucracy efficient, but it can never be creative'.
And the BCE will not solve the more immediate problem of French complaints
about Madrid's inability to cut rates further. Spain is not used to
international criticism. The reaction in Madrid has consisted mainly of a
hurt and whispered attempt to pass the buck.
Spain argues that the peseta is not the franc's real problem. The real
problem is the D-mark. Put aside the fact that the peseta and the franc are
at the top and bottom of their limits against each other in the EMS and it
is clear, they say, that if the Germans raise interest rates the franc would
also find itself on the floor against the D-mark.
The fact that the franc is not already there is that interventions by the
Bank of Spain and the bank of France are keeping it artificially strong.
The Spanish Government is keen to blame everybody but itself. Its banks are
distorting the money supply by lending expensively to eager consumers, and
the French are blind to their real problems. The only hole in this otherwise
impressive defence is the Treasury.
Here, the young Treasury chief, Mr Manuel Conthe, is a little more candid.
'Obviously there are some contradictions,' he says.
The Treasury has been scrambling to cut yields on all its paper for most of
this year. Last Friday it cut the interest rate on its 10-year bond 1.65
points to 11.83 per cent. Five-year yields have fallen to 12.26 per cent.
Foreign investors, astonished that a country with annualised inflation of
5.9 per cent still sells paper at almost 13 per cent, are being turned away
from Treasury auctions in droves. The volume of medium-term and long-term
paper held by foreigners tripled in the first quarter to Dollars 16bn.
Mr Conthe's problem is that he wants to build a credible market in
medium-term Spanish bonds (until now foreigners have bought mainly treasury
bills) but definitely does not want to become locked in to expensive
long-term borrowing.
The chickens are home and roosting.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
