<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Power surge on the Parana river - The uncertain economics of
the huge Itaipu hydro-electric project, which has just been completed on the
Brazil-Paraguay border
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The stone that sings' is the English translation of the romantic Indian name
for the world's largest hydro-electric dam. Itaipu, a joint project between
Brazil and Paraguay on the rushing Parana river which borders the two
countries, was completed yesterday, reaching its full potential of 12.6m kW.
Begun in 1974, Itaipu, more than any other single project, symbolises the
grandiose designs of Latin America's military dictators of the 1970s and the
far-off days when Brazil's economy grew 10 per cent a year and foreign banks
fell over themselves to provide finance regardless of ecological concerns.
Its name notwithstanding, Itaipu does not sing but roar as 32,000 cubic
metres of water a second crash through the spillway, raising clouds of mist.
Inside the power house, each of the 18 turbines is large enough to house a
small symphony orchestra, and between them they will provide up to 35 per
cent of Brazil's electricity.
'This is the work of the century,' says Mr Fernando Ferreira, president of
Itaipu Binacional, the company set up in 1973 to build it.
According to Mr Ferreira, 12.6m cu m of concrete went into Itaipu's
construction - 15 times more than in the Channel tunnel - and enough to
construct all the buildings for a city of 600,000.
Just as staggering are the costs. Instead of the projected Dollars 2bn, 17
years on Itaipu has so far cost Dollars 18.3bn, making it the world's most
expensive dam.
'These figures are misleading,' says Mr Ferreira. 'Of this total only
Dollars 9.5bn was direct investment, the rest is financial costs. Investment
costs rose because of an overvalued cruzeiro and having to provide local
infrastructure for employees which at the peak of construction numbered
40,000.'
Of Itaipu's Dollars 16.9bn debt, Dollars 7.4bn is with foreign commercial
banks and a further Dollars 1.1bn with Brazilian banks. The remaining
Dollars 8.4bn is with Eletrobras, Brazil's state electricity company, the
country's largest foreign debtor.
Herein lies the real story. Remarkably, for a long-term project of such
scale with only Dollars 100m capital, much of the financing came from
commercial banks in the form of high-interest loans with short-term
maturities of six or seven years. There was no financing from international
institutions in the construction phase and only more recently in the
transmission phase did the Inter-American Development Bank offer two loans.
'We were never approached,' says Mr David Atkinson, Brazilian representative
of the Inter-American Development Bank. 'Ten years ago Brazil preferred to
go with commercial institutions; it was a matter of national pride.'
Nor was there any shortage of banks offering money. Citibank, Deutschebank,
Bank of Tokyo, Bank of Paris and J P Morgan all came forward.
Mr Joel Korn, president of the Bank of America in Brazil which led a
consortium of foreign banks, says: 'Given its long-term nature this project
should have been financed through co-financing with multilateral
institutions. But the banks never treated this as a development project. It
was seen as a sovereign risk transaction, decision-making driven by the
republic's guarantee rather than the project's revenue-generating
possibilities.
Seen in this context it becomes a lot easier to understand Brazil's Dollars
63bn commercial bank debt - the developing world's largest. In the debt-led
growth days of the 1970s Itaipu was one in a series of often wasteful giant
infrastructure projects.
Brazilian officials argue that at least they have something to show for
their debt burden, unlike neighbouring Argentina where much of the
borrowings found their way into the pockets of generals. Mr Marcos Azambuja,
director-general of Brazil's Foreign Office, explains: 'We don't have the
guilt of other debtor countries. Most of the money went to projects people
can see.'
That is not to say that money did not go astray in the building of Itaipu.
'Itaipu became a byword of easy pickings,' says one energy consultant,
adding: 'Brazil's energy sector has long been run as a source of political
patronage rather than as a business.'
Ironically, as Itaipu's completion was celebrated yesterday in a ceremony
attended by the Brazilian and Paraguayan presidents, the company was facing
financial crisis. Hit by Brazil's austerity programme, its customers,
including the electricity distributors Eletrosul and Furnas, have not been
paying their bills, and, according to Mr Ferreira, the company is now owed
Dollars 700m.
Mr Ferreira admits that one problem is Brazil's low energy tariffs which the
World Bank has been criticising for years. Even though recent rises pushed
the tariffs to Dollars 45 or Dollars 50 per MWh, these numbers are below the
bank's recommended Dollars 70. The tariffs are also unfairly weighted
towards the distributor (Itaipu, for example, gets only Dollars 18.75).
As a result, Itaipu cannot pay its bills. Of the Dollars 2.4bn revenue it
should earn this year, 80 per cent is marked for debt servicing, 10 per cent
for operating costs and 10 per cent for royalties to the two governments for
use of the river.
The Itaipu treaty signed between Brazil and Paraguay in 1973 entitles each
to 50 per cent of the energy. Any not used must be offered to the other at
preferential rates. Paraguay uses only 1.8 per cent of the electricity
generated, or less than half the output of one turbine. It sells the rest to
Brazil. Absurdly, however, it insisted that its nine turbines produce
electricity compatible with the Paraguayan grid which operates on a 50Hz
frequency. This then is converted at extra cost for the Brazilian market to
60Hz frequency.
But owed Dollars 84m by Itaipu, Paraguayan demands are mounting for a
revision of the treaty to allow it to sell its share to a third party, such
as Argentina, which uses 50Hz.
Negotiations with Argentina were one of the project's big initial
difficulties. Argentina lies downstream and claimed the dam would slow the
river's flow. 'Itaipu was a feat of diplomatic engineering,' said Mr
Fernando Reis, head of the Americas department in Brazil's Foreign Office.
Some Brazilian officials favour an integrated energy system between the
three countries as part of the Southern Cone Common Market, formed in March
with the aim of establishing a free-trade zone between Brazil, Argentina,
Uruguay and Paraguay.
According to Mr Alan Poole, an independent energy adviser, linking up with
Argentina's thermal power system would provide a safeguard in dry years for
Brazil, whose energy is 96 per cent hydro.
He says that relying so much on one source in the form of Itaipu is risky.
But Mr Ferreira protests: 'Just as all Britain's energy resources happen to
be in the North Sea, ours happen to be in the Parana river.'
Yet since Itaipu was built Brazil's rate of economic growth decreased
rapidly, reducing the need for such a large project. In October 1984, when
the first two turbines started functioning, energy consumption had grown by
11 per cent in the first nine months. Last year, by contrast, the economy
contracted by 4.6 per cent.
But Mr Ferreira insists: 'Without Itaipu today we would be facing
blackouts.' He claims that despite the explosion of costs the dam is still a
viable proposition. 'The energy produced is cheap - only Dollars 700 per
installed kilowatt. Even including debt servicing it comes to Dollars 1,500
which is a competitive price.' He adds: 'When its debts are paid in 2023 we
will have a dam generating Dollars 1bn a year for each partner.'
He admits, however, that to build a dam that size today would be impossible
both for financial and ecological reasons such as the high cost of
resettling the 40,000 people whose lands were flooded.
Facing his desk in the company's directorate in Curitiba, some 350km
south-west of Sao Paulo, is an oil painting of Sete Quedas, one of the
world's highest waterfalls which was destroyed during Itaipu's construction.
Ecologists only realised the danger in 1982 when it was too late and the
falls were lost. As for the banks, these days they are only too aware of the
financial dangers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
