<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Letter: Education and the skills gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr G R TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I have to agree With Professor Desai's views (Letters, April 24) upon
the neglect of education being at the root of Britain's structural problems.
The notion of a skills gap in the UK is not a distant prospect; it is a
current reality. Only education, in the broadest sense, can close this gap.
The approach that supports the belief that qualifications do not matter is
one that also sponsors long-term decline.
As marketplaces become more competitive and the challenges facing managers
more complex so the debates about solutions have to be conducted at a higher
level. The laudable desire to involve as much of the workforce as possible
in problem-solving inevitably necessitates discussion at the lowest common
level of education. The lower this level is, the less efficient the debate
and the solution.
As they say at IBM. . .'If you think training is expensive, try
incompetence.'
G R Taylor,
52 London Road,
Berkhamsted, Herts
</TEXT>
