<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Letter: Germany sets a competitive example
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr THOMAS MARTINI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In the debate discussed in your article, 'Japanese cars and the EC'
(May 2), which is really a debate over what trade barriers EC politicians
will erect to prevent EC consumers from being able to exercise choice, too
little attention has been paid to the fact that, in 1990, Germany, for the
first time in over two decades, achieved a surplus in its car trade with
Japan. German cars to the value of Y593bn were imported by Japan, and
Japanese cars valued at Y518bn were exported to Germany. (Had exchange rates
not moved in Germany's favour in 1990, the bilateral trade would have been
in balance). This was achieved despite Germany being the only one of the
five large European car markets not to operate a quota system for Japanese
imports.
The obvious moral is that commercial success is most likely where there is
full exposure to competition, and where products are manufactured which can
successfully be sold abroad, rather than where internal wrangling over quota
extensions prevents rapid adaptation to best industrial standards.
At the FT London motor conference in March, Professor Daniel Jones, inter
alia European research director of MIT's global motor vehicle programme,
succinctly suggested that France and Italy would pay dearly for not letting
Japanese manufacturers into their countries.
Thomas Martini,
18 Poplar Road,
Merton Park SW19 3JR
</TEXT>
