<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Letter: No guarantee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PARVIZ DABIR-ALAI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stephen Fidler's article ('US seeks to raise World Bank's private profile',
May 1) leaves out answers to one vital question: Who is to gain?
The objective of structural reform promoted by the bank has, for some time,
been aimed at achieving more efficient resource allocation among the
economies to which they have been directed. At best results have been only
mixed. The failures have largely beeneither because of poor project
selection by bank staff or inefficient local management, or both.
Bank lending to the private sector is essentially an extension of the same
set of structural reform policies. These new ideas, if adopted, will not
necessarily expedite the development process as this new breed of private
borrowers will have to be at least partly vetted on the basis of their
respective projects' commercial viability. This defeats the objective of
alleviating 'backwardness' through sensitive resource allocation.
There is no guarantee that the new form of direct lending will enhance the
bank's record of picking winners - so yet further scarce resources will be
wasted at the expense of those who need them most.
Parviz Dabir-Alai,
lecturer in economics,
Richmond College,
Queens Road, TW10 6JP
</TEXT>
