<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Hang the Commons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOE ROGALY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Whenever a general election looms I consider the parties and try to shut my
eyes to the awful prospect that one of them might win. What a delight it has
been to contemplate last Thursday's local election results and savour the
possibility that perhaps, with any luck, no party will achieve an outright
victory. A hung parliament is not a recipe for chaos. If you believe that,
join the blinkered troglodytes who think Britain is doing well under
single-party rule. A forced deal in the lower house is, rather, the only
mechanism that offers even a glimmer of hope that we may overturn our serial
elective dictatorship, abolish the Lords, write a modern constitution and
prosper in the 21st century as the Federal Republic of Great Britain and
Northern Ireland.
The Liberals blew their chance in the late 1970s and Mr Paddy Ashdown is
over the top in demanding proportional representation without a referendum,
but we have to take what history offers us. If the leader of the Liberal
Democrats manages to win enough seats in the Commons to give him the
necessary leverage, and if he uses it successfully, he will deserve a statue
in his honour. Parliament Square is the correct site.
I enjoyed that. Now back to reality. The mundane question of the year is,
will Tortoise Major beat Hare Kinnock? In the original fable there was some
doubt at the beginning, but we all know that Tortoise won in the end. That
was because Hare lost his concentration, became over-confident, lolloped
about. Mr Neil Kinnock is doing none of that. He is leading the Labour party
as if the general election was due next week. Mr John Major is still trying
to find the starting line.
The two larger parties may be neck and neck in the opinion polls, but only
Labour is up and running, ready for a decisive national election. The
Conservative party is not. They are so unready that they failed to keep to
their strategy of introducing the health service reforms without making
changes that could damage their electoral chances. The job cuts by Guy's and
other opted-out hospitals may be right, and they may be technically outside
the domain of Mr William Waldegrave, secretary for health, but they need not
have been announced 10 days before the local elections. That was somewhere
between careless and unintelligent.
You can, however, bank on Labour's readiness for a national contest. The
party demonstrates every other day that it is fighting fit. If campaigning
is the yardstick, it is running rings around the Conservatives. It launched
no fewer than eight policy documents last month. Ostensibly aimed at the
local elections, they dealt with national issues: the arts, crime, health,
the environment, the family, education, and so on.
The rumbustious education secretary, Mr Kenneth Clarke, Only Labour is up
and running, ready for a decisive national election
has been obliged to respond, with increasing frequency, to the fresh
initiatives put out by his scholarly-looking Labour opponent, Mr Jack Straw.
Last week Mr Straw came out with a plan for broadening A-levels and
improving technical education for 16-18-year-olds; the best that Mr Clarke
could muster was that, just wait, his own gloss on technical education will
be published soon.
For the past several months Mr Gordon Brown has been advertising his 'policy
for industry', which is socialist to the extent that it might have been
written by Mr Michael Heseltine. You may or may not like the whiff of
interventionism discernible in this policy, but that is beside the political
point. Mr Brown has obliged Mr Peter Lilley, the industry secretary, to jump
to it, which he did smartly last Tuesday. Now he has to mouth the same
objectives as Mr Brown, leaving to the small print the considerable
differences between them.
Mr Michael Howard has had the unenviable task, for an employment secretary,
of defending the rapid increase in unemployment. His Labour counterpart is
one of the party's photogenic stars, the very image of a bright young
public-school conservative barrister, Mr Tony Blair. He has cajoled the
unions into apparent docility and now constitutes a not-so-secret weapon in
the battle for the centre-ground. Mr Blair has launched sections of his
party's policies for employment, training and reform of labour law five
times during the past couple of months and is due to bring forth a further
manifestation in a few weeks, when he will propose a cash-limited fund
against which bids could be made to support schemes to train employees in
work in areas of special pressure.
All this campaigning is being carried on in semi-private and in public. If
you are a captain of industry and you have not been invited to a discreet
meeting with Mr Blair, Mr Brown, Mr Straw or the shadow chancellor, Mr John
Smith, consider your position. Do you matter? Are you as important as you
think? But if you have been favoured you will know how prudent, how
reasonable, is the consumerist sales patter of these representatives of
producer interests. We can all now see the principal difference between
Labour and the Conservatives. The former will raise income taxes to fund
public services; the latter will proclaim an intention to improve services
and at the same time cut taxes. Labour has its arguments ready; the Tories
are arguing among themselves.
Maybe they will knock each other out and hang the Commons. The probability
is that more people will vote for lower taxes than the other way. Assuming
that when the time comes mortgages are down and the economic optimism is up
the Conservatives still stand the better chance of coming out as the larger
party; even an overall majority is not out of the question. If Mr Kinnock
had had the vision to embrace electoral reform wholeheartedly four years ago
he might be in de facto alliance with the suddenly important Mr Ashdown and
therefore in a commanding lead now. But he didn't and isn't.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19 Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
