<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Observer: Green blight
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Holding a Formula One motor race may not seem the most tactful way to
promote an environment conference, let alone the most environmentally
friendly. But Rio is the city where anything goes.
With preparations in full swing for the United Nations World Environment
Conference there in June 1992, all sorts of bizarre publicity ideas are
emerging. And the most controversial proposal is to hold a second Brazilian
Grand Prix in Rio during the conference.
Gilberto Cavalcanti, vice-president of the International Automobile
Federation, confirmed that Brazil has already asked the International
Automobile Federation for permission to hold the extra Grand Prix.
Discussions are under way with Rio authorities, he said.
The move has dismayed ecologists. They claim that promoting an environment
conference on the strength of racing cars burping far from ozone-friendly
fumes, is hardly good publicity for their cause or, for that matter,
consistent with Rio's aim to be the Green capital of the world.
</TEXT>
