<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Observer: Relaxation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England is as famous for boasting its forecasts are superior to
the Treasury's, as it is for refusing to publish them. But what are we to
make of the Old Lady's sudden interest in cold-calling top economists and
inviting them in for a chat?
After years of turgid meetings of gilt-edged market makers at the Bank, some
teenage scribblers hesitated before accepting the invitation from Andrew
Brooks, head of forecasting in the Bank's economics division. In the past,
the information flow has been all one way and the central bankers kept
annoyingly silent.
Not so in the current round of informal meetings with the City, I hear. The
Bank has opened a 'two-way dialogue' with analysts, which has been going on
since the Budget and continues today.
The privileged few are understandably chuffed. They think they're in a
position to gain valuable insights into the Bank's latest thinking on
monetary policy. If so, it would be surprising. But the relaxation of the
tight-lipped policy is welcome, especially if it eventually leads the Bank
to publish its own economic forecasts, independently of those of its
Treasury paymasters.
What better way for the Bank to show it is not just another nationalised
industry?
</TEXT>
