FT  07 MAY 91 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2's foreign affairs series, Assignment (7.45), visits the US to see how
some of the mis-applied principles of the 1960s generation (discrimination
with the word 'positive' stuck on the front, etc) have resulted in
resentment and accusations of censorship.
The third episode of Channel 4's engrossing series about England's Civil War
(8.00), concentrates on the actual fighting at such battles as Edgehill and
Naseby.
In the final episode of BBC1's series about a doubtful solicitor, Kinsey,
(9.30) many ends are tied: the runaway partner, Haynes, is rushed to a
Portuguese hospital, and Kinsey has to face up to his old emotional
involvement with Haynes' wife, Beth. But for true accounts of sexual
agonies, watch A Secret World Of Sex (9.50 BBC2) because today's episode in
this documentary series about sexual mores in pre-Second World War England
is the best of the lot. It tells of five women who had illegitimate babies
between the first and second world wars. Sex is also the subject of First
Tuesday (10.40 ITV) which deals with the abuse of young schoolboys. The boys
and their parents speak in what is described as 'an unprecedented set of
interviews'.
