<DOCNO>FT911-1353</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDABFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Arts: Old and Masterly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'The supply of authentic Giovanni Bellinis is unexhaustible,' or so Lord
Duveen used to assure prospective clients. Even then, in the 1920s, this was
not strictly true, and it certainly is not today. Old Master dealers - and
collectors - are in hot pursuit of an ever-dwindling supply of paintings,
which tend to be increasingly less old and less masterly.
Since its first exhibition a decade ago, however, Harari &amp; Johns has
established a well-deserved reputation for finding serious pictures. It is
symptomatic of the current market that the earliest painting in its tenth
anniversary offering, Five Centuries of Old Master Paintings (12 Duke
Street, SW1, until June 12), is a Madonna and Child with Saints by
Pesellino. Gold grounds are virtually unobtainable now - although Christie's
is selling an important Taddeo Gaddi on May 24. Relevant too that it is by
Pesellino, not by his master Fra Filippo Lippi, by one of whose altarpieces
in the Uffizi it is inspired.
Similarly, we find a portrait by Biagio D'Antonio rather than Botticelli and
a Landscape with Meleager and Atalanta from the hand of Giovanni Battista
Viola and not Domenichino. Duveen, no doubt, would have sold these works as
Lippi, Botticelli, and Domenichino. Only now is scholarship isolating
distinct artistic personalities for 'circle of' painters such as Biagio and
Viola.
Sixteenth-century pictures outclass those of the 15th, even here.
Outstanding among them is Dosso Dossi's half-length panel of St George,
which only came to light in 1975. It is an intense portrait-like
characterisation by the Ferrarese painter, who sets the saint against an
atmospheric Giorgionesque landscape of dawn breaking above the sea. A bright
foreground light pulls him out of the Stygian gloom, rendering his sleeve a
brilliant gold, playing across his breastplate, picking out the hairs of his
beard to concentrate on his troubled brow. Blocking the space between us is
the severed head of the dragon, its hairy snout substantiated by bold
strokes of pink and green.
More spectacular still is St Mary Magdalen at the Sepulchre by the Brescian
painter Savoldo, a glowing, golden variant of the even more seductive
silvery treatment of the subject in the National Gallery. The Magdalen is
depicted at the moment when, having visited the tomb to find it empty and
set down her ointment jar, she 'turned herself back and saw Jesus standing,
and knew not that it was Jesus'. There is no mistaking her former
profession.
The majority of the 17th and 18th century works are decorative and
commercial, with a substantial group of Roman capricci and Venetian vedute -
including a splendid Canaletto of the Colosseum - still-lifes and
flowerpieces. The most delightful of the latter is a confection of pale pink
roses and orange blossom by the best-known Spanish flower painter, Juan de
Arellano. There is a self-portrait bust by Murillo, a half-length portrait
of a gentleman by Rembrandt's pupil Govaert Flinck, and another, this time
full-length, by Gerard Ter Borch, stylish but understated to the point of
over-respectability. It is a relief - albeit briefly - to confront Ter
Brugghen's exuberant roistering fiddler, his bottle-nose shining like a red
traffic light at night. It is a marvellous picture, but hideous.
An unexpected pleasure is a conversation piece by Jan Joseph Horemans the
Elder, Antwerp's answer to Zoffany. Its neighbour, filling an entire gallery
wall, is more interesting still. This Good Samaritan is by the little-known
and short-lived Giovanni Battista Langetti, who was born and trained in
Genoa and went to Rome before ending up in Venice. His style is best
described as a sort of Ribera-Giordano inspired Caravaggism.
Once again, the gallery has found a quota of the impressive and the
unexpected for a show that, extending also to the German, French and British
schools, reflects the firm's unusual breadth of interest.
Old Master drawings rather than paintings are the subject of a loan
exhibition at Christie's (8 King Street, SW1, until May 14). The collection
was formed by Thomas Man Bridge, who travelled on the Continent in the
1830s, and bequeathed to Folkestone Library and Museum in 1924. This is the
first time that it has been on public display, and Christie's is its first
venue on a national tour that also takes in Dunkerque.
It is a curiously disjointed and uneven collection but it boasts a handful
of stunning sheets. An exquisite and richly washed drawing by Raphael's
pupil Perino del Vaga, The Reception of Psyche, is the most elaborate. What
a pity that its verso, represented by a photograph, could not have been
shown too. A Guercino study of a boy resting his head in his cupped hand is
a tour-de-force of draughtsmanship and observation, executed in that most
appealing of media, red chalk. Jusepe de Ribera employs it too, for a
careful and precisely outlined drawing of the Risen Christ. Bridge seems to
have had a predilection for the School of Bologna, and for 18th and 19th
century British watercolours and drawings. Spare a moment for John Brown's
sheet of studies of heads of monks, variously scowling under their ample
cowls.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17 Picture 'The Reception of the Psyche' by Raphael's pupil
Perino del Vaga at Christie's (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1354</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Arts: Nureyev - Wembley
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is being billed as 'Nureyev: The Farewell Tour', though the star denies
that it is a farewell and various doom-laden reports have been published
concerning Nureyev's dancing. On the evidence of Friday night's performance
at the unappealing Wembley Conference Centre, the gloom should concern the
nature of the presentation. This is basic to a point of insolence, and
unworthy of Nureyev and of at least some of the other artists who appear in
his concert programme. The lower, arena area of the hall is not raked, and
an intriguing view of events could be obtained by the audience as they
peered between the intervening rows of heads in order to see something below
the performers' knees. The stage is of good size, and, with the spendthrift
extravagance of several drunken sailors, the management provided black
curtains as setting. The accompaniment was recorded, and it was distressing
to see artists as distinguished as Evelyne Desutter (lately of the Monte
Carlo ballet) and the Bolshoy's Andrey Fedotov trying to cope with crippling
tempi in pas de deux from Don Quixote and Sleeping Beauty. But we know both
dancers are capable of very fine things, and Desutter's delicate grace,
Fedotov's elegance were, with Nureyev's performance in The Lesson, real
pleasures.
Nureyev wisely restricts himself to two works, Flemming Flindt's
Ionesco-inspired The Lesson and Jose Limon's The Moor's Pavane. Neither
makes the technical demands that Nureyev can no longer meet - I wish he had
not embellished The Lesson with a few laboured bravura steps - and he brings
a fine air of madness to the lunatic dance-teacher in this latter piece. It
is a genuinely chilling interpretation, and one finely supported by Desutter
as his pupil-victim and by Vivi Flindt as the accompanist-wardress.
About The Moor's Pavane I have many reservations. Limon's reduction of
Othello to the play's quartet of principals is a sacred text of Modern
Dance. With Limon it had a certain power; done now as a walk for
ballet-dancers who can indulge in a good deal of spurious emoting, it is nul
and void. And neither Nureyev, nor Flindt, nor Fedotov, nor Desutter, gifted
as they are, can redeem it from looking like Much Ado about Nothing.
The rest of the evening brought predictable sweetmeats. Some of Nureyev's
colleagues are from the Bolshoy, Staniskavsky and Odessa ballets, and they
offered unidiomatic Bournonville, a cabaret turn brightly calling itself a
'Bolero' by Petipa, and Dolin's Pas de quatre in which the dancer
impersonating Cerrito (whom the programme, a mine of non-information, does
not identify) was enchanting. I believe her to be Margarita Levina, a
ballerina from the Stanislavsky Ballet. A Franco-Russian dancer, Maria
Brissonskaya, gave a dry, dull account of The Dying Swan, and was no more
convincing in the ludicrous acrobatics of Oscar Araiz' Adagietto, where
Mahler is an excuse for reeling, writhing and fainting in coils. She and her
partner ( Alexander Bogatyrov of the Bolshoy, who deserves better) wore the
uneasy expressions of people who sense that the oysters weren't as fresh as
they ought to have been.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1355</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDABDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Arts: BCMG/Knussen - Adrian Boult Hall, Birmingham
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLEMENTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In each of its concerts this season, the Birmingham Contemporary Music Group
has included a premiere, and the last of the series on Sunday brought a new
work from the 21-year-old Scottish composer David Horne. Out of the Air had
been commissioned by the Michael Vyner Trust, set up to commemorate the late
director of the London Sinfonietta; though the Trust will naturally centre
its activities on the Sinfonietta, encouraging promising young composers to
write for the ensemble, it plans to spread its largesse as widely as
possible, and will work with other groups such as BCMG.
Horne is certainly a hugely promising talent; his towards dharma .., heard
at Edinburgh last summer, was evidence of that. He is now studying at the
Curtis Institute in Philadelphia and, naturally enough, still finding his
voice; perhaps for that reason Out of the Air, a sequence of 'five
inventions for ensemble', was not entirely consistent and coherent. The
first two movements are convincing, economical elaborations of rhythmic
figures; the final piece works up to a brilliant, extrovert finish. But the
slow third becomes over-dense and clogged, and the fourth lacks a
distinctive idea, so that the work seems more diffuse than it probably is.
The BCMG was conducted by Oliver Knussen; they had begun with a dreamily
sensuous account of his Ophelia Dances, coming up freshly minted and teeming
with ideas, each solo phrase lovingly shaped. The programme ended with
Birtwistle's Meridian, in a performance with the London Voices and the
mezzo-soprano Mary King, of glinting, crystalline textures and sinewy
expressive force.
Completed in 1971, Meridian is one of the most fascinating and transitional
of Birtwistle's early masterpieces. With its solo horn and cello it looks
back to the savage ritualised violence of the works around Punch and Judy,
while the hazy sound mobiles created by the eight sopranos start to explore
the world that would eventually encompass The Mask of Orpheus; its texts
too, a poem by Christopher Logue framed by stanzas from Thomas Wyatt,
dealing with the power of music and its fateful limitations, look forward to
that huge opera. Above all, though, it's a magnificently sustained piece of
word setting in its own right, with vivid ideas and highly wrought vocal
lines contained within a dramatic trajectory of irresistible certainty.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
