<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Construction Contracts: Oman housing ministry offices
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
YAHYA COSTAIN, a 60 per cent owned subsidiary of Costain group, has won an
Pounds 8.35m order to build a three-storey office block and headquarters for
the Ministry of Housing at Al Kuwair in Oman.
The octagonal building has a ground floor plan of 77,000 sq metres and its
central core rises five storeys - 29 metres to the top of the parapet. In
the core is a central atrium starting at first floor level, with an
aluminium-framed geodesic dome and stained glass infill roof. The top of the
roof will be 37 metres above ground floor level.
The three-storey offices form a ring round the central core. The main
entrance rises to the same height as the core and has a double-storey height
hall with two floors of offices above. On each corner of the octagon,
crenellated towers rise, giving the appearance of a fortified structure.
The building has a reinforced concrete frame on pad raft foundations with
concrete blockwork infill and partition walls, aluminium windows, and
glass-reinforced concrete decorative screens. Internally, all circulation
and executive areas will have marble cladding and flooring.
Mechanical and electrical services, security, landscaping, parking areas and
an 850 metre longboundary wall are included in the contract, which is due
for completion in October next year.
