<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Management: Why earn-outs can mean trouble in store - The
pitfalls of taking a deferred payment when selling a company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Alex Rice* is worried. One year into a three year earn-out arrangement with
the company which bought his business Rice and the purchaser cannot agree on
how much profit Rice's part of the group is making.
Since Rice stands to make a lot of money if he can reach the targets set in
the earn-out he is understandably concerned at the disagreement.
'On a day-to-day basis the arrangement has gone pretty much as expected,' he
says. 'But now we have reached the stage of the year end audit and things
are getting a bit heated. The profits are turning out to be a bit less than
I thought. They say mistakes have been made but whether that is genuine is
not quite clear.'
Part of the difficulty, Rice believes, is that the purchasing company took
over control of his accounting department and the accounting staff who used
to report to him now report to head office. In addition to this the
accounting systems were changed so it is difficult to compare the business's
most recent profits with its performance in previous years.
Rice hopes that when profits are averaged out over the three years of the
agreement he will still qualify for a sizeable part of the deferred payment.
But like many other company owners who sold out on the basis of an earn-out
agreement he may be in for a rocky ride.
Few of the earn-outs which became so popular in the late 1980s have run
their full term. Most have been re-negotiated or terminated early when the
vendor and the new owners of his company realised the deal was not working
out as planned.
Between 60 and 70 per cent of earn-outs - most of which are intended to run
for between three and five years - are terminated within two years,
according to Stephen David, a director of David Garrick, a London-based
acquisitions specialist.
The economic downturn has meant that many deals, negotiated in the more
buoyant conditions of 1987-89, are producing less than expected pay-outs for
the vendor. A survey by 3i Corporate Finance of eight recent deals which it
negot-iated where earn-outs have been calculated showed three had produced
less than expected pay-outs. Of 10 deals where earn-outs still had to be
calculated six were not expected to live up to initial hopes.
The earn-out rose to prominence in the second half of the 1980s as a method
of allowing the owners of service sector businesses to realise what they
believed to be the full value of their companies. Bidders were not prepared
to pay high multiples for businesses with few tangible assets but they were
willing to be far more generous if payment could be made dependent on future
profits.
Typically the purchaser would make an initial payment equivalent to the
value of the net assets in the business and a second, larger payment to
cover goodwill if the business which was being bought met agreed profit
targets.
Overuse of the earn-out technique has plunged some of the more enthusiastic
bidders into difficulties. Many built up considerable commitments either to
pay out cash or to issue shares. Publicly-listed companies such as FKB, a
marketing group, WPP, an advertising company, and Shandwick, a public
relations firm, have disclosed sizeable earn-out liabil-ities.
The problems of the vendors, the owners of the small businesses so eagerly
sought by the corporate empire builders, have been less well documented.
'The vendor has to be particularly careful in negotiating an earn-out,' says
Stephen David. 'The buyer has the company and he also retains most of the
money. All the vendor has is his contract.' 'What can you do if the
purchaser does something you don't agree with?' asks Roger Wardell, who
gained half of the maximum Pounds 4m possible when he sold his company by
way of an earn-out. 'You would have to spend your own money fighting your
case while the purchaser can use the company's money.'
For the purchaser the earn-out is a means of retaining the loyalty and
commitment of the owner-manager until he can put in his own managers. But
earn-outs frequently face vendors with substantial conflicts of interest as
they set what is best for the long-term future of the company against what
would boost short-term profits - and the size of their earn-out.
Fewer earn-outs are being negotiated in the more sober climate which now
prevails but prospective vendors should watch for a number of key issues:
The length of the earn-out. Do not tie yourself into a lengthy agreement
during which the business and external circumstances could radically alter.
'Watch the length of the deal,' warns Ian Smith, a director of Livingstone
Fisher Associates, a London-based acquisitions firm. 'Four to six year
earn-outs are a nonsense. We normally look to arrange one to three year
deals.'
But even these shorter periods can prove irksome. 'I don't know how people
sustain it for two to three years,' says Wardell, whose earn-out lasted just
six months. 'From the point of view of both purchaser and vendor it must be
a strained relationship. On the one hand the vendor wants to be loyal and
group-minded but what if that hits him in the pocket book? You are pulled
two ways.'
The definition of what constitutes profits. Vendors should keep their
original auditors or at least retain the right to call them in to ensure
that the accounting rules are not changed, advises Neil Williamson, managing
director of 3i Corporate Finance. 'Valuations of stock and work in progress
are the most common sources of disagreement,' he points out.
'Write the rule book before you sign the final sale contract,' says Ian
Smith. 'You don't want the buyer massaging profits or imposing unexpected
management charges. There is so much room for interpretation in the
accounting standards. Get your old accountants to check the numbers.'
Problems in integrating the business in the larger group. To enable the
vendor to distinguish the profits of his company from the larger group the
newly-acquired company cannot be integrated into the group until the
earn-out period ends. This is generally thought to work against the
purchaser but does have implications for the vendor.
'It is true that the purchaser cannot impose anything on you but neither can
you take risks,' comments Richard Payne, who recently completed a one year
earn-out. 'The business went into a sort of limbo. It was quite unreal and
meant that for a time I could not further my career with the company we had
sold to.'
It is problems with integration which most frequently lead to the premature
ending of earn-out arrangements. If the buyer insists on making changes that
should be taken into account in the profit calculation. One purchaser
installed a computerised stock control system in its new subsidiary. Both
the investment cost and the resulting improvement in profits had to be
neutralised in the earn-out agreement.
Safeguards if the purchaser cannot pay. Some buyers with extensive earn-out
commitments have found they cannot afford to meet them. 'What do you do if
the buyer cannot pay?' asks David Teacher, a partner in London solicitors
Teacher Stern Selby. 'You can't sue because then the whole lot goes down.'
Teacher's answer is to structure deals to give the vendor the right to
regain control of his business if the purchaser is unable to complete. Even
if the vendor does not actually want to regain control he is in a stronger
position to renegotiate the deal in his favour. The culture clash when an
independent entrepreneur becomes an employee in a larger company. 'The
vendor goes to a smart hotel for the completion lunch and the champagne
flows. Next morning he sits at his desk and gets a memo telling him he
cannot keep driving the Rolls but is only entitled to a Ford Granada,' says
Stephen David. 'That can cause problems.'
The cultural issue is perhaps the most difficult to overcome. Many vendors
find they simply do not fit in to the purchaser's more formal corporate
structure. Many of the other pitfalls can be avoided, however, with a little
planning.
*The names of vendors and some details have been changed.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
