<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Management: You're not only there for the beer - Hints on
how to behave at receptions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Have you ever been an unwilling participant at a reception where you know
no-one? Is everyone else engaged in animated conversation with what looks
like a clutch of old school chums? Do you end up standing in a corner eating
and drinking too much before creeping out with the determination never to
attend such an event again?
Despite the recession, it is likely that your diary contains a fair
sprinkling of receptions over the next few months. In addition there may
well be professional dinners, reunions and trade shows.
Careful preparation and a more positive attitude to these events can reduce
or even eliminate the misery and can even turn them into a rewarding
experience, according to How to Work a Cocktail Party, an advice note to
staff from the Canadian affiliate of accountants Touche Ross.
The guide recommends that you:
Do your homework. Who will be attending the event? Who is the sponsor? Are
there likely to be specific people there you want to meet? If so, make a
note of their names, positions, recent mentions in the press.
Do not set out with a negative attitude or with the view that you are only
going for the food, the drink, or 'to put in an appearance'.
Set personal and professional goals for the event: to make, say, two new
contacts or to meet a particular individual.
Prepare your small talk and make a mental note of topical professional
issues which may come up in discussion.
Make sure that your partner, if you are taking someone, is also informed
about the event, the people and likely tone.
Arrive at the starting time. This means you will be in one of the happy,
chattering groups from the outset instead of trying to break in with the
other late-comers.
Walk into the room with confidence. Do not hang about in the doorway.
Look for people you know or want to know to get started but do not just
stick with people you know. The aim, after all, is to get to know new people
who may be fun knowing personally or worth knowing professionally.
Always give a firm handshake. Avoid jellyfish, knuckle-breakers, finger
squeezes and kissing. Do not burden yourself with plates, drinks or papers
which prevent you from keeping a hand free for shaking hands.
Place your name tag where it can be easily read. Use other people's name
tags to start conversations.
Prepare a brief self-introduction to outline how you fit in with the group
and provide others with enough information to start a conversation. It can
be hard to think up an opening line but it is better to say something than
wait for the best line.
When introduced to others repeat their name; it will help you to remember
it.
To enter an on-going conversation it is best to approach groups of three or
more people since there is a greater chance that one individual will be
willing to make an opening for a newcomer.
If the situation is uncomfortable, excuse yourself and move on.
Spend no more than eight to 10 minutes with any one person. To achieve a
smooth exit say that you are going to get something to eat or drink or that
there is someone else you need to talk to.
After the event review how the evening went. Were the techniques you used
successful? Did you notice any other examples of effective (or of
ineffective) behaviour? How many contacts did you make?
Social conditioning makes it difficult for many people to feel comfortable
at receptions. They feel uneasy talking to strangers, fear rejection and
would prefer to be 'properly introduced.'
But preparation and a positive approach can make a big difference to what
you get out of it, however.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1369</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEGBDAAZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910507
</DATE>
