<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Economics: German data will be scrutinised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE are no economic statistics scheduled for release in the UK or France
but plenty this week in Germany and the US.
With the D-Mark so weak on foreign exchanges, and anxiety growing about the
shape of the post-unification economy, the releases will be scrutinised for
signs that the German decline has been exaggerated. This might prompt
sentiment that the D-Mark is oversold.
Improved weather in March could boost the production data scheduled for
release this week. For eastern Germany, data is thin on the ground but
anecdotal evidence suggests further output falls this year. Analysts expect
foreign manufacturing orders to have revived after the dollar's recovery.
Orders offer good clues to future growth in gross national product, which is
expected to slow to 1.9 per cent this year from 4.5 per cent in 1990.
Unemployment data should continue to show that joblessness is falling in the
west of the country, but not as fast in April as in March.
The current account, meanwhile, was in deficit for the second month running
in February, partly as a result of Germany's contributions to the allied
effort in the Gulf War. With domestic demand strengthening, Germany's
merchandise trade position has been deteriorating, with export volumes lower
than a year ago and imports markedly higher.
In the US the focus will be on the Treasury's quarterly refunding. Though
the outlook for US bonds is favourable - with last week's cut in the
discount rates and evidence of subdued inflation likely in producer prices
figures on Friday - there are fears that the Treasury will eventually have
to raise more funds because of the recession. This is making the market
anxious about supply and the likely absence of Japanese buyers.
Other notable events and statistics, with median market forecasts from MMS
international, the financial research company, include:
Today: US, wholesale trade balance for March, start of Treasury Quarterly
refunding, consumer credit (down Dollars 1bn), three-year note auction,
senate banking committee hearing.
Tomorrow: Canada, housing starts (110,000). US, 10-year note auction.
France, Victory Day, all markets closed.
Thursday: US, 30-year bond auction, weekly initial claims and weekly money
supply data. All markets in Denmark, Sweden, Norway, Holland, Austria and
Switzerland closed for Ascension Day. Canada, new housing price index.
Australia, April employment (down 20,000) and unemployment rate (9.4 per
cent).
Friday: US, producer prices index (0.1 per cent), excluding food and energy
(0.2 per cent). Canada, employment growth (flat), unemployment rate (10.6
per cent).
During the week: Germany, April unemployment (west down 15,000, east up
40,000), vacancies, unadjusted for April, industrial production and
manufacturing orders for March, current account balance (down DM3.5bn) for
March.
</TEXT>
