<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / ILO seeks end to ban on unions at GCHQ
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR LABOUR EDITOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Labour Organisation, the United Nations agency, has called
for talks between the government and unions as a way of ending the block on
union membership at the GCHQ communications centre in Cheltenham.
An ILO committee of experts has renewed its criticism of several aspects of
British labour law in spite of hearing a defence of legislation from the
government. Britain may be asked to explain further at the annual ILO
conference next month.
Although the government could ignore the ruling by the committee of experts,
it is a signatory to the ILO and the criticism of several pieces of
employment legislation since since 1979 is potentially awkward.
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary, said yesterday that it was
'shameful that a country and a government that places so much store on the
authority of the UN and the value of world opinion' should be criticised in
this way.
Mr Willis said the government should follow the advice of the committee of
experts and 'bring this country in line with civilised standards without
delay'. The ban on independent unions at GCHQ has existed since 1984.
The ruling by the committee of experts criticises the provisions of the 1988
Employment Act under which unions are prevented from disciplining members
who refuse to take part in industrial action called after a ballot.
The committee says that interferes with the right of unions to set their own
constitutions. It says unions should be free to impose sanctions on members
who will not comply with democratic decisions.
</TEXT>
