<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Companies found ignorant of EC market law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH shows that most of the UK's top companies have a poor knowledge of
European Community competition law, Robert Rice writes.
Market studies carried out for Theodore Goddard, a leading City law firm,
indicate that only 4 per cent of UK companies knew that the EC could impose
a fine of up to 10 per cent of a company's turnover for contraventions,
compared with 28 per cent of their French counterparts. The survey covered
50 leading companies in the UK and France with a minimum turnover of Pounds
70m and a similar number of advisers including lawyers, accountants and
bankers.
Yet 84 per cent of the companies had been involved in a cross-border merger,
acquisition, joint venture or trade agreement in the EC in the past three
years. Almost all expected to be involved in such activity within the next
five years. All the French companies had recent experience of cross-border
activity.
Overall, 84 per cent of the companies thought that their understanding of
national competition law was 'fairly good'.
Even so, 64 per cent of the UK companies admitted a 'fairly poor' or 'very
poor' knowledge of EC competition law. The comparable figure for French
companies was only 8 per cent.
</TEXT>
