<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / Moscow deal may not end coal strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NOVOKUZNETSK, MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOVIET government yesterday transferred control of coal mines to the
Russian Federation, as part of a deal with Mr Boris Yeltsin to end a
crippling two-month coal miners' strike.
But Mr Alexander Smirnov, a strike leader in the vast Siberian Kuzbas coal
fields, said the Kremlin's signature yesterday of a protocol relinquishing
the mines did not yet mean an end to strikes. He said a third of the 80
Kuzbas pits were still idle yesterday, together with 25 other pits in the
area.
Mr Smirnov said the striking miners would wait to see the fine print of the
agreement, before calling off industrial action which has paralysed sectors
of Soviet industry.
He said leaders of the local strike movement would today meet their
counterparts from Vorkuta, the other Russian mining region covered by the
protocol, together with miners from the Donbas in the Ukraine, where the
strike has all but crumbled.
Meanwhile, workers in the vast Siberian oil and gas fields of Tyumen have
written to President Gorbachev demanding a tripling of their pay and an
increase in the extremely low internal oil price of Rbs38 a tonne to Rbs180.
And a group of workers at the huge Kirov plant in Leningrad yesterday
launched a warning strike to call for Mr Gorbachev's resignation and protest
against a proposed one-year ban on strikes.
The protocol, signed by Mr Yeltsin last week, gives the Russian mines more
independence from the state and the right to spend part of their hard
currency revenues on imported goods and other benefits for miners. But
details of the protocol have yet to be published. It is also likely to be
followed by a transfer of other industries and plants to Russian
jurisdiction. Workers at the giant Uralmash engineering plant in the Urals,
for instance, last week voted in favour of a similar transfer.
Kommersant newspaper said yesterday that miners would be able to dispose of
7 per cent of the Russian mines' hard-currency earnings. It also reported
that the protocol provided for the transfer to Russian jurisdiction of two
big steel plants.
</TEXT>
