FT  07 MAY 91 / Full reconciliation between France and Iran expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE recent improvement of political relations between France and Iran was
taken a large step forward over the weekend during talks in Tehran between
the two foreign ministers. It is now expected to culminate in a full-scale
reconciliation, with a visit to France soon by President Ali Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani.
Relations between the two countries became strained after the Shah was
overthrown by the Islamic revolution of 1979, and were aggravated by a wave
of Iranian-sponsored kidnappings and terrorism attacks in France in the late
1980s.
In the last two years, however, the pragmatic moderation of Iranian policy
under President Rafsanjani has opened the door to more frequent diplomatic
contacts between the two countries, starting two years ago with a first
visit to Tehran by Mr Roland Dumas, French foreign minister, and followed
last December by the return visit to Paris of Mr Ali Akbar Velayati, his
Iranian opposite number.
The French government has shown itself anxious to settle the big financial
dispute, over nuclear co-operation contracts, left hanging in the wake of
the fall of the Shah's regime, and now appears ready to make significant
concessions to finalise the matter. Indeed, the French Foreign Ministry
appears determined to override the negotiating reservations of the Finance
Ministry, according to reports here.
French anxiety for reconciliation with Iran is largely attributed here to
eagerness to secure access for French companies to the lucrative Iranian
market.
</TEXT>
