<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 91 / 'Stop Czech arms sales to Syria' - Shamir
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Yitzhak Shamir, the Israeli prime minister, yesterday called on
Czechoslovakia to halt arms sales to Syria and to other Middle Eastern
countries hostile to Israel. Prague says it cannot afford to stop selling
arms until substitute industries are in place.
Mr Marian Calfa, the Czechoslovak prime minister, caused a stir in Israel
over the weekend when he admitted during a visit to Jerusalem that Prague
was negotiating the sale of Czech-built Soviet tanks to Syria, Israel's
chief military foe.
In Prague, the newspaper Rude Pravo reported that the government was
considering selling about 100 new T-72 tanks to Syria and some old T-55
tanks to Iran. Last Friday, the US urged Czechoslovakia, a prime supplier of
heavy arms to the Middle East while it was under communist rule, not to
proceed with the sales.
Mr Calfa said his government would rather not sell arms, but could not
afford to give them up, because the Slovakia region relied heavily on the
industry for employment. About 80,000 people work in arms production in the
region, where unemployment is already rising and the government fears
separatist unrest.
Mr Calfa, who yesterday addressed a meeting of the World Jewish Congress,
turned the argument into an appeal for aid to help convert arms production
into civilian production.
'Czechoslovakia is not interested in producing tanks. But we don't want to
break the economy of a region. Conversion requires enormous capital. We need
assistance. I'm here to ask Israel and the World Jewish Congress for help,'
he said.
In talks yesterday, Mr Calfa told Mr Shamir that Czechoslovakia had 'learned
the lessons of the Gulf war' and did not intend that its arms should be used
against Israel. But Mr Shamir said a decision should be taken not to sell
arms to Syria and elsewhere before the transition to civilian production had
been completed.
</TEXT>
