<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Minding Your Own Business: The only system that worked -
Computing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID CARTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'I'M A chartered accountant and in my practice I have 400 clients. About 200
of them are on computer. I have been an auditor for 20 years and in all that
time I can honestly say that I have only ever found one computerised
accounting system which worked.'
My old friend Godfrey was talking about the problems facing businesses that
do not have qualified accounting staff to do the books  - in fact, most
businesses turning over less than Pounds 1m.
'Hold on. Half the businesses in the UK have got their accounts on computer.
There must be thousands of them. Surely you can't be saying that none of the
computerised accounting systems works?'
'Oh, the computer works all right; it's simply that the users cannot operate
it with the level of accuracy required for financial accounts. I would say
that whenever one of my clients gets a computer, the cost of my audit fee
goes up.
'You see, with a manual set of books, mistakes are easily discovered and
corrected. But with a computer, the posting has gone automatically through
the system in all directions. If I find an error it is a terrible job to
find where it has gone and reverse it out. Between you and me, when I
produce accounts for my smaller customers I just ignore all the computer
print-outs they give me and start from scratch with the bank statements and
the paying-in books. It's quicker.'
'What about the one system that did work?'
'It was an accounts system for a hotel. It did a self-contained job and the
people were able to reconcile it. Let me tell you: if you ever find a
computerised accounts system which works it will not be comprehensive.'
The source of most of these businesses' problems is the nominal ledger. In
computer terms, a nominal ledger package is the simplest accounting package
of all. Most of the different accounts postings take place within the
nominal and that is why it holds so many terrors for the non-accountant. To
illustrate the problem, let us look at just one of the standard accounting
entries  - wages and Paye.
Imagine a typical small business which employs five full-time staff and
three part-time. The full-timers are on Paye and each earns Pounds 200 gross
per week. The part-timers are not on Paye and each earn Pounds 70 gross per
week.
An accountant is running the books and wishes to post this week's wages to
the nominal ledger. He has to prepare two journals. First he must write up
the wages book in order to calculate deductions of tax and employee National
Insurance for the five staff on Paye.
Their gross wages combined comes to Pounds 1,000. Suppose deductions come to
Pounds 300, leaving net wages of Pounds 700. The company also has to pay
employer's NI, say 10 per cent of gross wages. So his first journal to the
nominal will be as follows: debit Pounds 1,000 to gross wages and Pounds 100
to employer's NI in the profit and loss account. Credit Pounds 700 to wages
control and Pounds 400 to Inland Revenue in the balance sheet.
When the week's wages of Pounds 910 (Pounds 700 to the full-time employees
and Pounds 210 to the part-timers) are actually paid, the accountant posts
his second journal entry.
He credits Pounds 910 to the bank account, debits Pounds 700 to wages
control in the balance sheet and Pounds 210 to part-time wages in the profit
and loss account.
In both journals the debits balance the credits, and he has used a control
account, one of the tricks of the accounting trade, to make sure he doesn't
mix up the wages of the part-timers with those of the Paye staff. (Correct
postings to wages control will always balance themselves out to zero. If he
had posted the whole wages bill of Pounds 910 to wages control by mistake,
the resulting balance of Pounds 210 would tell him he had made an error.)
That is the way Paye works for any business that employs people.
When it comes to posting wages and Paye to the nominal ledger,
the typical nominal ledger package gives no help. All it does is ask which
accounts you want debited and which credited. The user is left to work out
which accounts are involved; whether they are in the profit and loss account
or in the balance sheet; which is to be debited; which credited, and so on.
There are many accounts packages on the market, all trumpeting themselves as
ideal for the non-accountant user, but when it comes to such accounting
systems the gap between theory and reality is vast.
Many doubt whether the small businessman could ever produce his own
accounts, and his right-hand person, the experienced book-keeper, is almost
extinct. Certainly there is a great deal more that the software companies
could do to help. The clue lies in asking why it is that, although they
cannot handle a nominal ledger package, non-accountants are quite happy with
a sales or purchase ledger.
Suppose you are using a sales ledger package and you want to record a sales
invoice for Pounds 115. When the 'invoice entry' screen appears you put
Pounds 15 in the 'Vat' box and Pounds 100 into the 'Net' box. You don't have
to work out which accounts are involved. In fact you don't see any mention
of debits and credits at all. This is because the invoice entry option is a
pre-defined journal where all the accounts and the debits and credits have
been pre-programmed in advance. The computer automatically credits Pounds 15
to Vat, Pounds 100 to sales, and Pounds 115 to debtors. All you have to do
is to fill in the boxes.
Pre-defined journals in the sales ledger allow the user to make correct
accounting entries for quite complex accounting transactions such as the
taking of settlement discounts or refunding cheques. A pre-defined
wages/Paye journal would make any nominal ledger package much more
'user-friendly'. Closing stock adjustment and depreciation are two other
candidates, as are accruals and prepayments. When a nominal ledger arrives
with pre-defined journals for every difficult accounting entry, then for the
first time the market will see a true business accounting package.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
Weekend Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1398</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEEAAAFVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Faces turn green as the green stock fades /
Charting the decline into shareholder revolt at Tace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOARDROOM musical chairs at Tace and Goring Kerr, its controlled
subsidiary, comes at the end of an unhappy period in which the environmental
monitoring and control equipment group has passed from takeover candidate to
an under-performing market laggard.
But if Sir David Nicolson, the chairman who is currently being stalked by
rebellious institutions, is to be believed, Tace's assets are being
thoroughly under-utilised.
While some of the shine has worn off green stocks, the company which Mr Jock
Mackenzie floated more than 20 years ago, operates in areas which continue
to grow by 30 per cent a year.
'The company should have sales 10 times bigger than the Pounds 36m it
enjoyed in 1990,' Sir David said last month, shortly after his controversial
appointment and before the institutions resumed their efforts to install Mr
Michael Beckett as chairman.
Tace's strength lies in environmental pollution monitoring equipment and
contaminant detectors. In the US, the 1990 Clean Air Act has stipulated that
companies must monitor airborne particle emissions by size and quantity.
Tace is confident it now makes a monitor that has become the industry
standard, partly because it is used by the Environmental Protection Agency.
Furthermore, the EPA is using Tace's equipment in the joint studies of air
pollution levels it is conducting with the EC in Europe.
Another development fueling growth in the US, where the group derives half
its sales, is the tightening controls on gas emissions from land-fill sites.
Some 50 states have approved Tace's equipment to test emission levels, and
the group says this should enhance the dominant position it already has
monitoring emissions from the pulp and paper industry.
The other focus is contaminant detectors for the food and pharmaceutical
industries. The equipment is designed to identify bone, plastic, glass and
metal in food on production lines that are moving at speed.
Tace says that a number of UK food manufacturers and some retailers have
bought machines to test and that the order book has rocketed because of
fears of liability claims.
The two areas evolved from the 51 per cent-controlled Goring Kerr, which in
the early 1980s supplied equipment to the food industry and spun off cash
for Tace to develop its environmental services activities.
The strategy was to seek niche markets that would be supported by
increasingly stringent national and international legislation, Sir David
says.
An impressive growth of return on capital, earnings per share and cash flow
came to a grinding halt in 1988. Tace stopped making acquisitions for shares
that the market was more than happy to finance and started to raise debt.
The share price, which had been more than Pounds 5 in 1985 and above Pounds
3 after acquisitions in 1989, fell to a low of 130p.
At the same time, Mr Mackenzie resigned as chairman of London &amp; Northern, a
go-getter mini-conglomerate stock of the 1960s, after selling his stake to
Evered Bardon. Tace took over the entire running costs of the L&amp;N premises
off London's Fleet Street, from where, in a corner, it had operated a head
office.
By 1990, despite reporting pre-tax profits of only Pounds 3.9m, the group
was paying Pounds 1.7m in head office costs. Tace recently announced it
would move out of these offices.
Sources close to the company and the proposed new board say the head office
was constantly draining cash from the operating groups and preventing
essential investment.
This process led to severe demoralisation in the operating companies. At one
stage Mr Dick Richardson, Tace's managing director, held letters of
resignation from most of middle management in his briefcase, according to Mr
David Floyd, of Belmont Bank.
Following efforts by Sir David to persuade management that things would
change, most resignations have been withdrawn.
Behind the institutions' move yesterday to remove the entire Tace board and
replace it with a team led by Mr Beckett, lies the knowledge that Sir David
had decided not to remove any of the board that had allowed Tace's costs to
get so badly out of control. Illust. Sir David: the assets are thoroughly
under-utilised
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10 Photograph Sir David, the assets are thoroughly
under-utilised (Omitted).
