<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Parallel turns on the Essex coast: An alternative to the
crowded pistes of ski resorts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX WILKINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE QUESTION was: can one enjoy the annual skiing holiday without the
inconvenience of crowded airports, lift queues, uncertain snow, and the
contagion of the package tour - in short, without actually going skiing?
High hotels and helicopters allow the rich to get away from us all; but even
serious money is subject to air traffic control and the greenhouse effect.
So I tried a different solution: the Essex coast in April. It may be
objected that one does not ski in Essex during April. But the choice was
based on more subtle reasoning. Discard for a moment the image of pine trees
dusted with new snow, the squeak and thump of lift cables on their wheels,
and the mingled aromas of sun lotion, french fries and socks in Alpine huts.
Consider instead the essential character of the sport, which draws people
year after year with the eagerness of escaping prisoners. The awesome power
of the mountains and the high romance of their inaccessible beauty? Perhaps.
But these pleasures can be enjoyed more easily and with more variety in
summer.
No, the appeal of skiing is different, and in some ways inimical to the
contemplation of Europe's grandest spectacle. It depends on speed, balance
and a perpetual frisson of danger. Skiing has gained popularity because the
technology of plastics, resins and fibre made it easier and safer for the
unfit, the overweight and the semi-skilled ; but the excitement of
controlling gravity and the swing of the skis with a ripple of the body, is
the same as it was in the days of leather and wood.
On the Essex coast, one cannot try ones skill against gravity, but there is
plenty of wind and, instead of snow, miles of unspoiled virgin water. The
action is surprisingly similar. One stands on a board rather longer and
about three times as wide as a pair of skis, with the back straight and the
rear knee bent, while hanging on to a wishbone which supports the sail.
In a good breeze, the effect is between skiing and hang-gliding. The sail
leans towards the horizontal, with the sailor hanging like Icarus below a
wing. The force of the wind lifts him until the board skims over the waves
with a roar of spray. It can go as fast as a speedboat.
But is it the real thing? Can the sailboard offer that afterglow of
satisfaction which captured the imagination of generations of skiers? Is it
not wet, cold and, frankly, unsmart? After a week of spring sunshine and
fine breezes, I do not think I would have traded the Colne and Stour
estuaries for Davos or La Plagne.
Skiing and board-sailing offer variations on a common theme: speed surging
from an elemental force but controlled by muscular skill; the wild impulse
to go a little too fast; the exultation of getting it together and then the
inevitable collapse. A bit like Don Giovanni, but quite respectable and
nobody hurt.
Board sailing, also, has been transformed in recent years by synthetic
materials. So, just as the skier debates whether to pit himself against a
slope marked in blue, red or black (in order of difficulty), board sailors
stare out to sea asking apprehensively whether they dare try the '7' or will
play safe with the '5.5' - the size of the sail in square metres. The
biggest modern sails keep a perfect aerodynamic shape and drive the board at
speed even on days when the sea is a gently dappled green and blue. In
blustery weather the newer small rigs improve the board sailor's ability to
negotiate the waves, just as plastic boots and sharp edges hold the skier
firmly on an icy piste.
So also, neoprene wet suits (and helmets for us bald men) make driving spray
a mere flourish of the seascape, certainly no worse than snow on the
mountain. Nor need board sailing be a solitary pursuit. No-one would do it
for the apres surf, of course. Yet on a fine Saturday morning, the municipal
greensward on Mersea Island's shore is packed with people standing, like
penguins facing the sea, all wondering who will go in first. As in the
mountains, groups form to enjoy the luxury of tired limbs, beer and
exaggeration.
Why then, do not skiers desert the overcrowded alps for the pleasures of the
shore? Partly, no doubt, because the skiing industry has catered so cleverly
for those who dislike the sport, but go for pasteurised Gemutlichkeit and
noise. By contrast, the vigil of the board-widow guarding the Thermos in the
car park is bleak. Then the initial cost can be quite high - perhaps Pounds
1,500 for a complete new set of gear (but less second hand). And a board
sailor capsized half a mile offshore, may admit his sport is rugged.
Whatever the reason, board sailors enjoy one advantage: they escape the
modern skiers' hectic search for new terrain with all the apparatus of
multiple lift passes and linked resorts and ski busses. Unlike the face of a
piste, the sea never looks the same. Its expression is constantly varying
under the influence of wind, tide and clouds. The board sailor close to the
surface feels its subtlest variations. And so it was that on a fine English
morning, with harness hooked on and aft knee flexed, outward bound from
Brightlingsea, I joined the bustling craft at the mouth of the Colne,
squared off for the low shoreline of Mersea Island, glanced at the sky and
thought: 'Gluwein, who needs it.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV Photograph Sailaway, windsurfing as it should be done
(Omitted).
</PAGE>
