<DATE>910504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family: Damaging effect of inflation
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TWO difficulties have regularly faced those planning for pensions
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
inflation and the effect of moving to a new job.
The 1974-79 Labour government introduced the concept of linking the basic
state pension to growth in earnings or prices, whichever was the greater.
However, since the level of basic pension was low in relation to average
earnings, this move would have taken decades to improve the value of the
basic pension compared with price inflation.
However, even this limited improvement was taken away by the Tory government
which increased the basic state pension in line with inflation as measured
by the Retail Price Index - by no means a representative measure of the
effect of inflation on pensioners.
Thus pensioners relying on the state are locked into the standard of living
prevailing in 1982. Progress has been made by governments in ensuring that
company schemes meet the requirements of employees and pensioners.
The government, as an employer, has set the standards required in its public
sector occupational schemes as a model for company schemes in two major
areas - maintaining the value of pensions against inflation and ensuring
that employees who change jobs are treated fairly compared with those who
stay. The latter difficulty has become crucial as job mobility has
increased.
Almost two decades ago, the government ensured that public sector pensions
were automatically increased each year in line with rises in the RPI.
It also ensured that employees who changed jobs within the public sector had
their benefits transferred in full from one scheme to another and employees
who moved into the private sector had their accrued pensions revalued up to
retirement in line with the RPI.
The overall response from the private sector was patchy so that the
government was forced to take legislative action. Twenty years ago, an
employee changing jobs was entitled to no more than a refund of
contributions.
An employee is now entitled to a deferred pension based on his accrued
service and salary at the time of leaving, revalued in line with the RPI, up
to a limit of 5 per cent. Schemes can revalue at a higher rate.
Also, employees can take the cash equivalent of this deferred pension and
transfer it to another company pension scheme or invest with a life company.
Nevertheless, although the differential has narrowed, employees who stay
with an employer until retirement still do better than those who leave
beforehand.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1411</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEEAAAFIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family (Wall Street): A quixotic attempt to
lead by example
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE good news this week was an unexpected cut in US interest rates. The
not-so-good news was the economic background which prompted the move.
On Tuesday, the Federal Reserve took Wall Street by surprise and cut the
discount rate - the rate charged when banks borrow reserves directly from
the central bank - by half a percentage point, to 5.5 per cent.
That cleared the way for it to engineer a quarter point drop in the key
short-term Fed Funds rate, to 5.75 per cent, and for the commercial banks to
drop their prime lending rates by half a point to 8.5 per cent.
All this was welcome news to the equity market, with the Dow Jones
Industrial Average rising 53 points over the two-day rate-cutting period;
and to the White House, as the Bush administration has been repeatedly
calling for an easing of monetary policy to combat the recession. The US
government spent much of last weekend in a quixotic attempt to persuade
other leading industrial nations to co-ordinate a round of rate cuts.
Beneath the market's enthusiasm lay an undercurrent of concern: many
analysts had expected the Fed's monetary stance to remain on hold, while it
weighed up conflicting signs as to where the economy was heading. So what
prompted it to act now?
The answer seems to be concern over recent statistics showing no indication
of a recovery in industrial production and capital goods spending, on top of
weak consumer demand.
The Bush administration and many economists still say they expect a gradual
recovery from around the end of the second quarter. They may be right, but
not so long ago the consensus was that the recession would be short and
shallow, and it is now in its 10th month. At the start of the year, the
White House claimed the worst of the recession was over, yet figures last
week showed that real GNP fell at an annual rate of 2.8 per cent in the
first quarter, compared with 1.6 per cent in final three months of 1990.
There is still little hard evidence to suggest a recovery is just around the
corner. It is true a very modest upturn seems under way in residential real
estate, while the latest Fed survey of regional economic trends said this
week that there were 'some indications that the decline may be bottoming
out'.
Figures yesterday on the April jobs market showed a surprising drop in the
unemployment rate, but government statisticians cautioned against reading
too much into this. A further decline in non-farm employment suggests that
the economy has yet to reach the bottom of the trough.
Nor are there any glimmers of light on the industrial front. John Akers,
chairman of International Business Machines, warned this week that it had
yet to see any evidence of an improving business climate.
Similarly, the Big Three Detroit car makers accompanied dreadful
first-quarter results with some cautious remarks about the outlook for the
year. Both General Motors and Ford forecast a gradual second-half recovery
for the US economy, but this may have been based on hopes following the
economic consensus rather than concrete evidence from dealers' forecourts.
GM suffered a first-quarter net loss of Dollars 1.17bn (Pounds 690m)
(excluding one-off gains), while Ford lost Dollars 884m and Chrysler Dollars
598m. Large losses are also expected in the second quarter. Wall Street does
not expect any second-half recovery to be sufficiently strong to put the Big
Three back in the black for the 1991 financial year.
Of course no recession lasts for ever and sooner or later the optimists  -
most of the economics profession - which has been constantly predicting a
recovery will be proved right, probably some time this summer. The equity
market has been discounting a resurgence of economic activity for so long
now, and shares are sufficiently expensive (on a 17 plus historic
price/earnings ratio) for the dearth of recovery signs to be producing a
little edginess.
This feeling has been underscored by an enthusiastic response by investors
to certain new share issues, notably a listing on the New York Stock
Exchange this week by Duracell International, the battery manufacturer. It
saw its shares surge to a 38 per cent premium in heavy first day trading.
until the economic signals are more positive, there seems little to push the
Dow much above 3,000 again, but equally the 2,850 floor that has stood for
the past 12 weeks seems relatively strong. More sideways crawling may be in
prospect.
 ----------------------------
