<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Share trading compensation row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is pressing the Stock Exchange to raise from Pounds 50m to
Pounds 1bn the proposed compensation ceiling to cover losses by personal
shareholders through the Taurus electronic share settlement system.
The argument has added to the rift between the City and the Department of
Trade and Industry about the development of the long-delayed electronic
system, which will replace share certificates by entries on computers.
The compensation scheme would protect all losses in any one year by private
shareholders in the event of electronic failure, fraud or error.
Mr John Redwood, corporate affairs minister, sees the higher limit as a way
of winning the confidence of individual shareholders in the system.
The DTI is understood to have based its call for compensation of up to
Pounds 1bn on the fact that private individuals own about Pounds 84bn of UK
shares. Once Taurus is fully operational all these shares will be
'dematerialised', or brought into the electronic system.
The DTI said yesterday that its aim was to secure sufficient protection for
investors without adding to their costs. It said it was discussing with the
exchange a level for the compensation scheme which would reflect this
balance.
The exchange has told the DTI that the cost of insurance to cover a Pounds
1bn scheme would add significantly to dealing costs for private investors.
Most of the premiums would fall on private client brokers.
The exchange has also said it could not buy enough insurance to match the
Pounds 1bn ceiling because there was not enough capacity in the market. It
added that such a limit was unnecessary, as tight security and a daily
reconciliation of all shares held in Taurus would make such vast losses
impossible.
With the delays, Taurus, originally planned for October, is unlikely to come
into operation before the summer of 1992 at the earliest.
</TEXT>
