<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: TV companies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's results from Scottish Television did nothing to alter the
market's view that one incumbent bidder at least will be back in the saddle
this autumn. Scottish has a strong balance sheet - net cash currently stands
at Pounds 20m - and the company is better placed than any would-be
competitor to meet the local programming requirements of the Independent
Television Commission. Scottish shares, which advanced another 10p to 645p
on news of maintained profits last year, have surged 20 per cent since March
when the only declared rival pulled out of the race.
Yet investors in all quoted TV companies will need strong nerves. Fact will
replace rumour in a couple of weeks when the ITC publishes a list of formal
franchise contenders for the 15 independent regions, though most of the
uncertainties will remain. Those companies unopposed, or perceived to face
weak opposition, will presumably benefit from a rapid re-rating.
But under the sealed bidding system, successful applicants may end up paying
over the odds. It is impossible at this stage to tell whether the sector's
average multiple - at a 20 per cent discount to the market - is accurately
reflecting the risks.
Franchise winners may struggle to print serious money. Advertising should be
one of the first sectors to see real recovery, which augurs well for profits
over the next two years.
Longer term, however, there is a big question mark over what proportion of
TV advertising revenue will go to the renamed Channel 3 and how much will
leak away to satellite, cable and Channels 4 and 5. The ending of the
takeover moratorium in 1994 - perhaps bringing in a string of bidders from
continental Europe - may not come a minute too soon.
</TEXT>
