<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: UK markets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kinnock doubtless has more faith in the judgment of the local electorate
than he does in stock markets. Yet the sanguine reaction of London shares to
the Tory setback in Thursday's poll is hardly encouraging for the Labour
party.
Either the market still refuses to believe that he can win come the Big Day,
or it is reassured by the thought that any UK government will have to
operate within the constraints of the ERM.
Since a June election is now almost certainly ruled out, and an October poll
increasingly unlikely, the political element is likely to drop out of market
thinking for a while - perhaps until Mr Major's next misfortune revives it.
At some point, the market will want to see improving economic statistics in
the autumn reflected in the Conservatives' opinion-poll rankings.
Without that, the gilt market in particular is likely to start reflecting
that Labour could still devalue inside the ERM; and its PSBR could easily
outstrip even that of a kinder, gentler Toryism.
</TEXT>
