<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: Walking the plank at Allied-Lyons
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,522.7 (-8.0)
Allied-Lyons' remarkable letter to shareholders shows why the company was
initially so unwilling to elaborate the bare facts of its foreign exchange
fiasco. It is now apparent this was the corporate equivalent of the
Hammersmith and Fulham swaps debacle. Such has been the damage to Allied's
reputation that it clearly had no alternative to telling all and
re-shuffling the board.
The fact that an internal inquiry in the summer of last year failed to spot
any irregularities is the best measure of the inadequacy of its financial
controls. Small wonder the chairman and chief executive felt it appropriate
to step aside. One could ask what took them so long.
In coming so clean, Allied may have been too frank for its own good: the
immediate challenge will be to knock takeover speculation on its head.
That aside - and it might have been more quickly achieved by bringing in an
outsider or two - the biggest strategic question mark hangs over the group's
brewing operations.
Commercial logic says Allied should dispose of its brewing assets and
concentrate on exploiting its retailing muscle. The new management team,
with its retailing background, might be so inclined. The problem is that if
it waits too long, the breweries will fetch much less than today's value of
up to Pounds 400m.
The other nettle is already giving rival Bass plenty of pain. Allied must
find a solution to the inefficiencies of its clutch of regionally managed
brands. The recent failure to pull off this trick in the catering division
is a measure of the challenge.
The real irony of the last few months is that Allied's shares are better
under-pinned than at any time since Hoylake bid for BAT in July two years
ago. It remains to be seen what Allied will do by way of a dividend policy,
but profits should bounce towards Pounds 700m in 1992, which puts the shares
on a reasonable prospective rating of around 12. Investors who think the new
management will pass its test might see this as a good time to jump aboard;
for if it fails, the rewards could be even greater.
</TEXT>
