<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / US jobless fall fuels recovery hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN UNEXPECTED fall in US unemployment last month, the first since June,
fuelled speculation yesterday that the US recession might be easing.
The dollar rallied strongly on the news, rising 3 1/2 pfennigs to DM1.7465
at midday and closing at DM1.7495. Bond prices fell sharply as analysts
discounted the prospect of further monetary easing.
The unemployment rate fell to 6.6 per cent, compared with 6.8 per cent in
March. However, the decline largely reflected a rise in self-employment and
an increase in government jobs. Non-farm payroll employment continued to
fall, although at only half the rate of the previous three months.
The better figures surprised markets following the Federal Reserve's
decision to cut the discount rate by half a percentage point on Tuesday. The
Fed, which had been under strong White House pressure to cut rates, usually
eases in anticipation of economic weakness.
Ms Janet Norwood, the head of the Bureau for Labour Statistics, cautioned
that the unemployment figures were based on volatile household survey data.
It would take more than a single month's decline in the jobless rate to set
a clear new trend.
The fall follows two large consecutive monthly increases in the unemployment
rate, which remains more than a point higher than at the start of the
recession last July.
After seasonal adjustment, non-farm employment - seen as a more reliable
guide to labour market trends - fell by 125,000 last month to 109.1m. This
was a smaller decline than expected, but from a lower base. Employment
figures for March were revised substantially - to show a fall of 240,000,
compared with a previously estimated fall of 205,000. About 1.6m jobs (1 1/2
per cent of the total) have been lost since last summer.
Manufacturing employment fell by 40,000 last month to 18.3m - about a third
of the average monthly loss since late autumn. Job losses were also less
widespread.
Mr Richard Berner, senior economist at Salomon Brothers, the New York
securities firm, said the figures indicated that 'the economy was groping
for a bottom'.
Editorial comment, Page 8
</TEXT>
