<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / International Company News: Mitsubishi in Netherlands
carmaking deal with Volvo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL and KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE HAGUE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MITSUBISHI Motors, a leading Japanese car maker, has signed a letter of
intent to begin car production in the Netherlands, in a joint venture with
Volvo of Sweden and the Dutch government.
It is to buy a 33.3 per cent stake in Volvo Car BV, Volvo's Dutch affiliate,
from the Dutch government, giving the Japanese company its first production
facility in Europe and making it an equal partner in the venture with Volvo
of Sweden. Volvo Car BV, which currently produces the Volvo 400 series, is
presently owned 30 per cent by Volvo of Sweden and 70 per cent by Dutch
state interests.
The long-awaited move by Mitsubishi Motors to establish a European car
production base will add significantly to the growing Japanese car assembly
presence in Europe. Nissan, Toyota and Honda are developing car plants in
the UK, and Suzuki is to begin car assembly in Hungary.
The three partners - the Dutch government, Mitsubishi and Volvo - plan to
pump more than Fl 2.1bn (Dollars 1.1bn) into Volvo Car BV to modernise its
production lines and to enable it to manufacture a new medium-sized 1.6-2.0
litre car with production beginning in 1995-96. New production capacity will
total 200,000 cars a year shared equally between Volvo and Mitsubishi.
According to Dutch officials, the new cars will be based on a common
'platform' or chassis with separate Volvo and Mitsubishi body styles and
each marketed through the companies' own distribution systems.
The letter of intent was signed yesterday in The Hague. A definitive deal is
expected in September. Under the agreement, the Dutch state will reduce its
70 per cent stake in Volvo Car to one-third by selling a 33.3 per cent
holding to Mitsubishi. It will also sell a 3.3 per cent holding to Volvo,
which already owns 30 per cent of the company.
The transaction will raise a total of Fl 240m (Dollars 123m) for the Dutch
state. Each of the three partners will invest Fl 700m in Volvo Car in the
form of interest-free subordinated loans. On top of this Fl 2.1bn capital
injection, the company will also borrow Fl 500m from banks to finance its
expansion.
Mr Koos Andriessen, the Dutch minister of economic affairs, said the
agreement granted the Dutch state a 'put option' for selling off its
remaining 33 per cent in Volvo Car in the second half of the 1990s. Volvo of
Sweden and Mitsubishi would each buy exactly half of the state's remaining
shares, making Volvo Car BV a 50/50 joint venture.
Mr Andriessen said Volvo Car, the Netherlands' sole automobile production
company, was too small in its present form to ensure its long-term survival.
'If this hadn't happened, I would have had to fear for the future of the
whole company,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1430</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEEAAAEZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / International Company News: American buys TWA UK routes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JETS belonging to American Airlines, the large US carrier, will start flying
out of London's Heathrow airport on July 1, after last-ditch opposition to
its London route sale deal with Trans World Airlines, the heavily-indebted
carrier, proved ineffective yesterday.
American won approval last month from the US Department of Transportation
for the purchase of TWA's three main London routes, although TWA was not
permitted to sell American three less significant routes.
Late on Thursday night, the Texas-based carrier also sealed an agreement
with Mr Icahn, TWA's owner, over the purchase price and closed the deal
yesterday. It will pay Dollars 445m for the three routes - the price it had
originally proposed for the six-route sale. Mr Icahn appears to have had the
whip-hand in the latest round of negotiations, with American anxious to gain
entry into Heathrow by the peak summer season and to shut out any rival
deal.
The remaining obstacle to the TWA-American transaction came from TWA unions,
together with the City of St Louis, the carrier's main operating base. These
parties asked the aviation authorities to delay the route transfer until the
courts could hear an appeal against the DoT decision. Yesterday afternoon,
however, the Transportation Department denied the motion.
TWA, meanwhile, has yet to reach agreement with some of its noteholders,
having missed certain interest payments two months ago. The noteholders have
a right to repossess at least 10 aircraft and some additional jet engines as
a result of the default.
Mr Icahn said he would be meeting unions, St Louis representatives, and
debtholders in 'the next several days to discuss TWA's future'.
</TEXT>
