<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Letter: Taxing property by value
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From M J PRITCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I wonder why the government decided to apply bands of taxation
according to value of property. The added burden placed upon those living in
the south-east is self evident and any system related to values will, by
definition, involve the expense of valuation. A far more equitable
refinement of the system would have been to create banding by property type,
eg terraced house with two bedrooms, moving up to terraced house with three
bedrooms; semi-detached house with three bedrooms and so on. The implication
seems to be that those in the south-east pay more for their homes because
they can afford to, whereas in reality I wonder whether expendable income,
having been saddled with the high cost of a house in the south east, is any
higher than that of the north. I am no expert in these matters but I very
much doubt whether southerners have the expendable income of those in the
north.
M J Pritchard,
managing director,
Commercial Relocation Consultants
PO Box 230
Beaconsfield,
Buckinghamshire
</TEXT>
