FT  04 MAY 91 / Letter: Marks and Spencer and a question of philosophy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr A L DOWDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The reasons given in your article ('Marks and Spencer adopts a harsh
diet', April 30) for the 850 job losses in Marks and Spencer were sadly
unconvincing.
With the advantages of customer and employee loyalty, huge investment in
information technology and low payroll costs as a percentage of sales
revenue, it is not at all surprising to learn that profits will be up on
last year despite trouble in the High Street elsewhere. What is surprising
is that the cuts should be explained by lame statements about industrial
trends and lack of immunity from recession. Such words cut no ice.
The fact is that these are policy cuts called for by the new hard man at the
top and designed to reposition the company as an employer and with the cuts
go the career hopes of hundreds of bright young graduates, each courted by
the company and attracted by its universal reputation as an employer, many
with several years service backed by further training and periodic
assessment. To move the goalposts at this stage of their careers is callous
enough: to refer to them in as 'a lot of dead wood which is now being thrown
overboard' is unforgivable.
How sad that the new chairman has departed so savagely from the philosophy
of his illustrious predecessor. In 'Don't Ask the Price', Lord Sieff wrote
that 'the improvement of good relations in the working place' was one of
three things he would continue to strive for in the September of his life.
The April of Mr Greenbury's chairmanship may well become the winter of
discontent for the erstwhile flagship of the retail sector.
A L Dowding,
Radley College,
Abingdon,
Oxon OX14 2HR
</TEXT>
