<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Everything is still to play for: Winners and losers in the
council elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is some weeks since anyone seriously thought John Major would call a June
election. But that assumption was turned into a certainty by Thursday's
voting. The 6 per cent swing from Conservative to Labour would, if repeated
in a general election, be more than enough to eliminate the Conservatives'
clear majority even though it would not put Labour in full power: it would
get just over 300 seats, a shade ahead of the Conservatives but below the
magic 326 needed for an absolute majority.
However, the shock of the night was the Liberal Democrats' performance.
Everyone, Mr Paddy Ashdown included, expected them to fall away from their
1987 peak. In fact, they not only gained seats but gained more than Labour.
Even though they lost votes in most of the areas where they were a poor
third, they advanced wherever they were the main challenger. Their share of
the overall vote was near their 1987 general election level - and 8 points
above the current opinion poll rating.
It was a three-cornered fight. The Independents continued their long, slow
decline: the Greens elected only nine of their 1,300 candidates; Plaid Cymru
won 36 and lost 14 seats; and a few Ratepayers cocked a successful snook at
the party system.
There are several ways in which the results can be judged:
council seats gained or lost;
changes in party shares of the vote;
councils controlled by each party;
the outcome in marginal constituencies if this had been a general election.
The seats fought on Thursday were last contested in 1987 when the polls
showed Conservatives at 41 per cent, Labour at 31 per cent and the Alliance
at 27 per cent. Yesterday, an Evening Standard poll of polls found
Conservatives and Labour at 41 per cent each, and Liberal Democrats at 14
per cent. The result in seats does not quite match that trend.
The Conservatives' loss was greater than in any year since the Second World
War. But Labour's gains, though impressive, did not justify the triumphalism
expressed by the party leadership yesterday.
The May 1987 votes can be contrasted with an estimate of those recorded on
Thursday (see the accompanying table on share of votes). These figures are
based on a limited sample and are somewhat at variance with Labour's
optimistic calculations from its selection of marginals. When the final
figures become available in the next week, we shall know where the truth
lies.
Labour made an appreciable advance in control of local councils. With
remarkable victories in the long-term Tory strongholds of Blackpool and
Plymouth, as well as in the more volatile Nottingham, Darlington and Luton,
the party controls every large city in England and Wales, except Derby
(where there is a tie), Bournemouth and Portsmouth. Mr Heseltine may find
local government even less co-operative after this week. The Liberal
Democrats' achievement in adding to its local power base was notable. On
Wednesday they had clear control of only three of the 369 councils that went
to the polls. Today they have an absolute majority in 20, including such
Tory resorts as Cheltenham, Torbay, Poole and Eastbourne. They lost the
balance of power in a dozen councils; they gained it in 30 others.
The voters showed some discrimination, for example, in ousting the
Conservatives in Blackpool, or the Labour party in Barrow and Wear Valley.
But the success of five out of the six Militant rebels in Liverpool should
be recorded.
The swing to Labour was far stronger in the south than elsewhere; it was
notably lower in the Black Country. But even within regions, individual
constituencies produced contrasting results. On Thursday's figures, Labour
would gain Elmet in west Yorkshire (with a swing of 8 1/2 per cent) but
would fail in nearby Keighley (3 per cent swing). Labour would gain the
Basildon constituency (6 per cent swing) although it lost control of the
Basildon council. There were swings to the Conservatives in Wallasey (+2 1/2
per cent) and Birmingham Northfield (+4 per cent), and the Liberal Democrats
would win Hazel Grove (on a 10 per cent swing from the Conservatives) and
defeat Chris Patten in Bath on a 2 per cent swing.
Past years offer ample warning against projecting Thursday's votes, national
or locally, on to what may happen in a general election in October or next
June. Harold Wilson, for one, was lured by the local results of May 1970
into the disaster of June 1970.
Liberals seem to fare better at the council than at the parliamentary level.
And the poll tax and health fiascos may not favour Labour so much six months
or a year hence.
Thursday's votes gave substantial pleasure to Labour and perhaps even more
to the Liberal Democrats. The Conservatives had little to be pleased about.
But there is still everything to play for in the months ahead.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
