<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Leading Article: The aftermath of the G7
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SHOULD COUNTRIES pursue 'low inflationary' or 'non-inflationary' growth?
That was the question for debate during this week's meeting of finance
ministers and central bank governors of the seven largest industrial
countries in Washington. 'Low inflationary growth,' said the US;
'non-inflationary growth,' said the Germans, with conviction, and the
British with exaggerated piety. The result was predictable: the countries
agreed to differ. But even though the rest of the G7 did not accede to
American pressure at the time, the US is likely to get the interest rate
cuts it wants.
The US administration may have failed to convince the G7 that the world is
on the verge of a global slump, but it did persuade the Federal Reserve to
cut the discount rate by half a percentage point to 5 1/2 per cent last
Tuesday, for the third time since December. Whether the Federal Reserve was
wise to yield to the pressure is another matter, especially given the long
lags associated with changes in interest rates.
The US economy is undoubtedly in a troubling recession with manufacturing
orders and retail sales depressed. But spring has brought faint signs of
recovery. Modest increases in consumer spending and new house sales, a rise
in the purchasing managers index, and yesterday's news of a smaller than
expected fall in employment in April, suggest that the worst may be over.
The risk for the US over the coming year is that 'high inflationary' rather
than 'low inflationary' growth will be the consequence of last week's
wrangling. Mr Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, gives the
appearance of having caved in under political pressure. Even if the cut was
justified on economic grounds, its timing does not add to the credibility of
the Federal Reserve - and in central banking appearances matter quite as
much as reality.
Bonn's resistance
Germany's refusal to cave in to pressure for lower interest rates may,
paradoxically, bring future cuts in German rates forward. At least the rally
of the D-Mark against the dollar, which followed the cut in US interest
rates cut, removed any remaining risk of a further rise in German rates at
last Thursday's meeting of the Bundesbank's council. Merely maintaining the
current tight monetary policy in Germany should be sufficient to persuade
wage bargainers of the Bundesbank's view that high wage claims will raise
unemployment. Similarly the Bank of Japan may be happier to cut Japanese
interest rates sooner rather than later, now that it will no longer give the
appearance of responding to external pressure.
France, Italy and the UK may also be able to cut interest rates further over
the coming months. Until recently the strength of the D-Mark in the exchange
rate system, combined with the general unwillingness to countenance a
realignment within the ERM, made such cuts difficult. Since the risk of a
further rise in German interest rates is declining, while the D-Mark remains
weak, further interest rate cuts are now feasible.
UK caution
Whether such cuts would be desirable is another question. The UK at least
must be cautious. While headline retail price inflation is set to fall
sharply over the coming months, underlying inflation appears stuck at over 7
per cent, while pay settlements show no signs of significant declines,
despite rapidly rising unemployment.
Clear signs that underlying inflation is falling are a precondition for
significant further cuts in interest rates. As in the US, there is a danger
that further cuts in interest rates now risk a bout of inflationary growth
next year.
The difference between 'low' and 'non-inflationary' growth must seem
academic to Conservative backbenchers, now analysing the impact of the
Conservatives' miserable performance in Thursday's local elections upon
their electoral prospects. Despite Mr Norman Lamont's optimistic predictions
that recovery is just round the corner, the UK economy still shows no growth
to speak of, but plenty of inflation.
The fancy of a June election must now have vanished from the prime
minister's mind. But economic recovery needs to begin this year if the
Tories are to have a good chance of forming the next government.
The rise in business confidence indicated in the latest Confederation of
British Industry Quarterly Survey suggests that a recovery of some kind may
materialise. However, the recession has already proved very damaging: the
survey also shows that companies are planning further cuts in spending on
capital investment and on product and process innovation over the coming
year.
Mr Lamont held out for non-inflationary growth in Washington. Yet he will be
fortunate to deliver much in the way of growth before the election, let
alone growth without inflation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
