FT  04 MAY 91 / British Gas workers reject strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BLUE-COLLAR workers at British Gas have voted overwhelmingly to reject
strike action over a 9.5 per cent pay offer, says the GMB general union, the
main union representing the 27,500 craft and manual workers.
Official ballot figures will not be announced until Tuesday but the GMB said
it was clear from a preliminary count that there would not now be industrial
action.
Unions are likely to accept the pay offer but could still decide to pursue a
claim for a shorter working week and consolidation of bonus payments.
GMB and TGWU general union leaders had previously warned of 'potentially
damaging industrial conflict'.
The threat of a strike at National Westminster Bank was also withdrawn
yesterday in spite of a narrow vote in favour of industrial action by
members of the banking union Bifu. The ballot result, described by the union
as 'non-viable', was on the basis of a low turnout.
NatWest told its 80,000 UK staff last month that it was imposing a 7.5 per
cent pay rise and introducing more flexible working hours.
