<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Labour flirts with reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S coy flirtation with electoral reform made a fleeting appearance at
the party's triumphant post-elections press conference yesterday amid fresh
speculation that it may have a walk-on part in the coming general election.
Mr Jack Cunningham, Lab-our campaigns co-ordinator, who is known to favour
reform, dismissed the suggestion that the party might hint at support for a
new voting system for the Commons before a general election is called. He
agreed it was an important issue. 'To say it is just mutterings and going to
go away . . . neither is true,' he said. 'It is much more important than
mutterings on the side.'
Mr Bryan Gould, the environment spokesman, said that only the Tories
indulged in the 'short-term opportunism and cynicism' of shifting policies
to gain electoral advantage.
Such a comment from one who is sceptical of the benefits of proportional
representation appeared to confirm the view among some Labour supporters
that electoral advantage could be gleaned from dangling the PR carrot.
At present, a Labour working party is examining all the electoral options
for the European parliament, the Commons and the proposed assemblies for
Scotland, Wales, and the English regions. The exercise was agreed at the
last party conference after delegates threw out a proposal by the National
Executive to confine its studies to systems for the Euro-elections and
planned assemblies. A preliminary report is due in the summer.
Opponents of change say adopting reform would show a potentially damaging
and defeatist lack of faith in the party's capacity to win a clear majority
in Westminster. Mr Roy Hattersley, the party deputy leader, also argues that
abandoning first-past-the-post voting for the Commons would condemn Labour
to coalition government.
Yet some Labour PR supporters believe that the possibility of electoral
reform should be mooted in the manifesto. That, they argue, would be
attractive to its proponents and might undermine the Liberal Democrat vote.
Ten years ago the subject was ideologically unacceptable. Now, it is the
centre of a vigorous debate, with many left-wing factions urging outright
backing for change. This week the Labour Co-ordinating Committee, a
soft-left lobby group that often enjoys the tacit blessing of the Walworth
Road leadership, came out openly for a new voting system for the lower
house.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1440</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEEAAAEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Targeting tactic rewards Democrats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT HAS long been an article of the third party's faith that it invariably
does better in local elections than its standing in national opinion polls
suggests. Even so, Thursday's results were well beyond the Liberal
Democrats' expectations.
The party made unprecedented net gains of more than 500 seats, and not only
kept control in their three councils, but won control of 17 others.
Their victories came mostly from councils in the south and south-west such
as Gosport in Hampshire, which had been under no overall control.
Even so, six - including Lewes in East Sussex, Newbury in Berkshire, and
Poole in Dorset - passed straight from the Tories. There were also more than
14 councils where the Liberal Democrats became the largest single party.
The party's claim that 'Labour is not immune' from their advance was not,
however, substantially borne out by the results. The Liberal Democrats
gained only one council from Labour - Wear Valley in Durham - and in none of
those where they became the largest party did they take that position from
Labour.
The Liberal Democrat campaign worked, party strategists believe, because it
concentrated on key areas where the party has a base both in terms of local
councils and in the challenge for the parliamentary constituency.
Such a targeted approach meant good use of resources where it counted.
Losses in areas where the party has been traditionally weak, as in some
metropolitan councils, were more than offset by gains that tipped the
balance of power.
Apart from the targeting, which will also be a feature of the general
election campaign, the party leadership believes that two other decisions
were crucial to the success.
The first was that Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, should
spend most of the campaign on tour in the target areas. Instead of being
tied to Westminster press conferences that were unlikely to gain extensive
media coverage, he generated local and regional media attention.
Party officials concede that the tactic risked leaving the national campaign
exposed, but say that one of the reasons it worked was the Tories' policy of
not matching Labour's daily press conferences.
The second decision was to differentiate the campaign from that of Labour
and the Tories by concentrating on local issues, and accusing the two main
parties of using the elections as just a dress rehearsal for the general
election.
Officials believe that focusing on local issues rather than the poll tax
meant that the party's campaigning was not knocked off course by the
announcement of a move to the council tax.
Mr Ashdown acknowledged yesterday that the localised campaign might make it
harder for Thursday's gains to be consistently reflected in a general
election.
However, he said Liberal Democrat parliamentary victories, such as those in
his own seat of Yeovil in Somerset and the by-election win at Eastbourne in
East Sussex, often followed local-government successes. The factor that led
Liberal Democrats to do better locally than nationally was diminishing, he
said.
The Tories in particular will be trusting that he may be wrong.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
