<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Imro orders record Pounds 100,000 fine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR investment companies owned by Hill Samuel, part of the TSB Group, have
been fined Pounds 100,000 in the toughest disciplinary action yet taken by
the Investment Management Regulatory Organisation, the investment watchdog.
The four had admitted 13 offences which together reveal a catalogue of
errors or oversight in their administration.
Hill Samuel said that no investors' money had been put at risk and that it
had co-operated fully with the regulatory body to put right any mistakes. It
added that one unnamed manager had been dismissed.
The offences related to the way bank accounts were designated and
reconciled, the handling of complaints, and a failure to provide Imro with
the proper information.
The four companies are: Hill Samuel Private Client Management, Hill Samuel
Unit Trust Managers, Hill Samuel Investment Services and Hill Samuel PEP
Managers. Hill Samuel could not say how many clients they have in all, but
said they have 16,000 PEP holders and Pounds 1bn of unit trusts.
According to Hill Samuel, the offences were 'procedural and reporting'
failures, and did not imply that its administration had broken down. It said
its offences were:
It failed to designate two bank accounts as client accounts, but had set
them up correctly in all other respects. It failed to reconcile the account
of about 160 unit trust investors in savings schemes every six months, as
required.
It failed initially to tell some clients who had complained to it that they
had a right to take their cases to a regulatory body, although it did tell
them later.
It failed to report the departure of a number of fund managers last autumn.
However, the redeployment of four fund managers from another part of the
group meant no client portfolios were left uncovered.
Imro would not comment on the specific offences, but did not disagree with
Hill Samuel's statements.
</TEXT>
