<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Rules on pension fund self-investment eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RULES which would have forced many UK company pension funds to sell property
in a depressed market have been relaxed by the Department of Social
Security.
The DSS has also relaxed rules which will force some funds to sell Unlisted
Securities Market shares, in recognition of the thin trading in many USM
companies.
The changes came to light as Mr Tony Newton, secretary of state for social
security, announced government regulations on self-investment by pension
funds.
In response to a written parliamentary answer, Mr Newton said the proportion
of a scheme's resources that could be self-invested would be limited to 5
per cent, confirming a 1988 proposal by the Occupational Pensions Board.
The principle of limiting self-investment was set out in the 1990 Social
Security Act, with the precise level left to be fixed by regulation. The act
defines self-investment as including any shares in or loans to a scheme's
employing company, as well as any property leased to the company.
Mr Newton also announced rules for disinvestment by schemes which are
already over the 5 per cent threshold. Contrary to the fears of the pensions
industry, he said disinvestment would be restricted to certain types of
investments: listed and USM shares and loans.
The National Association of Pension Funds welcomed the fact that companies
would not need to sell property investments over the 5 per cent limit, as
this could have been disastrous in a weak property market. It also welcomed
a five-year transition period for schemes to sell USM shares. Loans and
listed equities will have to be reduced to below the 5 per cent level within
two years.
Mr Newton's announcement was accompanied by publication of a report
commissioned by the DSS from Ernst &amp; Young, the accountancy firm, into the
extent of the self-investment by UK pension schemes.
Ernst &amp; Young reported that, of 6,500 large company schemes, 300 to 500 were
above the 5 per cent level. Of these, 150-200 had more than 10 per cent of
their assets self-invested. It added that forced rapid divestment could
cause significant problems, particularly for property.
Study of Self-Investment by Pension Funds. HMSO. Pounds 5.80.
</TEXT>
