<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Revival of HK special share plan thwarted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR official in the Hong Kong stock exchange has been thwarted in his
bid to reintroduce special share allocations to members of the exchange's
ruling council. His attempt has renewed concerns about the credibility of
the colony's financial markets.
Mr Philip Wong, senior vice chairman and tipped to become chairman in
October, last week asked the council to recognise the preferential
allocation of shares to council members and to call an extraordinary general
meeting to authorise the practice for future listings in Hong Kong. Both
proposals were passed at a hastily convened council meeting by 10 votes to
five.
The practice, widely seen as open to abuse, was stopped in 1988 following
the arrest of Mr Ronald Li, former chairman, and six other former stock
exchange officials on bribery charges. Mr Li was jailed for four years last
October and faces a second trial with the others later this year for
accepting preferential share allocations in 1987.
The Securities and Futures Commission, alarmed by Mr Wong's proposal,
intervened with the help of Sir QW Lee, exchange chairman, who had been
absent from the meeting. At a second meeting on Thursday the proposals were
overturned by 11 votes to five.
One member who voted against the proposals said they were potentially very
damaging to Hong Kong's image as a financial centre. He said their adoption
would undermine the improvements to Hong Kong's reputation made since the
arrest and conviction of Mr Li.
'The council is the ultimate arbiter of listings. Giving council members
special privileges would make their position very difficult,' the member
said.
Mr Wong has also said for the first time that he accepted preferential share
allocations when he was a member of the exchange committee under Mr Li in
1987. In a letter sent to council members dated April 25, he said: 'I took
up allocations of new listings in several companies in the course of that
year, in numbers greater than those allocated to ordinary members.'
Mr Wong said in the letter that he was making his statement because the
government and the SFC were pressing him to resign from the council over the
1987 share allocations. He claimed the practice of accepting shares was well
known at the time and the SFC, which is in conflict with the exchange on
several topics, was using the information to discredit him. He called for
the practice to be renewed to stop his name being blackened.
Mr Wong worked under Mr Li for several years as a computer expert in the
mid-1980s. Since Mr Li's arrest, and with strong backing from local
stockbrokers, he has risen quickly through the exchange ranks. He is thought
to be considering standing for election to the colony's Legislative Council
as candidate of the Peking-backed Chinese Chamber of Commerce, suggesting he
has good links with the mainland.
</TEXT>
