<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Walesa snub for parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND'S President Lech Walesa yesterday snubbed both houses of Parliament
when he failed to attend a ceremonial joint session to commemorate the 200th
anniversary of the country's first modern constitution.
Instead, Mr Walesa went to the Catholic shrine of Czestochowa for
celebrations traditionally held on May 3. He returned to Warsaw at noon to
attend a military parade and wreath-laying ceremony at the tomb of the
Unknown Soldier.
The president failed to attend parliament against the advice of Cardinal
Joseph Glemp, the Polish primate, and Mr Jan Krzysztof Bielecki, the prime
minister.
His gesture clearly signals that he attaches more importance to the church
and the military as sources of support than to Parliament as an institution.
He is particularly concerned to distance himself from this parliament, which
was elected in June 1989 under a deal between Solidarity and the Communist
authorities.
</TEXT>
