<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / East Germans urged to curb pay rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A PANEL of economic experts drawn up by the German government yesterday
issued a strong plea for east German workers to tone down wage rises to help
recovery in the former Communist part of the country.
Prof Karl Schiller, the 80-year-old former economics minister, who yesterday
re-emerged before the press as the chairman of a Strategy Forum on east
Germany, said 'moral suasion' was needed to curb wage rises in the east.
The Forum, set up by Mr Jurgen Mollemann, the economics minister, concluded
at its first meeting yesterday that high wages in the east were contributing
to mass unemployment.
Repeated calls from business and economic leaders for wage moderation have
fallen upon deaf ears in both east and west. Warning strikes in the west
German metalworking industry continued yesterday in pursuit of a 10 per cent
pay claim with 120,000 workers downing tools for short periods.
The stoppages, concentrated in the north and south-west of the country, were
more limited than earlier in the week. But the metalworkers' action was
supplemented by isolated stoppages yesterday in the printing industry, where
workers are stepping up pressure for an 11 per cent pay increase.
Mr Mollemann today meets union leaders in east Germany. He will tell them
the share of wages and salaries in east German gross domestic product - at
60 per cent last year - was much higher than the 45 per cent in west
Germany.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, under pressure from within the Bonn coalition over
his party's waning electoral fortunes, yesterday remained defiant after
cancelling a planned meeting with Bavarian party leaders.
The Bavarian Christian Social Union, which has lately stepped up criticism
of Mr Kohl's Christian Democrats, meanwhile signalled a more conciliatory
tone to limit the damage from the coalition squabble.
</TEXT>
