<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Lib Dem support surgesin first big test for Major
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday sought to shrug off a dismal Conservative
performance in the local elections as the results appeared to leave wide
open the outcome of the general election due by the middle of next year.
In the first widespread test of public opinion since Mr Major became prime
minister, a surge in Liberal Democrat support contributed to Tory net losses
of more than 850 seats and losses of control in more than 40 councils.
Labour demanded an instant general election, claiming that a similar
performance would give it a narrow overall majority in the House of Commons.
Some independent analyses pointed towards a hung parliament.
Mr Chris Patten, the Tory party chairman, confirmed that there would be no
June election, saying he had been 'pouring buckets of cold water on that
particular idea for months now.'
The final results saw Liberal Democrats jubilant at net gains of more than
500 seats, as they added 17 new councils to the three on which they kept
control. They had particular successes in Tory-dominated areas in the south
and south-west.
For the first time since the early 1980s Labour made considerable inroads
into Conservative strongholds in the south, where their gains included
taking control of Plymouth, Luton and Kingswood. They also made gains in key
areas of the midlands and the north-west.
Ministers regard the autumn as the earliest election date and have not ruled
out the long haul to next year.
In a brief exchange with reporters Mr Major described the results as
'disappointing but bearable.' He said that Labour had not done enough to win
an overall majority, adding: 'We are on an upswing and I think they have
peaked.'
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrats' leader, called his party's results
'a stunning achievement'. The Liberal Democrats were the only party on an
upward trend, he said.
He, too, claimed that Labour could not win an overall majority, and
confirmed that the price for his party's support in the event of a hung
parliament would be a clear commitment to legislating for proportional
representation within the lifetime of a parliament.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, said his party's advances in the
'battleground' seats showed it was 'the only party that can, and will, beat
the Conservative government.'
Labour's analysis of the local election results in 87 marginal
constituencies indicated a narrow overall majority of five parliamentary
seats. It showed Labour with a six-point lead over the Tories, on 43 per
cent and 37 per cent respectively. The Liberal Democrats were put at 17 per
cent. Tories took comfort from national opinion polls, showing them
neck-and-neck with Labour. Their analysis of marginal seats showed them just
ahead on 38 per cent to Labour's 37 per cent, with the Liberal Democrats on
20 per cent.
Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, was almost alone in claiming a
'dramatic recovery' in Tory fortunes, but his comments also highlighted the
line the party will emphasise over the summer. 'We all know inflation is
about to come down and interest rates will follow it. If the Labour party
have not made the breakthrough now, there isn't any chance of them making it
when things get better.'
Mr Patten plans to move on to the offensive after this month's Monmouth
by-election, which Tories concede they might lose. With the May retail price
index set to show a drop of two points in the inflation rate, the Tories
believe that improving economic circumstances will allow them to re-gain the
political initiative.
 -----------------------------------------------------------
            SEATS GAINED AND LOST
 -----------------------------------------------------------
