<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Allied-Lyons shake-upreceives cautious welcome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WIDE-RANGING management changes at Allied-Lyons, the UK drinks and food
group, yesterday received a cautious welcome in the City.
The moves, involving the early departure of the chairman and chief
executive, came in an effort to repair damage to investor confidence caused
by losses of Pounds 147m on the group's foreign exchange trading.
Analysts suggested, however, that the shake-up may not be enough to ease
concern entirely or to damp speculation about a takeover bid. One analyst
said the changes were 'the least that could be done'.
There has been heavy trading in Allied's shares in the past week amid
rumours of possible predators for the Pounds 4bn group. The shares dropped
9p to 552p yesterday but were still 32p up on the week.
Leading the changes, Sir Derrick Holden-Brown, chairman, has accepted
'ultimate responsibility' for inadequate management controls over the
group's foreign currency dealings and will retire a year early in July. Mr
Richard Martin will give up his post as chief executive.
Mr Michael Jackaman, architect of the group's successful wine and spirits
division, will take over as chairman, and Mr Tony Hales, head of the J Lyons
food division for the past two years, will become chief executive.
Recruitment of a prominent outsider to one of these posts would have
restored confidence more quickly, analysts suggested, although a finance
director will be brought in from outside to succeed Mr Cliff Hatch, who
resigned in March.
There was recognition of Mr Jackaman's achievements in restructuring Hiram
Walker-Allied Vintners, and Mr Hales's refocusing of the group's food
operations. Analysts also welcomed the appointments of Mr David Jarvis, 44,
former Allied Distillers boss and since last year responsible for Far East
and special markets, who will head the food division; and Mr John Giffen,
52, managing director of Hiram Walker-Allied Vintners, who will assume full
responsibility for the wines and spirits division.
Sir Derrick, in a letter to shareholders yesterday, said an investigation
into the losses by KPMG Peat Marwick McLintock, the company's auditor, had
revealed that Allied's treasury had been 'dealing in foreign currency
instruments which were inappropriate, and in which it lacked the requisite
trading skills'.
The scale of the trading, which led to an exposure of Pounds 1.5bn before
NatWest was called in to close positions in March, had been excessive.
Sir Derrick, who was first alerted by the Bank of England to unusual dealing
activity last summer, said an internal investigation then had found no need
for further action. After further warnings, it was discovered that the
group's exposure limit of Pounds 500m had been breached.
Changes in treasury staff and efforts to bring foreign currency exposures
'to more prudent levels' were made. Accrued losses diminished significantly
in February but the position deteriorated again as efforts were made to
trade out of the losses.
Sir Derrick said there was no evidence of dishonest or corrupt practices. It
was 'an isolated occurrence . . . though I do not seek to minimise the
seriousness of the losses incurred'. Foreign exchange trading had now been
restricted to 'the more conventional type of treasury activity'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
</DOC>
