<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / A way of telling tales out of court: A moneymaking
proposition for spreading enlightment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINIC LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I AM TOLD that people read the front half of the Weekend FT to discover
information which could enable them to increase their income, and this end
of the paper merely to be entertained. So I hope I'm not speaking out of
place if I suggest in this column a business proposition which I have long
been convinced would enrich anyone who acted on it.
My suggestion is the mass marketing of reports from the Law Courts in
tabloid form. But, unlike the tabloids themselves, there would be no
comment, bowdlerisation or sensationalisation - subscribers would have the
great satisfaction of knowing that they were actually reading the truth
about acts of corruption, horror and rascality, rather than a figment or
fragment.
It is true that the 'heavy' papers publish unvarnished law reports, but
these are highly selective, often woefully abridged, and, besides, are
buried in an inky morass of other news which no one is really interested in:
such as whether the Kurds' haven is safe enough for John Major to be able to
sleep at night, or the state of Paul Gascoigne's physiognomy, or whether
there will be growth in the spring, or when political journalists think
political pundits think MPs think the prime minister thinks he might hold
the next general election.
This is something which is approximately five stages from reality, and on
which people are apparently prepared to spend good money to read. How much
more potent and commercial is the cold truth of the courtroom.
On Thursday alone, for example, there was a spate of abridged reports of
different cases spread across the newspapers, which, consolidated into one
tabloid, would provide at least an hour's gripping reading and provoke
thought that would last the rest of the day.
I have space for only two here. First, in Thursday's Daily Telegraph there
is Ravenscroft v Rederiaktiebologet Transatlantic, in which the mother of an
employee crushed by a runaway forklift truck was awarded Pounds 16,500
damages for 'remote shock,' although she did not see the accident, was not
present at her son's death in hospital, and did not see his body immediately
afterwards. But two psychiatrists agreed that she was suffering 'a prolonged
grief reaction as defined by the International Classification of Disease
Code 309.1 (HMSO 9241540044 and 9241540052). All very interesting in the
light of yesterday's decision by the courts in Liverpool not to award
similar damages to the parents of those crushed to death in the Sheffield
football ground tragedy, even those parents who witnessed the horror live on
television.
Second, this from Thursday's Independent, detailing the case of C in the
Chancery Division (Court of Protection): the court, in the form of that most
amiable and sensible of judges, Lennie Hoffmann, decided to make a will and
dispose immediately of large chunks of C's considerable fortune, to hospital
authorities and relatives, because C, now 75, was born with such mental
retardation that, the court decided, she had 'lacked testamentary capacity
since birth.' The report stated that 'immediate gifts of Pounds 100,000 to
the friends of the hospital and Pounds 400,000 to family were ordered.'
Very nice, too. I couldn't help wondering, though, whether C's family had
any role in the development of the case. And I noticed that the wealthy Miss
C has been a long-term patient in a National Health Service hospital. And
since Miss C's pre-mortem bequests were made by order of the court on the
basis of what she would have wanted, had her mind been normal, whether it
might not also have considered that C would have wanted instead to spend her
own money on her own comfort in a luxurious private hospital. Miss C was
described as 'enjoying music, the sound of birds, the smell of flowers.' Mr
Justice Hoffmann should at least have ensured that a world-renowned string
quartet be paid top dollar to come and play at her bedside every Saturday
night.
Now, imagine cases like these distributed through your letter-box daily,
with no editorial and no advertisements. It is the business opportunity of a
lifetime; but to anyone who exploits the idea from this copyrighted column,
and fails to pay me commission, I have a message: see you in court, and read
all about it.
Dominic Lawson is Editor of The Spectator.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
