<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Arts: Last of 'Russian Spring'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLEMENTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOUTH Bank's celebration of Russian culture came to its end of Thursday,
when Kent Nagano conducted the London Philharmonic in a neglected
masterpiece by the greatest of all Russian composers. After all the
stylistic excursions of these concerts it was salutary to be returned to the
chaste neoclassical beauty of Stravinsky's Persephone, the 1934 'melodrama
in three acts' to a text by Andre Gide, especially in such a beautifully
prepared account as this, with the tenor Anthony Rolfe Johnson and narrator
Anne Fournet.
Yet the last week of the series had been dominated by a much less familiar
name. Nikolay Roslavets, born in 1881, was the leading avant-garde figure in
Soviet music in the 1920s; he had trained at the Moscow Conservatory,
followed much the same stylistic course through Rimsky-Korskaov and French
impressionism as the slightly younger Stravinsky. During the First World
War, however, Roslavets's style suddenly became much more radical; he
developed a system of harmonic organisation, and is credited with inventing
his own version of 12-note composition quite independently of Schoenberg,
whose music he seems not to have heard until 1923.
After the 1917 revolution he gladly put his music at the service of the new
state, believing, like so many poets and visual artists, that a new social
order automatically implied a revolutionary approach to the arts. He was
briefly head of a conservatory and edited a music journal, but inevitably in
the 1920s he began to fall foul of the Stalinist machine; his music was
condemned for its 'bourgeois ideology', and though Roslavets defended
himself in polemical style, his music was totally proscribed after 1930, and
his name expunged from all Soviet reference books.
He died in Moscow in 1944 and his music has remained just a footnote in the
histories of 20th-century music. But the centenary of his birth a decade ago
renewed interest in his achievement, and under glasnost his rehabilitation
has gathered momentum. The 'Russian Spring' series uncovered four pieces:
last week Ashkenazy and the Philharmonia brought the Violin Concerto of
1925, with Tatyana Grindenko as soloist; on Wednesday the Arditti Quartet's
Soviet programme included the British premieres of Roslavets's Music for
string quartet and his Third String Quartet, while Nagano began his concert
on Thursday with the first performance in Britain of the unfinished tone
poem from 1910, Aux Heures de la nouvelle lune.
Such stories deserves to have happy endings, and it would be wonderful to
greet Roslavets as a distinctive and significant voice, set to alter our
view of Russian music in the 20th century. But while Roslavets's historical
significance is undeniable his intrinsic musical worth, on the basis of the
works heard in London, seems uncertain. The confident French accents of the
tone poem, full of glittering orchestration a la Dukas and Ravel, show the
young composer as a prodigious talent who might well have flourished had he
followed Stravinsky and Prokofiev into exile during the Revolution. But the
technique that Roslavets thrashed out for himself during the years when
Russia tore itself apart and writing music must seemed the most irrevelent
of occupations, is so contrived that the instinctive early flair appears to
have been suffocated. The string quartets are busy with notes yet short on
rigour and ideas, while the Violin Concerto, composed in an elaborate
12-note technique at the height of his influence, still reeks of Skryabin
and uses repetitive, sequential gestures to over-stretch its thin material
and tie itself in structural knots.
Yet the re-emergence of a genuine radical voice from the early, untarnished
years of the Soviet Union must have strengthened the resolve of the
present-day musical radicals. As recently as 1980, it's worth remembering,
Edison Denisov and Sofia Gubaydulina were condemned by the chairman of the
Soviet Composers' Union. Now, though, visiting Russian orchestras bring
Gubaydulina's on tour: on Tuesday the Moscow Radio Symphony Orchestra
included her violin concerto, Offertorium, in the second of its South Bank
concerts.
Offertorium is the most sustained and impressive of Gubaydulina's works I've
heard so far, a fascinating 40-minute contemplation of Bach and Webern that
moves in ever wider sweeps until it flows into a final string chant. The
solo part was written for Gidon Kremer, who brings to it on disc a flair and
intensity that Vladislav Igolinsky just missed in this London premiere. If
the future of Russian music is Gubaydulina and Shnitke, as 'Russian Spring'
has demonstrated so convincingly, its past remains Prokofiev, Stravinsky and
Shostakovich, not Roslavets, however wishfully we might want to rewrite
history.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1478</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BEEAAADNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Arts: Favart the forgotten - Opera-comique rediscoveries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN COMMON parlance the Theatre de l'Opera-Comique is known as the Salle
Favart. The street running adjacent its one side is the Rue Favart. There is
a Hotel Favart across the way from the front entrance. But otherwise Charles
Simon Favart (1710-92), librettist and playwright, is a forgotten figure;
the founding role he played in the development of the French popular
operatic style will be unknown to all except the most assiduous of opera
students.
The programme of two small-scale operas on Favart librettos - 'Hommage a
Favart' - that has been mounted at the Opera-Comique was no doubt devised
with some such enlightening purpose in mind. Happily, it proves not at all
dusty exercise in music-historical revival but one of the most delightful -
and surprising - evenings of light entertainment I've spent in ages. This
beloved small theatre, scene of many landmark events in French opera, has
recently re-established a firm identity as the proper Paris stage for operas
small, unpretentious, or off the beaten track. The double bill of La Fee
Urgele (text by Favart, music by Duni) and La Repetition interrompue (text
by Favart, songs from popular stock) made an unbeatable case for its
continued existence: would that London possessed, and supported, a Salle
Favart of its own]
Favart's father, a pastrycook, was a devotee of those popular musical works,
descended from the fairground entertainments of the 16th century, in which
speech and song were the modes of delivery. His son was soon pouring out
texts for various outlets; he was to enjoy a long and picaresque career
whose unifying factor was a flair for the genre that was multifarious and
forward-looking.
It was Favart's driving force, his ability to learn good tricks from the
rival Italian troupes who crossed his Paris paths, and his skill in finding
new and enjoyable modes of expression for the perennial themes and
characters of popular opera, that directly encouraged the development of
opera-comique. From the 1750s onward, the use of traditional melodies gave
way to that of newly composed airs, and then to the commissioning of
properly-worked scores; Favart's close collaboration, in the later stages of
his career, with such composers as Monsigny, Philidor and the Vienna-based
Gluck indicates in itself the fascinating way opera-comique came in from the
streets and the fairgrounds without losing its popular character.
The Italian Egidio Duni (1708-75) was another of Favart's regular Paris
collaborators; La Fee Urgele (1765) was one of their biggest successes.
Favart based the libretto on a Voltaire tale: the testing in love of the
knight Robert for Marton, who turns out to be the fairy Urgele, 'protectrice
fidele des chevaliers'. Romantic-pastoral elements (a court of love presided
over by Queen Berthe and her all-female judges) mingle with supernatural,
comic episodes (Robert's unwilling amorous entanglement with an Old Woman,
Marton's servant in disguise) with Rousseau-esque sentiment.
In this first-rate performance, produced by Jean-Marie Villegier in the
enchanting chinoiserie set of Carlo Tommasi, choreographed by Nathalie Van
Parys, and with the orchestra of Les Arts Florissants conducted by
Christophe Rousset, the surprise was the saltiness of the humour, the
crispness of the unfolding, and the wonderfully natural movement between
speech and song. Duni's charming overture, dance movements and succession of
Italianate airs touch no great depths, undergo no Philidor-like adventures
with form; but his melodic fluency and bold sense of colour are gifts by no
means to be scorned, nor is the gentle lyricism which informs the later
passages of Robert's 'trials'.
If there was a fault in Villegier's production, it was perhaps a tendency to
overweight with undue emphasis the sentimental aspects of the work: since
there had already been a lengthy prologue to La Fee d'Urgele' in the form of
the highly amusing Repetition interrompue, and since Act 4 was taken at a
distinctly moderate pace, the sum total was a rather long sit.
But the expertise of the participants was almost always compensation. On
this evidence, the number of young French singers who can use their voices
with sweetness and elegance, who can speak, move and dance with easy
elegance and command of 18th-century deportment is now enviably large: the
sopranos Miriam Ruggeri (a deliciously funny Old Woman) and Monique Zanetti,
the tenor Pierre Catala (handsome, witty, and exceptionally musical) and the
baritone Jean-Francois Gardeil were only the most prominent of an expert
cast, which also included our own Jennifer Smith, that most multilingual of
British singers, in sparkling form.
This was one of those evenings when a whole neglected area of opera seemed
to spring to new life: I hope there will be many more such opera-comique
rediscoveries from Villegier and his Arts Florissants colleagues.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
